1
00:00:12,888 --> 00:00:15,390
♪♪

2
00:01:19,746 --> 00:01:21,873
♪♪

3
00:02:09,504 --> 00:02:11,673
♪♪

4
00:02:23,602 --> 00:02:25,395
Either the shell-pink
gossamer muslin

5
00:02:25,562 --> 00:02:26,647
or the figured damask

6
00:02:26,813 --> 00:02:29,941
would be most becoming
to your daughter, Mrs. Bennet.

7
00:02:30,108 --> 00:02:31,902
Eh, now, let me see.

8
00:02:32,819 --> 00:02:35,739
Yes. Yes, the pink suits you, Jane.

9
00:02:36,239 --> 00:02:37,282
And now we'll see whether the blue

10
00:02:37,449 --> 00:02:38,825
is becoming to you, Lizzy.

11
00:02:38,992 --> 00:02:39,951
Stand up, dear.

12
00:02:40,327 --> 00:02:43,664
Several young ladies have bought
new gowns for the Assembly Ball,

13
00:02:43,830 --> 00:02:47,084
but none will be more modish
than this muslin, madam.

14
00:02:47,334 --> 00:02:49,211
Isn't silk brocade
being very much worn?

15
00:02:50,087 --> 00:02:52,255
Mine is, Mama.
It's been worn for three years.

16
00:02:53,757 --> 00:02:56,635
Um, fashion decrees muslin
this season, madam.

17
00:02:56,885 --> 00:02:58,595
That should be good enough for us,
shouldn't it, Jane?

18
00:02:58,762 --> 00:02:59,554
Yes.

19
00:02:59,888 --> 00:03:02,683
Then, uh, pink for Miss Jane
and blue for Miss Elizabeth.

20
00:03:03,016 --> 00:03:05,143
I know exactly how I want mine cut.

21
00:03:05,394 --> 00:03:07,270
I shall look very worldly.

22
00:03:08,188 --> 00:03:09,189
How shall I look?

23
00:03:09,898 --> 00:03:11,900
Adorable, my love, as always.

24
00:03:12,067 --> 00:03:13,485
- Oh, Lizzy.
- Mm-hm.

25
00:03:13,860 --> 00:03:16,446
Hey, Mr. Beck. Mr. Beck, look.

26
00:03:22,828 --> 00:03:25,122
Looks-a-daisy, what a commotion.

27
00:03:26,748 --> 00:03:29,209
Just look at that carriage, my love,

28
00:03:29,501 --> 00:03:31,753
and those exquisite young men.

29
00:03:32,045 --> 00:03:33,839
They must've come straight from court.

30
00:03:42,139 --> 00:03:43,056
Oh, look, they're getting out.

31
00:03:43,306 --> 00:03:44,975
H-have you heard any
of our neighbors say

32
00:03:45,142 --> 00:03:46,685
if they're expecting visitors?

33
00:03:46,977 --> 00:03:47,978
No, Mama.

34
00:03:48,645 --> 00:03:51,481
Who do you suppose would be entertaining
people of fashion like these?

35
00:03:52,107 --> 00:03:53,900
Mr. Beck, eh, send over to the inn

36
00:03:54,067 --> 00:03:56,111
and find out if they're stopping
in the vicinity.

37
00:03:56,278 --> 00:03:57,571
Eh, slyly, of course.

38
00:03:57,779 --> 00:03:59,740
Oh, the hostler will tell us.

39
00:04:04,244 --> 00:04:05,370
La, here comes Aunt Philips

40
00:04:05,537 --> 00:04:06,747
as if something were after her.

41
00:04:08,248 --> 00:04:11,501
Looks-a-daisy, my sister's lost
all sense of decorum.

42
00:04:11,835 --> 00:04:14,337
Aunt Philips, oh, why such haste?

43
00:04:14,504 --> 00:04:15,630
Oh, you're out of breath.

44
00:04:15,797 --> 00:04:17,591
I saw your carriage outside.

45
00:04:18,008 --> 00:04:21,470
My dear, such news.
Did you see them?

46
00:04:21,636 --> 00:04:23,180
Of course we saw them.
Who are they, sister?

47
00:04:23,346 --> 00:04:25,182
They're the new tenants
of Netherfield Park.

48
00:04:25,348 --> 00:04:27,476
Netherfield Park is let at last.

49
00:04:27,642 --> 00:04:29,269
And to a young man of importance.

50
00:04:29,436 --> 00:04:30,562
His name is Bingley.

51
00:04:31,188 --> 00:04:32,689
Is the young woman Mrs. Bingley?

52
00:04:32,981 --> 00:04:35,233
No, dear.
That's the pleasantest part of It.

53
00:04:35,400 --> 00:04:36,568
She's his sister.

54
00:04:37,903 --> 00:04:38,945
She's his sister, Lizzy.

55
00:04:40,322 --> 00:04:42,032
Who's the other gentleman,
Aunt Philips?

56
00:04:42,324 --> 00:04:44,242
Oh, I don't know.
Some friend, I suppose.

57
00:04:44,409 --> 00:04:46,203
Oh, but let me tell you about
Mr. Bingley.

58
00:04:46,536 --> 00:04:49,831
He's very rich.
He has 5,000 pounds a year.

59
00:04:50,165 --> 00:04:52,125
Five thousand pounds and unmarried.

60
00:04:52,542 --> 00:04:53,960
That's the most heartening piece of news

61
00:04:54,127 --> 00:04:55,378
since the Battle of Waterloo.

62
00:04:56,087 --> 00:04:59,132
You can see how handsome
and elegant he is.

63
00:04:59,299 --> 00:05:00,342
Excuse me, madam,

64
00:05:00,550 --> 00:05:02,385
the second gentleman's name is Darcy.

65
00:05:02,552 --> 00:05:04,596
The two carriages and
the dogs are his.

66
00:05:04,846 --> 00:05:06,765
The chaise belongs to Mr. Bingley.

67
00:05:07,766 --> 00:05:08,934
Two carriages and--

68
00:05:09,392 --> 00:05:10,685
one, two, three, four, five--

69
00:05:11,144 --> 00:05:12,854
six liveried servants.

70
00:05:13,355 --> 00:05:16,358
My word, this Mr. Darcy must also be rich.

71
00:05:17,400 --> 00:05:19,611
I wonder if he's married.

72
00:05:20,362 --> 00:05:21,947
Ah, Mrs. Bennet,

73
00:05:22,322 --> 00:05:24,407
I thought we'd find you here.

74
00:05:25,158 --> 00:05:28,328
Good morning, Mrs. Philips.
Elizabeth, Jane.

75
00:05:28,703 --> 00:05:30,997
I just had to come in
and tell you the news.

76
00:05:31,164 --> 00:05:32,332
Dear Lady Lucas, you don't mean

77
00:05:32,499 --> 00:05:34,626
about, ah, the new tenants
of Netherfield?

78
00:05:34,793 --> 00:05:36,795
Ye--oh, you've heard it already?

79
00:05:36,962 --> 00:05:37,712
Yes, dear.

80
00:05:37,879 --> 00:05:40,757
Mr. Bingley has 5,000 pounds a year.

81
00:05:41,424 --> 00:05:42,843
Who is this Mr. Darcy?

82
00:05:43,134 --> 00:05:44,511
He's Mr. Bingley's guest.

83
00:05:44,803 --> 00:05:46,680
They're inseparable friends.

84
00:05:47,180 --> 00:05:48,682
He's one of the Darcys of Pemberley.

85
00:05:48,849 --> 00:05:50,809
Oh, Mr. Darcy of Pemberley.

86
00:05:51,101 --> 00:05:52,310
Is that all you know about him?

87
00:05:52,561 --> 00:05:54,771
What--? Oh, you mean, is he married?

88
00:05:55,188 --> 00:05:56,898
No, dear.
No, he isn't married.

89
00:05:57,190 --> 00:05:59,442
And he's even richer than Mr. Bingley.

90
00:06:00,193 --> 00:06:03,572
The Pemberley Estates alone are worth
a clear 10,000 a year.

91
00:06:03,738 --> 00:06:04,656
Ten thou--?

92
00:06:05,073 --> 00:06:07,742
Isn't it fortunate
to have two eligible young men

93
00:06:07,909 --> 00:06:08,952
come into the neighborhood?

94
00:06:09,119 --> 00:06:11,454
Perhaps one of them will fall
in love with you, Charlotte.

95
00:06:12,372 --> 00:06:15,000
Oh, not if he sees Jane or Lizzy first.

96
00:06:15,292 --> 00:06:16,835
You may not have beauty, my love,

97
00:06:17,085 --> 00:06:20,213
but you have character,
and some men prefer it.

98
00:06:20,589 --> 00:06:21,882
How true, Lady Lucas.

99
00:06:22,132 --> 00:06:25,135
That's why girls who have both
are doubly fortunate.

100
00:06:25,427 --> 00:06:26,136
Come, my dears.

101
00:06:28,638 --> 00:06:30,724
The dressmaker will call
for the muslin, Mr. Beck.

102
00:06:30,891 --> 00:06:32,058
Why such haste, Mama?

103
00:06:32,225 --> 00:06:32,934
Shh.

104
00:06:33,351 --> 00:06:34,436
Good morning, Lady Lucas.

105
00:06:34,978 --> 00:06:36,187
Oh, good morning, Mrs. Bennet.

106
00:06:36,438 --> 00:06:37,898
We shall meet
at the Assembly Ball, of course.

107
00:06:38,064 --> 00:06:40,025
Yes, indeed.
Goodbye, sister.

108
00:06:40,191 --> 00:06:43,028
Oh, you mustn't leave, Lady Lucas,
till Mr. Beck has shown you

109
00:06:43,194 --> 00:06:45,572
that exquisite piece
of flower damask.

110
00:06:45,739 --> 00:06:46,740
- Goodbye.
- Bye.

111
00:06:46,907 --> 00:06:49,034
- Goodbye, Lady Lucas.
- Goodbye.

112
00:06:49,576 --> 00:06:50,911
Come over to Longbourn soon, Charlotte.

113
00:06:51,077 --> 00:06:52,037
Mama.

114
00:06:52,621 --> 00:06:54,331
Heaven only knows
where your sisters are,

115
00:06:54,497 --> 00:06:55,540
and we must get home at once.

116
00:06:55,707 --> 00:06:56,750
But, Mama, why?

117
00:06:57,250 --> 00:06:59,085
Your father must call
on Mr. Bingley and Mr. Darcy

118
00:06:59,252 --> 00:07:00,253
this very afternoon.

119
00:07:00,587 --> 00:07:02,380
If he doesn't, the Lucases will.

120
00:07:02,631 --> 00:07:03,715
Now, there's no time to be lost.

121
00:07:06,009 --> 00:07:07,677
But the damask, milady.

122
00:07:07,844 --> 00:07:09,846
Oh, we'll choose the material
some other time, Mr. Beck.

123
00:07:10,013 --> 00:07:10,764
Come, Charlotte.

124
00:07:12,933 --> 00:07:14,142
Hurry, my dear.

125
00:07:17,145 --> 00:07:18,271
Where are those girls?

126
00:07:18,438 --> 00:07:20,523
Whenever I want them,
I never can find them.

127
00:07:20,857 --> 00:07:23,526
- There's Mary, Mama.
- Ye--oh, Mary.

128
00:07:23,902 --> 00:07:24,736
Mary!

129
00:07:27,113 --> 00:07:28,782
Isn't that just like the girl.

130
00:07:28,949 --> 00:07:30,075
Eh, eh, Mary.

131
00:07:32,202 --> 00:07:33,036
Mar--

132
00:07:35,455 --> 00:07:36,331
Mary.

133
00:07:38,083 --> 00:07:39,000
Come out.

134
00:07:47,467 --> 00:07:49,886
Look, Mama.
I have just purchased Burke's essay

135
00:07:50,053 --> 00:07:51,429
on the sublime and beautiful.

136
00:07:51,596 --> 00:07:52,639
You and your books.

137
00:07:52,806 --> 00:07:54,891
No wonder you're compelled
to wear disfiguring glasses.

138
00:07:55,475 --> 00:07:57,602
Oh, where are Kitty and Lydia?

139
00:07:58,186 --> 00:07:59,646
Look for an officer in a red coat

140
00:07:59,813 --> 00:08:00,522
and you'll find them.

141
00:08:00,689 --> 00:08:02,691
Y--Officers, yes.
Come, girls.

142
00:08:13,243 --> 00:08:14,035
Oh, yeah?

143
00:08:16,788 --> 00:08:18,623
Is that the way you'd treat a wife,
Mr. Wickham?

144
00:08:18,790 --> 00:08:20,709
More likely to be the way she'd treat me,
Miss Lydia.

145
00:08:21,084 --> 00:08:22,002
Oh, Mama,
there they are.

146
00:08:22,168 --> 00:08:23,420
Where?

147
00:08:24,045 --> 00:08:25,088
There. Look.

148
00:08:26,256 --> 00:08:27,674
Kitty, there's Mama.

149
00:08:27,841 --> 00:08:30,593
Kitty, Lydia. Eh, eh--come here.

150
00:08:32,303 --> 00:08:34,639
Those two are getting sillier
and sillier over officers.

151
00:08:34,806 --> 00:08:36,307
I don't know why you permit it, Mama.

152
00:08:36,474 --> 00:08:38,852
I had a weakness for the military
myself when I was young.

153
00:08:39,519 --> 00:08:41,813
Oh, Mama, do we have to
go home so soon?

154
00:08:42,147 --> 00:08:43,982
We just met the most fascinating
new officer.

155
00:08:44,149 --> 00:08:47,193
A Mr. Wickham. He's just joined
the Blankshires. He's charming.

156
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:48,653
Yes, that's very delightful.

157
00:08:48,820 --> 00:08:51,906
Oh, dear. Where is that coachman?
Where is Jennings?

158
00:08:52,073 --> 00:08:54,117
Oh, there he Is.
Now, come along, girls. Don't dawdle.

159
00:09:01,791 --> 00:09:03,835
Stay where you are, Jennings, stay
where you are. There's no time to lose.

160
00:09:04,002 --> 00:09:05,503
Would you take this, please?
Thank you.

161
00:09:06,087 --> 00:09:07,756
Mama, can't we stay here?

162
00:09:10,091 --> 00:09:12,177
♪♪

163
00:09:15,388 --> 00:09:17,515
Look, Mama, Lady Lucas' carriage.

164
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:20,435
Pass them, Higgins.
Pass them.

165
00:09:29,527 --> 00:09:31,696
Overtake them, Jennings!
Overtake them.

166
00:09:35,366 --> 00:09:36,868
That's it, Jennings.
That's it.

167
00:09:46,878 --> 00:09:49,881
Ah, that'll teach her a lesson.

168
00:09:50,340 --> 00:09:51,883
Keep on going, Jennings.

169
00:09:56,262 --> 00:09:58,681
♪♪

170
00:10:06,523 --> 00:10:09,192
I must tell your father about this
at once.

171
00:10:09,359 --> 00:10:10,443
No time to lose.

172
00:10:10,610 --> 00:10:11,903
Uh, go in the drawing room, girls.

173
00:10:12,320 --> 00:10:14,322
Matthews, get the other parcels
out of the chaise.

174
00:10:14,489 --> 00:10:16,783
- Yes, ma'am.
- Mr. Bennet. Mr. Bennet.

175
00:10:17,450 --> 00:10:18,326
Mr. Bennet.

176
00:10:18,493 --> 00:10:19,786
Yes, my dear.

177
00:10:21,246 --> 00:10:22,288
Mr. Bennet,

178
00:10:23,873 --> 00:10:26,126
Netherfield Park has been let at last.

179
00:10:26,292 --> 00:10:27,168
Mm-hm.

180
00:10:27,752 --> 00:10:28,670
Did you hear me?

181
00:10:28,837 --> 00:10:30,922
Netherfield Park has been let at last.

182
00:10:31,089 --> 00:10:32,090
Indeed, Mrs. Bennet.

183
00:10:32,257 --> 00:10:34,425
Well, don't you want to hear
who's taken it?

184
00:10:34,676 --> 00:10:35,677
Well, you want to tell me.

185
00:10:35,844 --> 00:10:37,345
I have no objection to hearing it.

186
00:10:37,679 --> 00:10:38,888
Mr. Bingley is his name,

187
00:10:39,055 --> 00:10:41,641
and it seems he's a young man
of large fortune.

188
00:10:41,891 --> 00:10:44,978
And he's single, my dear. Think of it.

189
00:10:45,395 --> 00:10:48,106
What a fine thing for our girls.

190
00:10:48,273 --> 00:10:48,982
Is it?

191
00:10:49,149 --> 00:10:52,026
Mr. Bennet, you know
perfectly well what I mean.

192
00:10:52,277 --> 00:10:54,362
I'm thinking of his marrying
one of our daughters.

193
00:10:55,155 --> 00:10:58,283
Oh, is that his design in settling here?

194
00:10:59,784 --> 00:11:01,202
How can you talk so, Mr. Bennet?

195
00:11:01,619 --> 00:11:02,912
This is a serious matter.

196
00:11:03,454 --> 00:11:04,998
You must go and visit him at once.

197
00:11:05,165 --> 00:11:06,457
You and the girls go.

198
00:11:07,125 --> 00:11:09,544
Or better still,
send the girls by themselves.

199
00:11:10,461 --> 00:11:11,921
For you're as handsome as any of them,

200
00:11:12,422 --> 00:11:14,340
and Mr. Bingley may like you best of all.

201
00:11:14,507 --> 00:11:15,967
Oh, my dear, you flatter me.

202
00:11:16,426 --> 00:11:18,678
When a woman has
five grown-up daughters,

203
00:11:19,053 --> 00:11:21,055
she ought to give over
thinking of her own beauty.

204
00:11:21,222 --> 00:11:23,266
Well, in most such cases,
a woman hasn't much beauty

205
00:11:23,433 --> 00:11:24,475
to think of, my dear.

206
00:11:25,768 --> 00:11:27,478
Now, seriously, Mr. Bennet,

207
00:11:27,854 --> 00:11:29,480
you must go and see Mr. Bingley.

208
00:11:30,023 --> 00:11:31,357
If you don't, Sir William and Lady Lucas

209
00:11:31,524 --> 00:11:33,443
will get there before us. Hm-hm!

210
00:11:33,610 --> 00:11:35,653
You should've seen her
galloping her horses

211
00:11:35,904 --> 00:11:37,614
to beat me from the village just now.

212
00:11:38,031 --> 00:11:38,823
Did she win?

213
00:11:39,240 --> 00:11:41,659
Ha! Indeed she did not.

214
00:11:43,536 --> 00:11:44,621
But she'd stop at nothing

215
00:11:44,787 --> 00:11:47,040
to get Mr. Bingley interested
in her Charlotte.

216
00:11:47,415 --> 00:11:48,666
Well, I'll tell you what I'll do, my dear.

217
00:11:49,083 --> 00:11:50,668
I'll write to assure him
of my hearty consent

218
00:11:50,835 --> 00:11:52,921
to his marrying whichever
he chooses of the girls.

219
00:11:53,922 --> 00:11:55,757
Though I must throw in
a good word for my Lizzy.

220
00:11:56,174 --> 00:11:58,593
Elizabeth is not one whit
better than the others,

221
00:11:58,885 --> 00:12:00,887
but you always give her the preference.

222
00:12:01,512 --> 00:12:04,557
Oh, they're all silly
and ignorant, like most girls.

223
00:12:05,850 --> 00:12:07,769
But Lizzy has some glimmerings of sense.

224
00:12:08,144 --> 00:12:08,937
Mr. Bennet,

225
00:12:09,270 --> 00:12:11,898
how can you abuse
your own children in such a way?

226
00:12:12,941 --> 00:12:15,276
You take delight in vexing me.

227
00:12:16,069 --> 00:12:19,405
You've no compassion on my poor nerves.

228
00:12:20,907 --> 00:12:22,533
Oh, you mistake me, my dear.

229
00:12:22,825 --> 00:12:24,827
I have the highest respect
for your nerves.

230
00:12:25,245 --> 00:12:27,205
I have heard you mention them
with consideration

231
00:12:27,372 --> 00:12:28,915
for the last 20 years.

232
00:12:29,082 --> 00:12:31,459
How can you be so resigned
to your daughters

233
00:12:31,626 --> 00:12:33,878
growing up to be penniless old maids?

234
00:12:34,379 --> 00:12:36,214
Leaving everything
to that cousin of yours,

235
00:12:36,381 --> 00:12:38,591
that--that odious Mr. Collins.

236
00:12:38,758 --> 00:12:40,802
Mrs. Bennet,
for the thousandth time,

237
00:12:41,427 --> 00:12:43,638
this estate was entailed
when I inherited it.

238
00:12:43,972 --> 00:12:46,099
It must, by law, go to a male heir.

239
00:12:46,683 --> 00:12:48,476
A male heir, Mrs. Bennet.

240
00:12:49,477 --> 00:12:52,313
And as possibly you remember,
we have no son.

241
00:12:53,147 --> 00:12:54,440
All the more reason

242
00:12:54,774 --> 00:12:56,317
why you should take
some responsibility

243
00:12:56,484 --> 00:12:58,486
about getting husbands for them.

244
00:12:58,653 --> 00:13:01,572
No, you escape into
your unintelligible books

245
00:13:01,739 --> 00:13:03,199
and leave everything to me.

246
00:13:06,327 --> 00:13:07,161
Look at them.

247
00:13:07,704 --> 00:13:09,247
Five of them without dowries.

248
00:13:09,414 --> 00:13:10,790
What's to become of them?

249
00:13:12,500 --> 00:13:15,253
Yes, what is to become
of the wretched creatures?

250
00:13:16,254 --> 00:13:18,298
Perhaps we should've
drowned some of them at birth.

251
00:13:18,923 --> 00:13:20,508
Mr. Bennet.

252
00:13:20,758 --> 00:13:23,886
I'm glad you didn't drown me, Papa.

253
00:13:24,053 --> 00:13:25,888
Much too nice just being alive,

254
00:13:26,055 --> 00:13:27,265
even if I never have a husband.

255
00:13:27,432 --> 00:13:29,684
Well, I hope Mr. Bingley likes the hat.

256
00:13:30,685 --> 00:13:33,104
We are not in the way of knowing
what Mr. Bingley likes,

257
00:13:33,271 --> 00:13:34,397
since we're not to meet him.

258
00:13:34,689 --> 00:13:35,648
Mary, stop pecking.

259
00:13:35,982 --> 00:13:38,276
Don't keep on coughing, Kitty.
Good heavens,

260
00:13:38,693 --> 00:13:40,820
have a little compassion
on my poor nerves.

261
00:13:40,987 --> 00:13:42,822
Oh, Kitty has no discretion
in her coughs.

262
00:13:42,989 --> 00:13:44,073
She times them ill.

263
00:13:44,240 --> 00:13:46,409
I don't cough
for my own amusement, Mama.

264
00:13:47,201 --> 00:13:48,995
Mama, why aren't we to meet
Mr. Bingley?

265
00:13:49,329 --> 00:13:50,747
Don't speak about Mr. Bingley.

266
00:13:51,247 --> 00:13:52,123
I'm sick of him.

267
00:13:52,290 --> 00:13:54,751
Eh? Oh, I'm sorry to hear that, my dear.

268
00:13:55,209 --> 00:13:56,836
If I'd known that you'd feel like this,

269
00:13:57,003 --> 00:13:57,920
I shouldn't have gone
out of my way

270
00:13:58,087 --> 00:13:59,297
to make his acquaintance last week.

271
00:13:59,547 --> 00:14:00,465
Papa!

272
00:14:00,631 --> 00:14:02,925
Oh, it's very unlucky.

273
00:14:03,343 --> 00:14:05,303
I even gave him tickets
to the Assembly Ball.

274
00:14:06,679 --> 00:14:09,140
And I believe he intends to make himself
known to you there.

275
00:14:09,515 --> 00:14:12,435
Mr. Bennet, you've been acquainted
with him all the time.

276
00:14:12,602 --> 00:14:14,645
Since he signed his lease
at Netherfield, my dear.

277
00:14:16,898 --> 00:14:19,400
Did you tell him that you had
five daughters, Papa?

278
00:14:19,567 --> 00:14:22,528
Well, I told him if he ran into
five of the silliest girls in England,

279
00:14:22,695 --> 00:14:24,739
they would be my daughters.

280
00:14:46,427 --> 00:14:49,138
Do you suppose our neighbors
from Netherfield are not coming?

281
00:14:49,514 --> 00:14:51,307
Very discourteous if they don't,

282
00:14:51,516 --> 00:14:53,518
considering Mr. Bennet gave them tickets.

283
00:15:12,245 --> 00:15:14,497
Don't you think we dance
beautifully together, Mr. Wickham?

284
00:15:14,664 --> 00:15:16,749
I suspect you dance beautifully
with anyone, Miss Lydia,

285
00:15:17,250 --> 00:15:18,251
and I know I don't.

286
00:15:35,268 --> 00:15:37,562
Tell me, who is the lovely creature
in the blue dress?

287
00:15:38,855 --> 00:15:41,649
That lovely creature
is my sister Elizabeth.

288
00:15:41,816 --> 00:15:43,359
Ah, then I'm in luck.

289
00:15:43,609 --> 00:15:45,611
Please present me
when the dance is over.

290
00:15:47,321 --> 00:15:49,490
Lizzy, this is Mr. Wickham.

291
00:15:49,991 --> 00:15:50,950
He wants to meet you.

292
00:15:51,367 --> 00:15:52,994
He thinks you're a lovely creature.

293
00:15:56,956 --> 00:15:59,208
Someday I'll tell you
what sort of a creature you are.

294
00:16:05,506 --> 00:16:07,967
After that introduction, I hardly know
how to begin, Miss Elizabeth.

295
00:16:08,426 --> 00:16:10,011
Shall I offer a remark on the weather?

296
00:16:11,137 --> 00:16:13,222
If you can make it fit
for a young lady's ears.

297
00:16:13,389 --> 00:16:14,140
You're right.

298
00:16:14,307 --> 00:16:15,850
The weather's too dangerous a subject.

299
00:16:16,017 --> 00:16:16,767
To be quite safe,

300
00:16:16,934 --> 00:16:18,936
I shall ask you
how you like it here in Meryton.

301
00:16:19,145 --> 00:16:21,063
Ah, that's anything but safe.

302
00:16:22,356 --> 00:16:25,234
I'm just discovering
that I like it prodigiously.

303
00:16:31,157 --> 00:16:32,408
I hope you'll ask me when I began

304
00:16:32,575 --> 00:16:34,076
to like it so prodigiously,
Miss Elizabeth.

305
00:16:34,619 --> 00:16:35,536
I will.

306
00:16:37,288 --> 00:16:38,998
- When did you?
- Uh--

307
00:16:44,003 --> 00:16:46,881
- The moment I saw you.
- Very pretty, sir.

308
00:16:47,632 --> 00:16:49,800
Shall I tell you what I thought
the moment I saw you?

309
00:16:49,967 --> 00:16:52,053
- Only if it's pleasant.
- It is. I thought--

310
00:16:56,766 --> 00:16:58,142
You were going to say,
Miss Elizabeth?

311
00:16:58,309 --> 00:17:00,686
Oh, yes. I'm sorry, I forget.

312
00:17:05,733 --> 00:17:06,943
♪♪

313
00:17:10,947 --> 00:17:11,948
Ladies and gentlemen,

314
00:17:12,365 --> 00:17:15,618
Miss Bingley, Mr. Bingley
and Mr. Darcy.

315
00:17:15,993 --> 00:17:17,662
This is indeed an honor.

316
00:17:19,121 --> 00:17:20,581
Very distinguished.

317
00:17:21,123 --> 00:17:23,376
Uh, Kitty, Kitty,
your dress is too décolleté,

318
00:17:23,543 --> 00:17:24,252
pull it up a little.

319
00:17:24,418 --> 00:17:26,837
Uh, Lydia--Lydia,
there's perspiration on your nose.

320
00:17:27,004 --> 00:17:29,173
Don't get so hot.
It's very unladylike.

321
00:17:29,632 --> 00:17:31,509
- Oh, Jane. Jane, dear.
- Yes, Mama?

322
00:17:31,968 --> 00:17:34,262
Of course,
you're quite perfect, my dear.

323
00:17:34,512 --> 00:17:36,681
Lizzy, Lizzy, do try to make
a good impression.

324
00:17:36,847 --> 00:17:38,766
You can be so appealing
when you want to be.

325
00:17:39,016 --> 00:17:42,311
Oh, uh, Mary,
try to sparkle a little.

326
00:17:43,479 --> 00:17:44,522
Just a little.

327
00:17:54,657 --> 00:17:56,867
- A waltz, Mr. Darcy.
- Yes.

328
00:17:57,034 --> 00:17:59,078
- How modern.
- Yes, indeed.

329
00:17:59,579 --> 00:18:02,123
- Shall we have our dance now?
- If you care to.

330
00:18:14,719 --> 00:18:17,305
What a handsome young man
Mr. Darcy is.

331
00:18:17,555 --> 00:18:18,848
And so rich too.

332
00:18:19,390 --> 00:18:23,102
His mother was a daughter
of the Marquis of Scarlingford.

333
00:18:23,519 --> 00:18:26,814
Did you hear that, Jane?
The Marquis of Scarlingford.

334
00:18:26,981 --> 00:18:30,109
- And doesn't he know it.
- I like Mr. Bingley better.

335
00:18:30,693 --> 00:18:31,611
Mr. Darcy's so--

336
00:18:31,861 --> 00:18:33,154
So supercilious.

337
00:18:34,071 --> 00:18:36,365
And my goodness,
he does have an air about him.

338
00:18:41,245 --> 00:18:44,040
Pray, Sir William,
who is that uncommonly handsome girl?

339
00:18:44,415 --> 00:18:45,082
Who?

340
00:18:45,249 --> 00:18:46,459
Over there, next to the pillar.

341
00:18:47,501 --> 00:18:49,337
Oh, that's Miss Bennet.

342
00:18:51,380 --> 00:18:53,007
This is our dance, Miss Elizabeth.

343
00:19:04,101 --> 00:19:07,188
Oh, Mrs. Bennet,
may I present Mr. Bingley?

344
00:19:07,688 --> 00:19:09,440
Mrs. Bennet, Mrs. Philips,

345
00:19:09,774 --> 00:19:12,443
Miss Jane Bennet,
Miss Mary Bennet.

346
00:19:14,904 --> 00:19:18,449
Mr. Bingley, we're all so delighted
that you've taken Netherfield.

347
00:19:18,616 --> 00:19:19,742
Having it standing empty

348
00:19:19,909 --> 00:19:21,911
was a loss to
the whole neighborhood,

349
00:19:22,244 --> 00:19:25,331
like an oyster shell
without an oyster in it.

350
00:19:25,915 --> 00:19:27,375
Well, here is the oyster, madam.

351
00:19:28,084 --> 00:19:29,627
But if I may be permitted to say so,

352
00:19:29,877 --> 00:19:31,337
it is you who have the pearl.

353
00:19:31,545 --> 00:19:33,297
Charming, charming.

354
00:19:33,631 --> 00:19:35,049
Oh, uh, Jane, dear,

355
00:19:35,216 --> 00:19:37,134
why don't
you say something to Mr. Bingley?

356
00:19:38,552 --> 00:19:39,679
Good evening, sir.

357
00:19:40,429 --> 00:19:42,181
May I have the honor
of this dance, Miss Bennet?

358
00:19:42,807 --> 00:19:43,933
With pleasure.

359
00:19:47,853 --> 00:19:50,690
Think of having a daughter
happily settled at Netherfield.

360
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:53,776
She'll be pricing
wedding garments tomorrow.

361
00:19:55,319 --> 00:19:58,239
Hey, Jemima.
Stop scratching yourself.

362
00:19:58,406 --> 00:19:59,198
Yes, Mama.

363
00:20:08,207 --> 00:20:11,293
Well, is Miss Bingley engaged
to Mr. Darcy?

364
00:20:11,460 --> 00:20:12,628
If she Is,
she ought to break It.

365
00:20:12,795 --> 00:20:13,462
Why?

366
00:20:13,879 --> 00:20:15,965
No man can be in love
and look so bored.

367
00:20:16,340 --> 00:20:18,509
Did you ever see such people,
Mr. Darcy?

368
00:20:18,676 --> 00:20:20,553
Really, I think my brother
ought to apologize

369
00:20:20,720 --> 00:20:22,179
for bringing us
to a place like this.

370
00:20:22,430 --> 00:20:24,306
He's so dreadfully undiscriminating.

371
00:20:24,557 --> 00:20:27,226
He seems to be able to
enjoy himself in any society.

372
00:20:27,393 --> 00:20:29,395
I'm not surprised at his being
able to enjoy himself...

373
00:20:29,937 --> 00:20:31,063
in that society.

374
00:20:31,230 --> 00:20:33,023
You know, Miss Bennet, you've done
a very extraordinary thing.

375
00:20:33,190 --> 00:20:34,358
- What?
- You have talked to me

376
00:20:34,525 --> 00:20:35,693
about all your friends in Meryton

377
00:20:35,860 --> 00:20:37,737
without saying one malicious word.

378
00:20:37,903 --> 00:20:39,613
Oh, but they're all such agreeable people,

379
00:20:39,780 --> 00:20:41,031
so kind and pleasant.

380
00:20:41,198 --> 00:20:43,659
That never prevented anyone
from talking maliciously.

381
00:21:02,344 --> 00:21:03,637
- Your health.
- Your health.

382
00:21:04,138 --> 00:21:05,431
Uh-uh, no heel-tapping, Miss Kitty.

383
00:21:05,598 --> 00:21:06,432
Down in one gulp.

384
00:21:11,270 --> 00:21:13,814
Don't cough, chicken.
Put your hands over your head.

385
00:21:15,149 --> 00:21:17,234
Oh, look, they're dancing.
That should help you.

386
00:21:21,322 --> 00:21:23,407
My goodness, what a hullabaloo.

387
00:21:23,574 --> 00:21:25,534
One is only young once.

388
00:21:26,786 --> 00:21:28,204
That odious Mr. Darcy,

389
00:21:28,537 --> 00:21:29,997
looking down his nose at everybody.

390
00:21:30,247 --> 00:21:31,624
Does he think he's
too good for us?

391
00:21:31,791 --> 00:21:32,708
Come, sister.

392
00:21:44,053 --> 00:21:46,180
Isn't that delightful,
your like riding as much as I do?

393
00:21:46,347 --> 00:21:47,014
Yes.

394
00:21:47,181 --> 00:21:48,891
I hope we may be able
to ride together sometime.

395
00:21:49,058 --> 00:21:51,060
- That would be nice.
- Why, Caroline.

396
00:21:51,227 --> 00:21:53,562
Miss Jane, will you take
a little stroll about the room with me?

397
00:21:53,729 --> 00:21:54,772
With pleasure.

398
00:21:54,939 --> 00:21:56,607
Oh, no, Charles,
you were not invited.

399
00:21:56,774 --> 00:21:59,109
I have a thousand things
I want to ask Miss Jane.

400
00:22:03,697 --> 00:22:06,742
You know, I have a feeling
about Mr. Bingley and Jane.

401
00:22:07,243 --> 00:22:09,912
I really have.
Look, look, sister.

402
00:22:13,457 --> 00:22:16,418
Miss Bingley is being
excessively gracious to Jane.

403
00:22:16,669 --> 00:22:19,338
What did I tell you?
It's a sure sign.

404
00:22:20,714 --> 00:22:22,550
You must come over
to Netherfield one day.

405
00:22:22,716 --> 00:22:23,676
I shall be so bored.

406
00:22:24,009 --> 00:22:25,094
- What?
- Oh, you know,

407
00:22:25,261 --> 00:22:27,096
marooned out here in the wilderness.

408
00:22:27,680 --> 00:22:29,223
We'll arrange it,
shall we, very soon?

409
00:22:29,390 --> 00:22:30,432
That would be delightful.

410
00:22:52,746 --> 00:22:55,541
Oh, isn't this better than
brazening it out in the open?

411
00:22:55,791 --> 00:22:57,459
No one can tell
we haven't partners here.

412
00:22:57,793 --> 00:23:00,588
Oh, why is England cursed with
so many more women than men?

413
00:23:02,715 --> 00:23:03,716
Darcy.

414
00:23:06,135 --> 00:23:09,013
Come, I hate to see you stalking about
by yourself in a stupid manner.

415
00:23:09,179 --> 00:23:10,681
- Why don't you dance?
- With whom?

416
00:23:11,265 --> 00:23:13,475
Your sister is engaged and
there isn't another woman in the room

417
00:23:13,642 --> 00:23:15,686
that it wouldn't be a punishment
for me to stand up with.

418
00:23:16,145 --> 00:23:17,855
But the place is full of pretty girls.

419
00:23:18,022 --> 00:23:20,733
I've noticed only one, and
you seem to have monopolized her.

420
00:23:21,150 --> 00:23:22,234
Yes, isn't she lovely?

421
00:23:22,818 --> 00:23:24,570
But there's that sister of hers,
Miss Elizabeth.

422
00:23:24,945 --> 00:23:26,322
They say she has a lively wit.

423
00:23:26,655 --> 00:23:28,782
Provincial young lady with a lively wit.

424
00:23:28,949 --> 00:23:30,659
Heaven preserve us.
And there's that mother of hers.

425
00:23:31,118 --> 00:23:32,453
It's not the mother
you have to dance with, Darcy.

426
00:23:32,620 --> 00:23:34,163
It's the daughter.
She's charming.

427
00:23:34,330 --> 00:23:36,248
Yes, she looks tolerable enough.

428
00:23:36,749 --> 00:23:38,626
But I'm in no humor tonight
to give consequence

429
00:23:38,792 --> 00:23:40,377
to the middle classes at play.

430
00:23:46,133 --> 00:23:47,760
What a charming man.

431
00:23:50,262 --> 00:23:53,474
Of all the arrogant, detestable snobs.

432
00:23:53,807 --> 00:23:55,559
Oh, but, Lizzy,
he didn't know you were listening.

433
00:23:55,726 --> 00:23:56,602
What difference does that make?

434
00:23:56,769 --> 00:23:58,395
He'd have said it
just the same if he had.

435
00:23:59,605 --> 00:24:01,690
"Oh, she looks tolerable enough,

436
00:24:02,608 --> 00:24:04,777
but I'm in no humor tonight
to give consequence

437
00:24:04,944 --> 00:24:06,904
to the middle classes at play."

438
00:24:08,072 --> 00:24:10,282
And think how we badgered
poor Papa to get him here.

439
00:24:10,449 --> 00:24:12,242
- Oh, I could--
- Oh, praise heaven.

440
00:24:12,743 --> 00:24:14,787
I have this dance
engaged with Canon Stubbs.

441
00:24:14,954 --> 00:24:17,206
He's never learned the steps,
but he likes the exercise.

442
00:24:17,373 --> 00:24:19,166
And it gets me away from the wall.

443
00:24:36,433 --> 00:24:39,311
- Um, but as I was saying--
- I was about to ask you, Sir William,

444
00:24:39,478 --> 00:24:41,814
if you would do me the kindness
to introduce me to Miss Bennet?

445
00:24:41,981 --> 00:24:43,273
Oh, certainly, yes.

446
00:24:43,440 --> 00:24:45,651
Dancing is a charming amusement
for young people.

447
00:24:45,818 --> 00:24:48,737
In my opinion,
it's one of the first refinements

448
00:24:48,904 --> 00:24:50,322
of a polished society.

449
00:24:50,489 --> 00:24:51,615
It has the added advantage, sir,

450
00:24:51,782 --> 00:24:53,742
of being one of the first refinements
of savages.

451
00:24:53,909 --> 00:24:56,704
- Every Hottentot can dance.
- Yes, yes, quite so.

452
00:24:57,997 --> 00:24:59,415
80, Miss Elizabeth,

453
00:24:59,581 --> 00:25:02,292
may I have the honor
to present Mr. Darcy?

454
00:25:02,668 --> 00:25:04,962
He's eager to invite you to dance.

455
00:25:06,797 --> 00:25:09,216
Now that you've been forewarned
of my eagerness to dance with you,

456
00:25:09,591 --> 00:25:11,343
may I hope that you will
do me the honor?

457
00:25:11,635 --> 00:25:13,971
I am afraid that the honor
of standing up with you,

458
00:25:14,138 --> 00:25:16,056
Mr. Darcy,
is more than I can bear.

459
00:25:16,765 --> 00:25:17,933
Pray, excuse me.

460
00:25:18,183 --> 00:25:19,727
Am I to understand that you

461
00:25:19,893 --> 00:25:21,770
do not wish to dance with me,
Miss Bennet?

462
00:25:21,979 --> 00:25:24,481
Sir, I am begging to be excused.

463
00:25:27,026 --> 00:25:28,235
The loss is mine, I'm sure.

464
00:25:28,402 --> 00:25:30,696
You perhaps know best about that, sir.

465
00:25:32,573 --> 00:25:34,867
Miss Elizabeth,
if you're not engaged,

466
00:25:35,075 --> 00:25:36,452
will you honor me
with the next dance?

467
00:25:36,618 --> 00:25:38,537
I should be very happy
to dance with you.

468
00:25:39,246 --> 00:25:41,373
Oh, this is Mr. Wickham, Mr. Darcy.

469
00:25:42,624 --> 00:25:44,209
Mr. Darcy and I have met before.

470
00:25:46,003 --> 00:25:47,254
We have indeed.

471
00:25:50,424 --> 00:25:51,592
The man must be mad.

472
00:25:52,009 --> 00:25:54,678
Mad? You're too charitable,
Miss Elizabeth.

473
00:25:56,096 --> 00:25:58,599
If you were better acquainted,
you'd see in him another man.

474
00:25:58,766 --> 00:26:00,142
Have you known him a long time?

475
00:26:00,601 --> 00:26:01,810
Yes, since childhood.

476
00:26:02,061 --> 00:26:04,021
But as you saw,
we're not on friendly terms.

477
00:26:04,897 --> 00:26:07,232
Without knowing anything about it,
I'm on your side.

478
00:26:07,441 --> 00:26:08,817
Thank you, Miss Elizabeth.

479
00:26:09,318 --> 00:26:11,945
You see, my father was steward
at the Darcy estate.

480
00:26:12,404 --> 00:26:13,906
Young Darcy and I grew up together,

481
00:26:14,239 --> 00:26:15,407
almost like brothers.

482
00:26:16,450 --> 00:26:18,327
But I mustn't trust myself
on that subject.

483
00:26:18,827 --> 00:26:20,537
After what Darcy has done to me, I...

484
00:26:21,121 --> 00:26:22,456
I wouldn't be a fair judge.

485
00:26:23,373 --> 00:26:25,751
Oh, polka-mazurka.

486
00:26:26,376 --> 00:26:28,921
I didn't expect to find Meryton
abreast with the new fashion.

487
00:26:29,379 --> 00:26:30,964
You underrate us, Mr. Wickham.

488
00:26:31,465 --> 00:26:33,092
Meryton is abreast of everything.

489
00:26:33,592 --> 00:26:36,512
Everything except insolence
and bad manners.

490
00:26:37,304 --> 00:26:39,640
Those London fashions
we do not admire.

491
00:27:13,757 --> 00:27:15,425
Things are working out exactly as I hoped

492
00:27:15,592 --> 00:27:18,137
the first minute I set eyes
on Mr. Bingley.

493
00:27:18,387 --> 00:27:19,596
What's this about Mr. Bingley?

494
00:27:19,763 --> 00:27:21,431
I'm dining with him
and his sister, Papa.

495
00:27:21,598 --> 00:27:23,976
- This is the day.
- Oh, great and fateful day.

496
00:27:24,143 --> 00:27:26,979
Mama, do you suppose
they'll have turtle soup for dinner?

497
00:27:27,396 --> 00:27:28,814
They're so frightfully rich.

498
00:27:29,148 --> 00:27:30,899
No, dear,
you--you can't expect turtle soup

499
00:27:31,066 --> 00:27:32,943
until the engagement
is actually announced.

500
00:27:33,277 --> 00:27:35,154
Now, Jane,
don't forget what I told you.

501
00:27:35,529 --> 00:27:37,239
Eh, don't be too distant with him,

502
00:27:37,614 --> 00:27:39,908
and be sure and laugh
when he makes a joke.

503
00:27:40,075 --> 00:27:41,160
Yes, even if it's a bad one.

504
00:27:41,493 --> 00:27:42,911
Especially if it's a bad one.

505
00:27:43,245 --> 00:27:46,415
And try to sit where
he can see you in profile.

506
00:27:46,832 --> 00:27:48,584
You know, dear,
although I say it, I shouldn't,

507
00:27:48,834 --> 00:27:51,253
you have the loveliest profile
in all Herefordshire.

508
00:27:51,420 --> 00:27:52,754
Mama.

509
00:27:53,755 --> 00:27:55,090
♪♪

510
00:27:58,260 --> 00:28:01,096
Oh, and, Jane,
if Mr. Bingley should suggest

511
00:28:01,263 --> 00:28:03,682
a stroll before dinner,
don't refuse.

512
00:28:03,849 --> 00:28:05,893
There are such delightfully secluded walks

513
00:28:06,059 --> 00:28:07,394
in those shrubberies
around Netherfield.

514
00:28:07,561 --> 00:28:08,187
Yes, Mama.

515
00:28:08,645 --> 00:28:10,439
There won't be much
strolling today, Mama.

516
00:28:11,607 --> 00:28:13,775
Oh, dear me, Lizzy,
I'm afraid you're right.

517
00:28:14,067 --> 00:28:16,778
Oh, and I had such hopes
of those shrubberies.

518
00:28:18,405 --> 00:28:19,656
Get out, Jane.
Get out, dear, at once.

519
00:28:19,823 --> 00:28:20,741
But, Mama, I want to go.

520
00:28:20,908 --> 00:28:21,783
Who said you weren't going?

521
00:28:21,950 --> 00:28:23,952
Get out and change
your clothes immediately.

522
00:28:24,244 --> 00:28:26,288
Uh, take the carriage
back to the stables, Jennings,

523
00:28:26,455 --> 00:28:28,707
and tell the boy to saddle
Miss Jane's horse.

524
00:28:29,082 --> 00:28:31,793
Oh, but, Mama, you can't send
Jane out on horseback.

525
00:28:32,085 --> 00:28:33,754
It's going to rain,
and she'll catch a cold.

526
00:28:33,921 --> 00:28:36,757
Oh, fiddlesticks, people don't catch
cold from a few drops of water.

527
00:28:36,924 --> 00:28:39,843
Besides, if it rains she won't be able
to ride home after dinner.

528
00:28:40,010 --> 00:28:41,386
They'll have to keep her all night.

529
00:28:41,720 --> 00:28:44,181
You know, dear, there isn't a thing like
wet weather for engagements.

530
00:28:44,640 --> 00:28:47,434
Your dear father and I became
engaged in a thunderstorm.

531
00:28:48,518 --> 00:28:50,437
♪♪

532
00:29:07,162 --> 00:29:09,748
You'll be confined here
for at least a week, Miss Bennet.

533
00:29:09,915 --> 00:29:10,958
- A week?
- A week?

534
00:29:11,208 --> 00:29:12,960
I hope your mother
won't be too much upset.

535
00:29:13,126 --> 00:29:14,711
Oh, no. Mother will be delight--

536
00:29:15,754 --> 00:29:18,674
I mean, she'll be grateful
I'm with such good friends.

537
00:29:24,388 --> 00:29:26,974
Now, tea. Thoroughly sweet.

538
00:29:36,149 --> 00:29:37,025
This way.

539
00:29:38,819 --> 00:29:40,279
Now, open your mouth.

540
00:29:42,906 --> 00:29:44,408
Say "ah."

541
00:29:45,534 --> 00:29:46,201
Ah?

542
00:29:46,368 --> 00:29:48,370
- Once more. "Ah."
- Ah.

543
00:29:48,787 --> 00:29:51,248
A-a-achoo!

544
00:29:53,875 --> 00:29:57,212
The epidermis seems to have
lost its sudorific activity.

545
00:29:57,546 --> 00:30:00,632
I detect distinct symptoms of pyrexia.

546
00:30:00,799 --> 00:30:02,718
Oh, is that bad, Dr. McIntosh?

547
00:30:02,884 --> 00:30:05,053
He just means you're
rather feverish, Miss Jane.

548
00:30:05,220 --> 00:30:05,929
Oh.

549
00:30:06,346 --> 00:30:09,599
There is also acute coryza
of the nasal cavities,

550
00:30:09,891 --> 00:30:12,394
accompanied by local
inflammation of the larynx.

551
00:30:12,853 --> 00:30:15,272
Not to mention
some pulmonary congestion

552
00:30:15,731 --> 00:30:18,483
and neuralgic pains
in the temporal region.

553
00:30:19,026 --> 00:30:20,152
In other words, Miss Jane,

554
00:30:20,319 --> 00:30:22,362
you have a bad cold
and a headache.

555
00:30:24,656 --> 00:30:26,033
What do you want us to do, doctor?

556
00:30:26,241 --> 00:30:28,994
I would advise the immediate
application of a sinapism.

557
00:30:29,453 --> 00:30:31,788
A sidapisup?
A mustard plaster.

558
00:30:32,497 --> 00:30:34,916
There seems to be someone
coming up the drive.

559
00:30:38,295 --> 00:30:39,588
It would appear to be
one of your sisters.

560
00:30:40,422 --> 00:30:41,381
Miss Elizabeth.

561
00:30:41,548 --> 00:30:42,674
Well, I'll go down and meet her.

562
00:30:46,053 --> 00:30:47,054
Come in, Miss Elizabeth.

563
00:30:47,804 --> 00:30:48,597
Oh.

564
00:30:49,598 --> 00:30:52,684
How do you do, Mr. Bingley?
We got Jane's note this morning.

565
00:30:52,851 --> 00:30:54,353
She will be so happy to see you.

566
00:30:55,520 --> 00:30:56,104
Thank you.

567
00:31:05,364 --> 00:31:06,782
Uh, this way, Miss Elizabeth.

568
00:31:15,207 --> 00:31:16,333
Please forgive me, Miss Bingley,

569
00:31:16,500 --> 00:31:18,001
I'm afraid it's a great intrusion.

570
00:31:18,168 --> 00:31:20,629
My uneasiness about my sister
must be my excuse.

571
00:31:20,796 --> 00:31:22,381
It's just a little cold, that's all.

572
00:31:22,589 --> 00:31:24,716
Ah, but Dr. McIntosh says
there's some fever.

573
00:31:25,008 --> 00:31:27,594
It doesn't amount to anything.
Nothing to get agitated about.

574
00:31:27,761 --> 00:31:29,388
I thought I heard your voice,
Miss Elizabeth.

575
00:31:29,554 --> 00:31:30,889
Have you come to visit your sister?

576
00:31:31,348 --> 00:31:33,433
And she seems actually to have walked.

577
00:31:34,851 --> 00:31:36,061
The horses were needed at the farm.

578
00:31:36,228 --> 00:31:37,562
I had no alternative.

579
00:31:37,771 --> 00:31:40,023
- You didn't come alone, I hope.
- All alone.

580
00:31:40,399 --> 00:31:41,358
But how shocking.

581
00:31:41,858 --> 00:31:43,151
Don't you think so, Mr. Darcy?

582
00:31:43,652 --> 00:31:46,279
Is it shocking for a young lady
to be concerned about her sister?

583
00:31:46,446 --> 00:31:49,616
But to have come all this way
unaccompanied, and on foot.

584
00:31:50,283 --> 00:31:52,494
Mr. Bingley, would it be
possible for me to see Jane?

585
00:31:52,744 --> 00:31:54,204
At once. I'll take you up myself.

586
00:31:54,371 --> 00:31:55,914
♪♪

587
00:32:05,549 --> 00:32:10,262
♪ Thou green-crested lapwing... ♪

588
00:32:10,887 --> 00:32:12,472
Papa, listen to Mary.

589
00:32:12,764 --> 00:32:14,266
I can't help listening, my dear.

590
00:32:15,267 --> 00:32:16,643
Will you be quiet!

591
00:32:16,810 --> 00:32:19,104
NAP-fl
♪ I charge you disturb not... ♪

592
00:32:19,271 --> 00:32:20,772
Mama, the sun's shining.

593
00:32:21,106 --> 00:32:22,274
May I go to the village?

594
00:32:22,441 --> 00:32:24,568
Mm. May I go, too, Mama?

595
00:32:24,734 --> 00:32:26,111
Oh, I suppose so.

596
00:32:26,570 --> 00:32:28,530
Oh, and stop that caterwauling.

597
00:32:29,448 --> 00:32:31,408
Has anybody heard how
Jane is this morning?

598
00:32:31,575 --> 00:32:33,827
Uh, Mr. Bingley sent
a note over by his groom.

599
00:32:33,994 --> 00:32:34,995
She is much better.

600
00:32:35,162 --> 00:32:37,789
Such a happy idea of mine,
sending her off in the rain.

601
00:32:38,123 --> 00:32:39,541
Yes, but to Jane must go all the credit

602
00:32:39,708 --> 00:32:41,126
for having caught the cold, my dear.

603
00:32:41,835 --> 00:32:43,378
How much longer
are Elizabeth and Jane

604
00:32:43,545 --> 00:32:44,504
going to stay at Netherfield?

605
00:32:44,671 --> 00:32:46,298
Well, we're hoping Elizabeth can manage

606
00:32:46,465 --> 00:32:47,632
to catch a cold of her own

607
00:32:47,799 --> 00:32:50,218
and stay long enough
to get engaged to Mr. Darcy.

608
00:32:51,094 --> 00:32:52,888
Then if a good snowstorm
could be arranged,

609
00:32:53,054 --> 00:32:55,056
we'd send Kitty over.

610
00:32:55,390 --> 00:32:57,142
And if a young man should happen
to be in the house,

611
00:32:57,309 --> 00:32:59,394
a young man who likes
singing, of course,

612
00:32:59,561 --> 00:33:01,771
and can discuss philosophy,
Mary could go.

613
00:33:02,689 --> 00:33:05,233
Then, if a dashing young soldier

614
00:33:05,400 --> 00:33:07,402
in a handsome uniform
should appear for Lydia,

615
00:33:07,944 --> 00:33:09,529
everything would be perfect, my dear.

616
00:33:10,113 --> 00:33:11,656
Just a little marmalade please,
Kitty darling.

617
00:33:13,366 --> 00:33:14,576
That's 20 and 10 for the game.

618
00:33:14,868 --> 00:33:16,161
I have two and 20, I believe.

619
00:33:16,912 --> 00:33:17,662
Ah.

620
00:33:18,413 --> 00:33:20,457
Miss Eliza, is your patient asleep?

621
00:33:20,624 --> 00:33:21,791
Is she better, Miss Elizabeth?

622
00:33:21,958 --> 00:33:23,376
Yes, her fever is quite gone.

623
00:33:23,585 --> 00:33:26,213
I'm so glad.
Will you join us In a game of cards?

624
00:33:26,546 --> 00:33:28,798
No, thank you. Please continue
with whatever you were playing.

625
00:33:28,965 --> 00:33:31,259
I'd enjoy looking at
some of your books, if I may.

626
00:33:31,510 --> 00:33:33,470
Miss Eliza is a great reader, I'm sure,

627
00:33:33,637 --> 00:33:36,348
and has no pleasure in anything
so frivolous as cards.

628
00:33:36,515 --> 00:33:38,391
Hm. Is that true, Miss Elizabeth?

629
00:33:38,892 --> 00:33:41,019
Not at all.
I'm not a great reader,

630
00:33:41,186 --> 00:33:43,772
and I have pleasure in many
frivolous things. Thank you.

631
00:33:44,105 --> 00:33:46,107
I'm sure you have pleasure
in nursing your sister,

632
00:33:46,608 --> 00:33:47,776
and I hope it will soon be increased

633
00:33:47,943 --> 00:33:49,027
by seeing her quite well.

634
00:33:49,236 --> 00:33:51,446
Thank you. I think she may
be taken home tomorrow.

635
00:33:51,780 --> 00:33:53,323
- Oh, not so soon.
- I'm afraid so.

636
00:33:53,490 --> 00:33:55,992
You see, my mother's expecting
a visit from our cousin Collins,

637
00:33:56,159 --> 00:33:57,327
whom none of us has ever seen.

638
00:33:57,494 --> 00:33:59,454
Naturally, you're curious to see her.

639
00:34:00,121 --> 00:34:01,665
My cousin Collins is a man,

640
00:34:01,915 --> 00:34:04,501
but we are curious to see him. Naturally.

641
00:34:04,834 --> 00:34:06,795
Miss Jane mustn't go out
until the doctor advises it,

642
00:34:06,962 --> 00:34:08,004
cousin or no cousin.

643
00:34:08,505 --> 00:34:10,423
There are others in the library
if you care for none of these.

644
00:34:10,632 --> 00:34:12,384
This will suit me perfectly, thank you.

645
00:34:13,009 --> 00:34:15,720
What a delightful library
you have at Pemberley, Mr. Darcy.

646
00:34:15,887 --> 00:34:18,223
It ought to be good.
It's the work of many generations.

647
00:34:18,640 --> 00:34:19,891
Shall we continue, Darcy?

648
00:34:20,517 --> 00:34:22,060
Oh, you and Miss Bingley play.

649
00:34:22,227 --> 00:34:24,145
I really must finish my letter
to my sister.

650
00:34:24,563 --> 00:34:27,274
How I long to see
your sister again, Mr. Darcy.

651
00:34:27,566 --> 00:34:29,901
I've never met anyone
who delighted me so much.

652
00:34:30,277 --> 00:34:32,362
Such a countenance, such manners.

653
00:34:33,196 --> 00:34:35,448
And so extremely accomplished
for one of her age.

654
00:34:35,615 --> 00:34:37,158
It's amazing to me how young ladies

655
00:34:37,325 --> 00:34:39,578
can have the patience to be
so accomplished as they all are.

656
00:34:40,078 --> 00:34:42,539
All young ladies
are not accomplished, Charles.

657
00:34:42,706 --> 00:34:43,623
All I know are.

658
00:34:44,624 --> 00:34:46,167
Aren't all you know
accomplished, Darcy?

659
00:34:47,043 --> 00:34:49,671
I can't boast of knowing more than
half a dozen who are really so.

660
00:34:50,130 --> 00:34:51,089
Nor I.

661
00:34:51,715 --> 00:34:53,216
What do you think, Miss Eliza?

662
00:34:54,551 --> 00:34:57,637
I think that you and Mr. Darcy
must comprehend a great deal

663
00:34:57,804 --> 00:34:59,598
in your idea
of the accomplished woman.

664
00:35:00,473 --> 00:35:01,141
I do.

665
00:35:01,308 --> 00:35:02,183
Oh, certainly.

666
00:35:02,350 --> 00:35:04,019
No one can really
be esteemed accomplished

667
00:35:04,185 --> 00:35:05,353
unless she has
a thorough knowledge

668
00:35:05,520 --> 00:35:07,147
of music, singing, dancing,

669
00:35:07,897 --> 00:35:09,733
and the modern languages.

670
00:35:10,275 --> 00:35:12,360
Besides, she must
also possess a certain something

671
00:35:12,527 --> 00:35:14,029
in the tone of her voice,

672
00:35:14,279 --> 00:35:16,823
in her address,
in her expressions,

673
00:35:17,115 --> 00:35:19,451
as well as in her figure and carriage.

674
00:35:19,826 --> 00:35:21,786
To which she must add
something more substantial

675
00:35:21,953 --> 00:35:24,789
in the improvement of her mind,
by extensive reading.

676
00:35:27,959 --> 00:35:29,669
I'm no longer surprised at your knowing

677
00:35:29,836 --> 00:35:31,129
only six accomplished women.

678
00:35:31,504 --> 00:35:32,839
I wonder at your knowing any.

679
00:35:34,341 --> 00:35:36,676
Caroline, are we to discuss
this subject further,

680
00:35:37,344 --> 00:35:38,386
or shall we play piquet?

681
00:35:38,678 --> 00:35:40,555
Oh, I don't wish to play cards, Charles.

682
00:35:40,805 --> 00:35:42,349
I think I'd prefer a book too.

683
00:35:42,766 --> 00:35:45,602
After all,
there's no enjoyment like reading.

684
00:35:48,396 --> 00:35:49,814
I'll play with you, Mr. Bingley.

685
00:35:50,940 --> 00:35:51,775
Will you cut?

686
00:35:54,778 --> 00:35:56,863
- Do you like dancing, Miss Elizabeth?
- Love It.

687
00:35:57,072 --> 00:35:59,282
As soon as your sister has
fully recovered, I'll give a ball.

688
00:35:59,491 --> 00:36:01,159
Oh, that's a delightful idea.

689
00:36:01,743 --> 00:36:02,994
Pray, tell your sister
that I am delighted

690
00:36:03,161 --> 00:36:04,746
to hear of her progress in music.

691
00:36:05,038 --> 00:36:06,831
And let her know
that I am quite in raptures

692
00:36:06,998 --> 00:36:08,708
with her beautiful little design
for a table.

693
00:36:09,751 --> 00:36:11,795
Will you allow me to defer your
raptures until I write again?

694
00:36:11,961 --> 00:36:13,505
I really haven't room to do them justice.

695
00:36:13,963 --> 00:36:15,965
It's of no consequence.
I shall see her soon.

696
00:36:16,841 --> 00:36:19,344
I'm hungry. May I get you
some food, Miss Elizabeth?

697
00:36:19,511 --> 00:36:20,387
No, thank you.

698
00:36:20,845 --> 00:36:22,263
Miss Eliza, let me persuade you

699
00:36:22,430 --> 00:36:24,432
to join me in taking a turn
about the room.

700
00:36:24,766 --> 00:36:27,143
You'll find it very refreshing
after sitting for so long.

701
00:36:27,310 --> 00:36:28,228
With pleasure.

702
00:36:28,561 --> 00:36:31,106
Mr. Darcy, would you join us?

703
00:36:31,523 --> 00:36:32,565
Uh, no, thank you.

704
00:36:33,650 --> 00:36:36,027
I can imagine only two motives
for your walking,

705
00:36:36,444 --> 00:36:39,030
with either of which
my joining you would interfere.

706
00:36:40,990 --> 00:36:42,617
What does he mean by that,
Miss Elizabeth?

707
00:36:42,867 --> 00:36:44,452
If I read his character correctly,

708
00:36:44,619 --> 00:36:46,329
he means to be severe upon us.

709
00:36:46,746 --> 00:36:48,373
And the best way of disappointing him

710
00:36:48,540 --> 00:36:50,500
is not to ask.

711
00:36:51,000 --> 00:36:53,837
I'm not sure that your character reading
is too brilliant, Miss Elizabeth.

712
00:36:54,504 --> 00:36:55,797
Anyway, I must know.

713
00:36:56,131 --> 00:36:58,466
Pray, explain what the two motives
might be, Mr. Darcy?

714
00:36:58,717 --> 00:37:00,427
I have not the smallest objection
to explaining.

715
00:37:01,010 --> 00:37:02,804
Either you have
secret affairs to discuss,

716
00:37:03,138 --> 00:37:04,472
or you are conscious that your figures

717
00:37:04,639 --> 00:37:06,391
show to the greatest advantage
while walking.

718
00:37:07,183 --> 00:37:09,394
In the first case,
I should be completely in your way.

719
00:37:09,769 --> 00:37:12,272
And in the second, I can admire you
much better from where I am.

720
00:37:12,439 --> 00:37:13,648
How perfectly abominable.

721
00:37:13,982 --> 00:37:15,942
What should we do
to punish him, Miss Eliza?

722
00:37:16,443 --> 00:37:17,610
As you know him so well,

723
00:37:17,777 --> 00:37:19,404
I shall leave his punishment to you.

724
00:37:19,988 --> 00:37:21,489
I must go up and see Jane.

725
00:37:22,407 --> 00:37:23,825
- Goodnight.
- Goodnight.

726
00:37:25,660 --> 00:37:27,120
Why disclaim punishment,
Miss Elizabeth,

727
00:37:27,287 --> 00:37:29,581
when you deliberately inflict it
by leaving us so soon?

728
00:37:29,998 --> 00:37:32,167
If my departure
is any punishment, Mr. Darcy,

729
00:37:32,333 --> 00:37:33,418
you are quite right.

730
00:37:33,752 --> 00:37:35,670
My character reading is not too brilliant.

731
00:37:36,671 --> 00:37:38,089
Goodnight, sir.

732
00:37:51,895 --> 00:37:53,813
Charming, my dear.
Charming.

733
00:37:54,272 --> 00:37:55,648
But, uh, that will do.

734
00:37:56,065 --> 00:37:57,859
Uh, Mary. Mary.

735
00:37:58,193 --> 00:37:59,736
That's quite enough, dear.

736
00:38:04,157 --> 00:38:06,701
I'm so glad I went
to fetch Jane myself,

737
00:38:07,202 --> 00:38:09,204
if only to see the look
in Mr. Bingley's eyes

738
00:38:09,370 --> 00:38:11,456
when he assisted her into the carriage.

739
00:38:11,706 --> 00:38:13,666
Oh, Jane, clear, there you are.

740
00:38:15,376 --> 00:38:16,628
Oh, Jane.

741
00:38:17,754 --> 00:38:18,838
Are you feeling better, dearest?

742
00:38:19,005 --> 00:38:20,256
Oh, much better.

743
00:38:21,674 --> 00:38:24,636
Jane, dean
I was talking about dear Mr. Bingley.

744
00:38:24,886 --> 00:38:27,180
What a charming son-in-law he'll be.

745
00:38:27,430 --> 00:38:29,599
Why, he hasn't proposed yet,
has he, Mama?

746
00:38:29,891 --> 00:38:30,975
He will.

747
00:38:31,476 --> 00:38:33,436
I told him some things
about Jane before I left.

748
00:38:33,603 --> 00:38:34,479
Mama.

749
00:38:35,313 --> 00:38:38,441
Only that you have
the loveliest disposition in the world.

750
00:38:39,025 --> 00:38:41,152
And I let drop the fact

751
00:38:41,319 --> 00:38:44,614
that you had declined any number
of marriage proposals.

752
00:38:44,864 --> 00:38:46,115
Oh, Mama, you didn't.

753
00:38:46,407 --> 00:38:48,201
Of course I did, didn't I, Lizzy?

754
00:38:48,910 --> 00:38:50,203
I'm afraid you did, Mama.

755
00:38:50,703 --> 00:38:53,122
And I set
that arrogant Mr. Darcy down, too,

756
00:38:53,289 --> 00:38:54,415
before I left.

757
00:38:55,041 --> 00:38:57,001
Did you hear what I said to him, Lizzy?

758
00:38:57,418 --> 00:38:58,086
Yes.

759
00:38:59,629 --> 00:39:01,130
I heard only too clearly.

760
00:39:02,382 --> 00:39:04,259
Oh, Matthews, is dinner ready?

761
00:39:04,425 --> 00:39:06,469
- Yes, madam.
- Good, I'm starving.

762
00:39:06,636 --> 00:39:07,512
So am I.

763
00:39:07,679 --> 00:39:10,515
How long do we have to wait
for this Collins person?

764
00:39:10,682 --> 00:39:12,725
Matthews, go upstairs

765
00:39:12,892 --> 00:39:15,562
and tell Mr. Collins
we're waiting dinner for him.

766
00:39:15,728 --> 00:39:16,646
Very well, madam.

767
00:39:18,022 --> 00:39:19,315
Insufferable creature.

768
00:39:19,649 --> 00:39:22,652
After all, Mama, it isn't his fault
he's to inherit the estate someday.

769
00:39:24,279 --> 00:39:26,197
To think we have to feed the man

770
00:39:26,364 --> 00:39:28,825
who's waiting to snatch
the bread out of our mouths.

771
00:39:29,158 --> 00:39:30,785
Scheming to rob us
of everything we have

772
00:39:30,952 --> 00:39:32,620
the moment your poor dear father is dead.

773
00:39:33,872 --> 00:39:34,873
I sometimes think, my dear,

774
00:39:35,039 --> 00:39:38,001
you take an unnecessarily gloomy view
about my future.

775
00:39:39,127 --> 00:39:41,254
Well, Papa, tell us what he's really like.

776
00:39:41,421 --> 00:39:43,339
Well, from the little I saw of him

777
00:39:43,506 --> 00:39:45,091
between the front door
and his bedroom,

778
00:39:45,425 --> 00:39:48,136
I should say that he was
an uncommonly fine specimen.

779
00:39:48,887 --> 00:39:50,013
Here he comes.

780
00:39:50,680 --> 00:39:54,100
♪♪

781
00:39:55,685 --> 00:39:56,978
I have heard much, madam,

782
00:39:57,145 --> 00:39:58,688
of the charm
and beauty of your daughters.

783
00:39:59,188 --> 00:40:01,774
Madam, I have heard much
of the charm and beau--

784
00:40:06,738 --> 00:40:09,282
Oh, heavens, what a pudding face.

785
00:40:09,949 --> 00:40:11,868
Perhaps he has beauties of character.

786
00:40:12,035 --> 00:40:13,328
Yes, perhaps, my dear.

787
00:40:13,620 --> 00:40:14,412
But we shall see.

788
00:40:22,503 --> 00:40:23,838
I trust I've not kept you waiting, sir.

789
00:40:24,005 --> 00:40:25,548
Not at all, sir, not at all.

790
00:40:25,882 --> 00:40:28,009
And now let me present you
to Mrs. Bennet and my daughters.

791
00:40:31,971 --> 00:40:34,307
Ahem. Mrs. Bennet, my dear.

792
00:40:35,516 --> 00:40:36,601
Mr. Collins.

793
00:40:37,435 --> 00:40:38,645
How do you do, Mr. Collins?

794
00:40:38,811 --> 00:40:40,647
I trust your journey
was not too fatiguing.

795
00:40:40,897 --> 00:40:42,815
Oh, madam,
the fatigues of the journey

796
00:40:42,982 --> 00:40:44,192
have been melted away

797
00:40:44,359 --> 00:40:46,778
by the warmth
of your gracious hospitality.

798
00:40:46,986 --> 00:40:49,989
My daughters,
Mr. Collins. This is Jane.

799
00:40:50,406 --> 00:40:51,658
This is indeed a privilege.

800
00:40:51,824 --> 00:40:52,450
Kitty.

801
00:40:53,451 --> 00:40:54,285
Another privilege.

802
00:40:54,452 --> 00:40:55,995
Lydia, our youngest.

803
00:40:56,663 --> 00:40:57,455
Mary.

804
00:40:58,873 --> 00:40:59,958
And Elizabeth.

805
00:41:00,500 --> 00:41:02,168
I am quite overpowered.

806
00:41:04,963 --> 00:41:06,089
Madam, I have heard much

807
00:41:06,255 --> 00:41:07,799
of the charm and beauty
of your daughters.

808
00:41:08,049 --> 00:41:12,136
But may I say that their fame
falls far short of the reality.

809
00:41:13,054 --> 00:41:14,097
Unfortunately,

810
00:41:14,263 --> 00:41:16,891
looks are not the only things
that count, Mr. Collins.

811
00:41:17,517 --> 00:41:19,852
Even a beautiful girl must have money.

812
00:41:20,269 --> 00:41:24,065
And things are settled
so very ugly in this family.

813
00:41:24,357 --> 00:41:26,109
Uh, quite so, madam.

814
00:41:26,818 --> 00:41:29,070
Speaking of beauty,
it might interest you to know

815
00:41:29,237 --> 00:41:31,781
that my taste in it was formed
by the expert opinion

816
00:41:31,948 --> 00:41:34,909
of my distinguished patroness,
Lady Catherine de Bourgh.

817
00:41:35,159 --> 00:41:37,078
Mr. Collins,

818
00:41:37,745 --> 00:41:40,456
won't you tell us something about
your distinguished patroness?

819
00:41:40,832 --> 00:41:42,375
Oh, Lady Catherine.

820
00:41:42,709 --> 00:41:44,711
Never in my life, sir,
have I witnessed such behavior

821
00:41:44,877 --> 00:41:45,837
in a person of rank.

822
00:41:46,087 --> 00:41:48,631
Such affability and condescension.

823
00:41:48,840 --> 00:41:49,966
You surprise me, sir.

824
00:41:50,383 --> 00:41:51,843
I had heard of Lady Catherine

825
00:41:52,010 --> 00:41:53,845
as a very proud and haughty woman.

826
00:41:54,178 --> 00:41:56,014
Such is a vulgar opinion, sir.

827
00:41:56,472 --> 00:41:57,348
But I can assure you,

828
00:41:57,515 --> 00:41:59,267
although I act
as her ladyship's librarian,

829
00:41:59,434 --> 00:42:00,810
she has always spoken to me

830
00:42:00,977 --> 00:42:02,353
as she would
to any other gentleman.

831
00:42:02,854 --> 00:42:05,106
Not really.

832
00:42:05,356 --> 00:42:06,983
And now let me give you
a further instance

833
00:42:07,233 --> 00:42:09,527
of her ladyship's
extraordinary condescension.

834
00:42:10,153 --> 00:42:12,530
She advised me to marry
as soon as I could

835
00:42:12,697 --> 00:42:15,241
and actually promised
to call upon my wife.

836
00:42:15,700 --> 00:42:18,619
Provided, of course,
I chose with discretion.

837
00:42:20,705 --> 00:42:21,956
Oh.

838
00:42:22,457 --> 00:42:24,917
Do explain yourself, Mr. Collins.

839
00:42:25,084 --> 00:42:26,044
As you are aware, madam,

840
00:42:26,419 --> 00:42:30,214
when a certain melancholy event occurs

841
00:42:30,673 --> 00:42:34,302
I shall be the involuntary means
of disinheriting your daughters.

842
00:42:34,469 --> 00:42:35,678
I have long felt it my duty

843
00:42:35,845 --> 00:42:37,930
to make such reparation
as was in my power.

844
00:42:38,389 --> 00:42:40,808
I quite understand, Mr. Collins.

845
00:42:40,975 --> 00:42:43,561
Unfortunately, I cannot make amends
to more than one.

846
00:42:44,187 --> 00:42:46,773
The difficulty now is one of, uh, choice.

847
00:42:46,939 --> 00:42:49,275
♪♪

848
00:42:53,071 --> 00:42:53,946
Mm.

849
00:42:57,575 --> 00:42:58,826
I think perhaps...

850
00:43:01,412 --> 00:43:01,996
Miss Jane.

851
00:43:04,540 --> 00:43:06,834
I'm sorry to disappoint you,
Mr. Collins,

852
00:43:07,418 --> 00:43:10,088
but Jane is practically engaged.

853
00:43:10,505 --> 00:43:13,758
Uh, we are expecting
a proposal any moment now.

854
00:43:14,300 --> 00:43:15,218
Well, then,

855
00:43:15,843 --> 00:43:16,427
Miss Elizabeth.

856
00:43:17,136 --> 00:43:19,180
That Is, If there's no prior claim.

857
00:43:19,347 --> 00:43:20,223
Oh, none.

858
00:43:20,765 --> 00:43:22,475
None that we know of.

859
00:43:22,642 --> 00:43:23,976
Dinner is served, madam.

860
00:43:24,227 --> 00:43:26,270
And now, my dear Mr. Collins,

861
00:43:26,646 --> 00:43:28,564
shall we adjourn to the dining room?

862
00:43:39,784 --> 00:43:42,453
♪♪

863
00:44:02,140 --> 00:44:04,475
Pray, taste the cold punch, Mr. Darcy.

864
00:44:04,642 --> 00:44:06,310
And see if it's properly blended.

865
00:44:10,940 --> 00:44:11,732
ExceHent

866
00:44:11,899 --> 00:44:13,192
Have it served at once, Robert.

867
00:44:13,359 --> 00:44:14,443
Very well, madam.

868
00:44:16,654 --> 00:44:19,615
Entertaining the rustics
is not as difficult as I'd feared.

869
00:44:20,158 --> 00:44:23,953
Any simple childish game
seems to amuse them excessively.

870
00:44:27,456 --> 00:44:28,374
Good for you, Sir William.

871
00:44:39,260 --> 00:44:41,220
Stop, stop, I'm going to fall!

872
00:44:41,512 --> 00:44:42,722
Give another pull, Denny.

873
00:44:47,476 --> 00:44:48,686
Miss Elizabeth.

874
00:44:52,148 --> 00:44:53,274
Elizabeth.

875
00:44:56,110 --> 00:44:57,403
Miss Elizabeth.

876
00:45:00,239 --> 00:45:01,324
Miss Elizabeth.

877
00:45:06,746 --> 00:45:07,705
Miss Elizabeth.

878
00:45:10,208 --> 00:45:11,125
Miss Elizabeth.

879
00:45:12,710 --> 00:45:13,753
Miss Elizabeth.

880
00:45:14,170 --> 00:45:16,839
Why, I say, sir. Sir.
I beg your pardon, sir.

881
00:45:17,673 --> 00:45:20,092
Do you--? Do you happen
to know Miss Elizabeth Bennet?

882
00:45:20,468 --> 00:45:21,135
I do, sir.

883
00:45:21,552 --> 00:45:23,638
Has she--?
Has she passed this way, may I ask?

884
00:45:26,933 --> 00:45:29,185
No, sir, she has not passed this spot.

885
00:45:30,061 --> 00:45:32,355
I suggest you try
the other side of the lake, sir.

886
00:45:32,855 --> 00:45:33,773
I'm obliged to you, sir.

887
00:45:38,986 --> 00:45:39,654
All clear.

888
00:45:43,199 --> 00:45:44,575
Thank you, Mr. Darcy.

889
00:45:44,992 --> 00:45:47,203
You've saved me from
one of the most dangerous bores

890
00:45:47,370 --> 00:45:48,120
in the country.

891
00:45:48,746 --> 00:45:49,622
If the dragon returns,

892
00:45:49,789 --> 00:45:51,249
Saint George Will know
how to deal with him.

893
00:45:51,916 --> 00:45:54,335
Meanwhile, what do you say
to a little target practice?

894
00:45:54,669 --> 00:45:55,461
Very well.

895
00:46:03,719 --> 00:46:05,888
Are you a good shot
with a bow and arrow, Mr. Darcy?

896
00:46:06,055 --> 00:46:07,348
Tolerable.

897
00:46:07,974 --> 00:46:09,308
Only tolerable?

898
00:46:09,642 --> 00:46:11,352
Well, it's a fine old sport.

899
00:46:11,769 --> 00:46:13,354
And one in which even a young lady

900
00:46:13,521 --> 00:46:14,772
can become proficient.

901
00:46:15,523 --> 00:46:16,524
So I've heard.

902
00:46:16,774 --> 00:46:18,067
At a short range, of course.

903
00:46:18,317 --> 00:46:19,402
And with a light bow.

904
00:46:24,699 --> 00:46:26,534
Hm. What a bad shot.

905
00:46:27,285 --> 00:46:28,995
Oh, on the contrary, well done.

906
00:46:30,830 --> 00:46:31,872
Well, it might have been worse.

907
00:46:32,290 --> 00:46:33,165
Now it's your turn.

908
00:46:33,916 --> 00:46:36,127
Now, the bow in the left hand.

909
00:46:36,711 --> 00:46:37,295
This way.

910
00:46:38,629 --> 00:46:41,340
So the arrow goes like this.

911
00:46:43,217 --> 00:46:45,303
That's right. Now, these,
uh, three fingers.

912
00:46:45,469 --> 00:46:47,388
So one, two, three.

913
00:46:47,972 --> 00:46:50,641
Now, the left arm straight.
Straight, straight, straight.

914
00:46:51,058 --> 00:46:53,060
Now turn sideways toward the target.

915
00:46:53,477 --> 00:46:54,895
Aim for the bull's-eye.

916
00:46:55,855 --> 00:46:56,856
That's right.

917
00:47:02,194 --> 00:47:03,029
Bull's-eye.

918
00:47:12,788 --> 00:47:14,081
And another bull's-eye.

919
00:47:15,624 --> 00:47:17,710
Next time I talk
to a young lady about archery,

920
00:47:17,877 --> 00:47:19,128
I won't be so patronizing.

921
00:47:22,965 --> 00:47:25,009
Yes, thank you for the lesson.

922
00:47:27,094 --> 00:47:28,637
Thank you for taking it so well.

923
00:47:28,888 --> 00:47:31,015
Most men would have been
offended, and rightly.

924
00:47:31,557 --> 00:47:32,558
Would you mind telling me,
Miss Bennet,

925
00:47:32,725 --> 00:47:34,310
why you're so determined
to offend me?

926
00:47:34,894 --> 00:47:37,438
Is that possible, Mr. Darcy?
I thought you were invulnerable.

927
00:47:38,022 --> 00:47:40,649
You always look so... impassive.

928
00:47:41,525 --> 00:47:42,985
Perhaps you don't laugh enough.

929
00:47:43,235 --> 00:47:45,988
You may be right.
But you haven't answered my question.

930
00:47:46,155 --> 00:47:47,156
Mr. Darcy.

931
00:47:48,157 --> 00:47:49,909
You promised to give me
a lesson with the darts.

932
00:47:50,076 --> 00:47:51,911
I give no more instructions
to young ladies.

933
00:47:52,411 --> 00:47:53,829
Hereafter,
they give Instructions to me.

934
00:47:54,121 --> 00:47:54,914
What do you say, Miss Bingley?

935
00:47:55,081 --> 00:47:57,416
Miss Elizabeth thinks
I do not laugh enough.

936
00:47:57,750 --> 00:48:00,127
I should be sorry to see
you laugh more than you do.

937
00:48:00,378 --> 00:48:04,048
To me there's something so unrefined
about excessive laughter.

938
00:48:04,215 --> 00:48:05,674
Oh, if you want to be really refined,

939
00:48:05,841 --> 00:48:06,759
you have to be dead.

940
00:48:07,093 --> 00:48:09,387
There's no one
as dignified as a mummy.

941
00:48:14,308 --> 00:48:16,394
And now may I ask you
a question, Mr. Darcy?

942
00:48:16,560 --> 00:48:17,395
By all means.

943
00:48:18,854 --> 00:48:19,522
What would you think of a man

944
00:48:19,688 --> 00:48:21,941
who had everything
the world has to offer?

945
00:48:22,817 --> 00:48:24,485
Birth, breeding, wealth.

946
00:48:25,361 --> 00:48:26,195
Good looks.

947
00:48:27,238 --> 00:48:29,490
Even charm when he chose to exercise it.

948
00:48:30,699 --> 00:48:33,160
What would be your opinion
of a man with such gifts

949
00:48:33,828 --> 00:48:36,038
who refused to accept
an introduction to another man

950
00:48:36,205 --> 00:48:37,706
who was poor
and of no consequence?

951
00:48:39,291 --> 00:48:40,459
I should reserve my opinion

952
00:48:40,626 --> 00:48:43,045
until I knew the circumstances
of the particular case.

953
00:48:44,338 --> 00:48:46,632
And do you suppose the gentleman
would reveal those circumstances

954
00:48:46,799 --> 00:48:47,591
if he were asked?

955
00:48:47,758 --> 00:48:48,551
No.

956
00:48:49,760 --> 00:48:52,346
A gentleman does not
have to explain his actions.

957
00:48:53,097 --> 00:48:56,058
He expects people to give him credit

958
00:48:56,225 --> 00:48:59,562
for being a man of honor and integrity.

959
00:49:01,105 --> 00:49:03,732
And now if you will excuse me,
I will retrieve the arrows.

960
00:49:12,074 --> 00:49:12,992
Miss Eliza.

961
00:49:15,327 --> 00:49:16,704
May I warn you as a friend

962
00:49:16,871 --> 00:49:19,165
not to take George Wickham too seriously.

963
00:49:20,374 --> 00:49:23,669
Oh. You knew I referred to Mr. Wickham?

964
00:49:23,919 --> 00:49:24,753
Of course.

965
00:49:24,920 --> 00:49:26,213
I know that he goes about saying

966
00:49:26,380 --> 00:49:28,299
that he's been ill-used by Mr. Darcy.

967
00:49:28,716 --> 00:49:30,301
While I'm ignorant of the particulars,

968
00:49:30,468 --> 00:49:32,386
I know that what he says is not true.

969
00:49:32,803 --> 00:49:34,763
How clever of you,
my dear Miss Bingley,

970
00:49:35,014 --> 00:49:37,141
to know something
of which you are ignorant.

971
00:49:37,516 --> 00:49:40,144
I've always found
George Wickham to be a man

972
00:49:40,311 --> 00:49:42,146
of absolutely no principle.

973
00:49:42,897 --> 00:49:45,858
But, though, what can you expect
of one of his low descent?

974
00:49:46,108 --> 00:49:48,194
I will tell you exactly what I expect.

975
00:49:48,903 --> 00:49:53,699
Kindness, honor, generosity, truthfulness.

976
00:49:54,575 --> 00:49:56,368
And I might add that I expect
precisely the same

977
00:49:56,535 --> 00:49:58,078
from persons of high descent.

978
00:50:02,333 --> 00:50:05,002
Oh, Mr. Darcy,
Miss Bingley is eager for her lesson.

979
00:50:05,336 --> 00:50:06,921
I hope you will enjoy it, Miss Bingley,

980
00:50:07,922 --> 00:50:09,715
and that you will learn
to direct your darts

981
00:50:10,466 --> 00:50:11,634
with greater accuracy.

982
00:50:13,427 --> 00:50:15,346
Such insolence and bad manners.

983
00:50:17,181 --> 00:50:19,975
Pray, what do you think
of her now, Mr. Darcy?

984
00:50:22,019 --> 00:50:24,271
I think she handles
a bow and arrow superbly.

985
00:50:26,232 --> 00:50:33,531
