987
00:50:41,038 --> 00:50:47,962
♪ My Mary's asleep
by thy murmuring stream ♪

988
00:50:48,295 --> 00:50:53,133
♪ Flow gently, sweet Afton ♪

989
00:50:53,425 --> 00:50:57,263
♪ Disturb not her dream ♪

990
00:50:57,555 --> 00:51:04,228
♪ Thou stock-dove whose echo
resounds from the hill ♪

991
00:51:04,562 --> 00:51:07,815
♪ Ye wild whistling blackbirds ♪

992
00:51:08,190 --> 00:51:12,403
♪ In yon thorny dell ♪

993
00:51:12,570 --> 00:51:14,655
♪ Thou... ♪

994
00:51:14,822 --> 00:51:17,992
♪ Green-crested lapwing ♪

995
00:51:18,200 --> 00:51:21,787
♪ Thy screaming forbear ♪

996
00:51:21,954 --> 00:51:27,835
♪ I charge you, disturb not ♪

997
00:51:28,085 --> 00:51:33,382
♪ My slumbering fair ♪

998
00:51:36,468 --> 00:51:37,970
Charming, Miss Mary. Charming.

999
00:51:38,137 --> 00:51:40,598
Won't you favor us
with another selection?

1000
00:51:41,473 --> 00:51:43,267
Well, if you really insist.

1001
00:51:43,434 --> 00:51:44,768
Papa, you must make her stop.

1002
00:51:44,935 --> 00:51:46,103
All right, dear. Shh, shh.

1003
00:51:51,275 --> 00:51:53,777
Very good, Mary, dear.
Very good.

1004
00:51:53,944 --> 00:51:56,280
But, Papa, this is another song.

1005
00:51:56,447 --> 00:51:57,906
Eh? Oh.

1006
00:51:58,073 --> 00:51:59,116
Oh, never mind, my dear.

1007
00:51:59,283 --> 00:52:00,951
You've delighted us quite long enough.

1008
00:52:01,660 --> 00:52:02,995
Give the other young ladies a chance

1009
00:52:03,162 --> 00:52:04,830
to make exhibitions of themselves.

1010
00:52:09,209 --> 00:52:11,712
Ah, Miss Elizabeth,
allow me to congratulate you.

1011
00:52:12,212 --> 00:52:12,838
On what?

1012
00:52:13,005 --> 00:52:14,506
On your family, of course.

1013
00:52:15,049 --> 00:52:16,383
A talented young singer.

1014
00:52:16,634 --> 00:52:18,844
A cousin distinguished
for his wit and learning.

1015
00:52:19,219 --> 00:52:21,722
Two young sisters with a toast
of the officer's mess.

1016
00:52:22,181 --> 00:52:24,933
A mother who's
a most diverting conversationalist.

1017
00:52:25,184 --> 00:52:27,186
To say nothing of your own dexterity

1018
00:52:27,353 --> 00:52:28,520
with bow and arrow.

1019
00:52:29,146 --> 00:52:31,607
Such an interesting,
accomplished family.

1020
00:52:57,091 --> 00:52:57,925
Miss Elizabeth,

1021
00:52:58,092 --> 00:53:00,219
I'm afraid something
has happened to disturb you.

1022
00:53:01,637 --> 00:53:02,846
Nothing at all, thank you.

1023
00:53:04,181 --> 00:53:05,599
Are you sure
there's nothing I can do?

1024
00:53:08,102 --> 00:53:10,145
You can leave me to make
a fool of myself...

1025
00:53:10,312 --> 00:53:10,938
alone,

1026
00:53:11,855 --> 00:53:12,731
if you don't mind.

1027
00:53:13,315 --> 00:53:15,776
It's hard to imagine you
making a fool of yourself.

1028
00:53:15,943 --> 00:53:17,403
Well, I do frequently.

1029
00:53:18,570 --> 00:53:20,239
Isn't that what I was doing
this afternoon?

1030
00:53:20,906 --> 00:53:23,492
I had rather admired what you did
this afternoon, Miss Elizabeth.

1031
00:53:24,076 --> 00:53:25,911
Your resentment of what
you believe to be an injustice

1032
00:53:26,078 --> 00:53:27,830
showed courage and loyalty.

1033
00:53:28,747 --> 00:53:30,249
I could wish that
I might possess a friend

1034
00:53:30,416 --> 00:53:33,293
who would defend me as ably as
Mr. Wickham was defended today.

1035
00:53:35,254 --> 00:53:37,297
You're very puzzling, Mr. Darcy.

1036
00:53:38,465 --> 00:53:42,344
At this moment, it's difficult
to believe that you're so... proud.

1037
00:53:43,554 --> 00:53:46,807
At this moment, it's difficult to believe
that you are so prejudiced.

1038
00:53:49,101 --> 00:53:51,729
Shall we not call quits
and start again?

1039
00:53:55,607 --> 00:53:56,900
Oh, Lizzy,
Mr. Bingley Is going to arrange

1040
00:53:57,067 --> 00:53:58,402
a Highland Reel for us.
Come along.

1041
00:53:58,569 --> 00:53:59,653
Yes, please do.

1042
00:54:02,823 --> 00:54:03,615
Shall we?

1043
00:54:07,286 --> 00:54:09,788
I must insist that you look
at Jane and Mr. Bingley.

1044
00:54:10,205 --> 00:54:12,666
The dear boy makes
no secret of his admiration.

1045
00:54:12,958 --> 00:54:14,626
And the week she was "I
here at Netherfield

1046
00:54:14,793 --> 00:54:16,295
completed the conquest.

1047
00:54:16,754 --> 00:54:17,755
I knew it would.

1048
00:54:17,921 --> 00:54:20,716
Wasn't it clever of me
to send her over in the rain?

1049
00:54:20,966 --> 00:54:22,593
And of course,
dear Jane will see

1050
00:54:22,760 --> 00:54:24,178
that the other girls have
an opportunity

1051
00:54:24,344 --> 00:54:27,264
of meeting all sorts of
rich young men. Mm.

1052
00:54:29,224 --> 00:54:31,518
I told you not to drink
so much punch, Kitty.

1053
00:54:31,810 --> 00:54:33,103
You know,
you're quite tipsy.

1054
00:54:33,270 --> 00:54:34,104
I am not.

1055
00:54:35,105 --> 00:54:36,482
Hold it! Hold up.

1056
00:54:37,733 --> 00:54:38,400
Stupid step.

1057
00:54:38,567 --> 00:54:40,944
Hello, Lizzy. Hello, Mr. Darcy.

1058
00:54:41,111 --> 00:54:43,781
Look at Kitty.
She's drunk as a lord.

1059
00:54:44,031 --> 00:54:45,282
I am not.

1060
00:54:50,829 --> 00:54:51,830
Ladies and gentlemen,

1061
00:54:52,289 --> 00:54:53,499
if you will choose your partners,

1062
00:54:53,665 --> 00:54:54,792
we'll all have a Highland Reel.

1063
00:54:59,296 --> 00:55:01,590
Such a gay dance, the reel.

1064
00:55:03,217 --> 00:55:04,802
Won't you allow me to take you in?

1065
00:55:04,968 --> 00:55:06,678
I'm sure there must be many young men

1066
00:55:06,845 --> 00:55:08,680
who are eager to dance it with you.

1067
00:55:09,348 --> 00:55:12,810
Ah, Miss Elizabeth, do you recall?
The first dance?

1068
00:55:13,727 --> 00:55:16,313
Ah, sir, will you please accept
the humble apology

1069
00:55:16,480 --> 00:55:18,190
of one who's only just learned
you are the nephew

1070
00:55:18,357 --> 00:55:20,901
of my esteemed patroness,
Lady Catherine de Bourgh?

1071
00:55:21,652 --> 00:55:23,237
- Indeed.
- You will be happy to learn

1072
00:55:23,403 --> 00:55:24,696
that when I left her
two weeks ago,

1073
00:55:24,863 --> 00:55:27,407
your gracious aunt was
enjoying the best of health.

1074
00:55:34,957 --> 00:55:37,584
What graciousness.
What condescension.

1075
00:55:38,043 --> 00:55:39,044
What snobbery.

1076
00:55:40,963 --> 00:55:42,881
Miss Eliza,
please remember that Mr. Darcy

1077
00:55:43,048 --> 00:55:44,800
is the nephew
of Lady Catherine de Bourgh.

1078
00:55:45,133 --> 00:55:46,385
I do, Mr. Collins.

1079
00:55:46,802 --> 00:55:48,887
I also remember that Mr. Darcy
is the sort of person

1080
00:55:49,054 --> 00:55:50,347
who offers his friendship...

1081
00:55:50,848 --> 00:55:54,017
and then at the first test
of loyalty, withdraws it.

1082
00:55:55,727 --> 00:55:56,812
Shall we go inside?

1083
00:55:56,979 --> 00:55:57,938
Of course.

1084
00:56:31,889 --> 00:56:35,058
♪♪

1085
00:56:48,822 --> 00:56:50,866
Kitty, would you stop moving about?

1086
00:57:03,462 --> 00:57:07,174
Oh, little fellow,
please don't cry.

1087
00:57:15,557 --> 00:57:16,600
Oh, there's Lizzy.

1088
00:57:21,730 --> 00:57:22,898
Lizzy. Lizzy.

1089
00:57:23,398 --> 00:57:24,775
Come and see how pretty this is.

1090
00:57:28,570 --> 00:57:30,072
Oh, that's charming, Kitty.

1091
00:57:30,447 --> 00:57:31,782
What a pity
you didn't make it bigger.

1092
00:57:32,115 --> 00:57:33,367
We could have put it 'round Mr. Collins

1093
00:57:33,533 --> 00:57:34,952
when he grows
too much of a bore.

1094
00:57:35,118 --> 00:57:38,080
Lizzy, how could you speak like that
about your charming cousin?

1095
00:57:38,246 --> 00:57:39,748
- Oh, but he's--
- There you are, Mrs. Bennet.

1096
00:57:39,915 --> 00:57:42,793
Oh! Oh, Mr. Collins,
we were just talking about you.

1097
00:57:43,085 --> 00:57:45,337
I thought you were walking
with Jane, Mr. Collins.

1098
00:57:45,504 --> 00:57:46,755
I left Miss Jane in the garden

1099
00:57:46,922 --> 00:57:48,298
with Miss Charlotte
and the new puppies.

1100
00:57:48,757 --> 00:57:49,675
I think I'll join them.

1101
00:57:49,841 --> 00:57:51,093
One moment please,
Miss Elizabeth.

1102
00:57:51,551 --> 00:57:53,387
Uh, madam,
may I have the permission

1103
00:57:53,553 --> 00:57:55,764
to solicit a private interview
with your daughter, Elizabeth?

1104
00:57:56,098 --> 00:57:56,765
Private?

1105
00:57:57,099 --> 00:57:58,976
Well, I, uh, really--

1106
00:57:59,393 --> 00:58:00,936
Uh, yes, indeed.

1107
00:58:01,478 --> 00:58:03,480
Lizzy will be only too happy.

1108
00:58:05,357 --> 00:58:07,651
Come, Kitty, I want you upstairs.

1109
00:58:08,151 --> 00:58:09,486
Why do you keep winking, Mama?

1110
00:58:09,653 --> 00:58:10,237
Winking?

1111
00:58:10,404 --> 00:58:12,406
Why, I wasn't winking.

1112
00:58:12,572 --> 00:58:13,407
But you were, Mama.

1113
00:58:13,573 --> 00:58:15,784
Don't contradict. Come, Kitty.

1114
00:58:15,951 --> 00:58:18,537
But Mr. Collins could have
nothing private to say to me.

1115
00:58:18,704 --> 00:58:19,663
No nonsense, Lizzy.

1116
00:58:20,163 --> 00:58:22,416
Lizzy, I desire you
to stay where you are.

1117
00:58:22,582 --> 00:58:23,500
Come, Kitty.

1118
00:58:24,042 --> 00:58:25,419
Mr. Collins.

1119
00:58:27,004 --> 00:58:28,171
Come along, Kitty.

1120
00:58:35,637 --> 00:58:37,222
Believe me,
my dear Miss Elizabeth,

1121
00:58:37,472 --> 00:58:39,808
your modesty does you
no disservice in my eyes.

1122
00:58:39,975 --> 00:58:42,602
Oh, wait. You can hardly doubt
the purport of my discourse.

1123
00:58:42,769 --> 00:58:44,980
My intentions have been
too marked to be mistaken.

1124
00:58:46,189 --> 00:58:47,774
I have singled you out

1125
00:58:47,941 --> 00:58:49,776
as the companion
of my future life.

1126
00:58:50,193 --> 00:58:52,362
Oh, please,
before my feelings run away with me,

1127
00:58:52,529 --> 00:58:54,197
let me state my reasons for marrying.

1128
00:58:55,115 --> 00:58:57,451
First, I regard it as the duty
of every gentleman

1129
00:58:57,617 --> 00:58:59,161
in easy circumstances
to marry.

1130
00:58:59,453 --> 00:59:01,872
Secondly, I'm convinced it will
add greatly to my happiness.

1131
00:59:02,122 --> 00:59:03,790
And thirdly,
I think it only right

1132
00:59:03,957 --> 00:59:05,876
that since I am to inherit
your father's estate,

1133
00:59:06,043 --> 00:59:07,586
I should try and
keep it in the family.

1134
00:59:07,753 --> 00:59:09,713
And fourthly,
it is the particular wish

1135
00:59:09,880 --> 00:59:11,006
of that very noble lady

1136
00:59:11,173 --> 00:59:12,841
whom I have the honor
to call my patroness,

1137
00:59:13,258 --> 00:59:14,634
Lady Catherine de Bourgh.

1138
00:59:15,969 --> 00:59:17,971
These, dear Miss Elizabeth,
are my motives.

1139
00:59:18,346 --> 00:59:20,557
And now, nothing remains
but to me to assure you

1140
00:59:20,724 --> 00:59:22,267
of the violence of my affection.

1141
00:59:22,934 --> 00:59:24,519
Why, you are too hasty, sir.

1142
00:59:24,978 --> 00:59:26,855
You forget that
I have made no answer.

1143
00:59:27,731 --> 00:59:29,149
Let me do so at once.

1144
00:59:30,275 --> 00:59:33,070
I appreciate the honor of your proposal.

1145
00:59:33,236 --> 00:59:34,821
Oh, my dear Miss Elizabeth.

1146
00:59:34,988 --> 00:59:36,531
But I must decline with thanks.

1147
00:59:36,740 --> 00:59:38,200
I understand,
my dear Miss Elizabeth,

1148
00:59:38,366 --> 00:59:39,826
that it is a delicate
and charming custom

1149
00:59:39,993 --> 00:59:41,661
of young ladies to say no
when they mean yes,

1150
00:59:41,828 --> 00:59:43,205
even to three and four refusals.

1151
00:59:43,455 --> 00:59:44,790
I am therefore
by no means discouraged

1152
00:59:44,956 --> 00:59:46,374
- by what you have said.
- Upon my word, sir,

1153
00:59:46,541 --> 00:59:47,667
you are very hard to discourage.

1154
00:59:47,834 --> 00:59:48,960
- Ah, my dear--
- Mr. Collins,

1155
00:59:49,127 --> 00:59:51,338
you have made your offer.
I have refused it.

1156
00:59:51,588 --> 00:59:53,548
You can therefore take
possession of this estate

1157
00:59:53,715 --> 00:59:56,051
without the least compunction
or self-reproach

1158
00:59:56,301 --> 00:59:57,677
whenever it falls to you.

1159
00:59:58,678 --> 01:00:00,430
So let's regard the incident as closed.

1160
01:00:00,597 --> 01:00:01,556
But, my dear Miss Elizabeth,

1161
01:00:01,723 --> 01:00:03,100
I think you ought to take
into consideration

1162
01:00:03,266 --> 01:00:05,477
that in spite of your loveliness
and amiable qualifications,

1163
01:00:05,644 --> 01:00:08,105
you are practically penniless.
And it is by no means certain

1164
01:00:08,271 --> 01:00:10,107
that another offer of marriage
may ever be made you.

1165
01:00:10,273 --> 01:00:11,024
Well, by all--

1166
01:00:11,191 --> 01:00:13,318
So I must therefore
attribute your refusal of me

1167
01:00:13,485 --> 01:00:15,320
to your wish of increasing
my love by suspense.

1168
01:00:15,821 --> 01:00:16,822
Which is, I am told,

1169
01:00:16,988 --> 01:00:18,907
the usual practice
of elegant females.

1170
01:00:19,199 --> 01:00:22,035
Believe me, sir, I am not
one of those elegant females

1171
01:00:22,202 --> 01:00:24,496
who takes pleasure
in tormenting a respectable man.

1172
01:00:24,830 --> 01:00:26,289
I am a rational creature,

1173
01:00:26,456 --> 01:00:27,916
speaking the truth
from her heart.

1174
01:00:28,083 --> 01:00:30,252
Ah, thank you.
You make me feel certain

1175
01:00:30,418 --> 01:00:31,545
that when my proposal is sanctioned

1176
01:00:31,711 --> 01:00:32,879
by the authority of your parents,

1177
01:00:33,046 --> 01:00:35,048
- you will plainly say yes.
- Oh!

1178
01:00:41,304 --> 01:00:42,097
Oh, Papa.

1179
01:00:42,264 --> 01:00:43,056
- What is it?
- Lizzy!

1180
01:00:43,557 --> 01:00:45,100
Oh, Papa, dear, I must tell you.

1181
01:00:45,267 --> 01:00:46,226
Come in the library.

1182
01:00:46,935 --> 01:00:48,145
Lizzy, what--?

1183
01:00:48,770 --> 01:00:49,396
Oh.

1184
01:00:56,820 --> 01:00:59,614
Oh, my dear future son-in-law.

1185
01:00:59,906 --> 01:01:01,867
Let me be the first to wish you joy.

1186
01:01:02,033 --> 01:01:02,742
Thank you, madam.

1187
01:01:02,909 --> 01:01:04,786
Indeed, I trust I have
every reason for joy.

1188
01:01:05,120 --> 01:01:06,746
Of course,
I know that my cousin's refusal

1189
01:01:06,913 --> 01:01:09,082
naturally springs
from her bashful modesty.

1190
01:01:09,249 --> 01:01:10,000
Refusal?

1191
01:01:10,542 --> 01:01:12,878
With Lizzy, that does not mean
bashful modesty.

1192
01:01:13,044 --> 01:01:14,337
But never mind, Mr. Collins.

1193
01:01:14,504 --> 01:01:15,964
She's a very foolish, headstrong girl

1194
01:01:16,131 --> 01:01:17,257
and does not know her own interest.

1195
01:01:17,424 --> 01:01:20,010
Foolish? Headstrong? Dear me.

1196
01:01:20,510 --> 01:01:22,512
Those failings will not make her
a very desirable wife.

1197
01:01:22,679 --> 01:01:24,472
Oh, but you quite misunderstand,
Mr. Collins.

1198
01:01:24,723 --> 01:01:27,058
Lizzy is only headstrong
in matters such as these.

1199
01:01:27,392 --> 01:01:28,810
Uh--you just wait, Mr. Collins.

1200
01:01:28,977 --> 01:01:30,770
Mr. Bennet always brings her to reason.

1201
01:01:32,189 --> 01:01:34,983
Headstrong? Foolish? Dear me.

1202
01:01:35,483 --> 01:01:37,110
Lady Catherine will never approve.

1203
01:01:38,612 --> 01:01:41,823
Mr. Bennet. Mr. Bennet,
we are all in an uproar.

1204
01:01:42,157 --> 01:01:44,075
Lizzy has refused to marry Mr. Collins.

1205
01:01:44,367 --> 01:01:46,578
You must force her
to change her mind immediately,

1206
01:01:47,120 --> 01:01:48,496
or he'll change his and not have her.

1207
01:01:48,663 --> 01:01:49,497
In which event, my dear,

1208
01:01:49,664 --> 01:01:51,708
the matter will be settled
at a satisfaction of both.

1209
01:01:51,875 --> 01:01:53,084
Please be serious.
Speak to her.

1210
01:01:53,251 --> 01:01:55,712
Tell her you insist upon her marrying him.

1211
01:01:57,088 --> 01:01:58,340
- Lizzy.
- Yes, Papa?

1212
01:01:58,506 --> 01:02:00,508
Your mother insists
that you accept Mr. Collins.

1213
01:02:00,675 --> 01:02:01,509
Isn't that 50, Mrs. Bennet?

1214
01:02:01,676 --> 01:02:03,762
Or else I shall never see her again.

1215
01:02:04,262 --> 01:02:06,598
An unhappy alternative
is before you, Elizabeth.

1216
01:02:07,182 --> 01:02:08,642
Your mother will never see you again

1217
01:02:08,808 --> 01:02:10,852
if you do not marry Mr. Collins.

1218
01:02:11,895 --> 01:02:13,813
And I will never see you again if you do.

1219
01:02:14,856 --> 01:02:15,649
Dear Papa.

1220
01:02:18,193 --> 01:02:20,070
♪♪

1221
01:02:24,074 --> 01:02:26,826
But, Mama,
you've no right to open Jane's letter.

1222
01:02:27,077 --> 01:02:29,246
It's against the principles
of Magna Carta.

1223
01:02:29,663 --> 01:02:31,581
No right to open
my own daughter's letters?

1224
01:02:31,748 --> 01:02:33,625
I--I never heard of such a thing.

1225
01:02:33,792 --> 01:02:35,877
Besides, dear Jane need never know.

1226
01:02:36,044 --> 01:02:38,797
Oh, I'm sure it's the proposal.

1227
01:02:39,256 --> 01:02:41,299
I can feel it in my bones.

1228
01:02:42,384 --> 01:02:43,510
"My dearest Jane..."

1229
01:02:47,138 --> 01:02:48,265
Oh.

1230
01:02:49,307 --> 01:02:50,183
Oh!

1231
01:02:51,351 --> 01:02:53,770
She's lost him.
She's lost him!

1232
01:02:54,604 --> 01:02:56,815
We've lost two of them!

1233
01:02:57,148 --> 01:02:58,233
What's lost, Mama?

1234
01:02:58,900 --> 01:02:59,526
Your husbands.

1235
01:03:00,860 --> 01:03:01,945
You've thrown away Mr. Collins,

1236
01:03:02,112 --> 01:03:03,989
and now here's Jane losing Mr. Bingley.

1237
01:03:04,155 --> 01:03:05,573
Well, what are you talking about, Mama?

1238
01:03:06,116 --> 01:03:06,700
Read that.

1239
01:03:06,866 --> 01:03:08,034
No, no, it belongs to Jane.

1240
01:03:08,201 --> 01:03:09,703
I--I thought it was a declaration,

1241
01:03:09,869 --> 01:03:10,704
so I opened it.

1242
01:03:10,870 --> 01:03:12,998
They've gone.
They've gone to London.

1243
01:03:13,164 --> 01:03:14,416
Well, who's gone to London?

1244
01:03:14,582 --> 01:03:17,585
Mr. Bingley, his sister, and Mr. Darcy.

1245
01:03:17,752 --> 01:03:20,714
They've packed up and
left without even saying goodbye.

1246
01:03:21,047 --> 01:03:21,673
Read it.

1247
01:03:22,007 --> 01:03:23,967
Read what Miss Bingley has to say.

1248
01:03:25,218 --> 01:03:26,052
Lizzy.

1249
01:03:28,638 --> 01:03:31,725
Well, nobody's going to miss that high
and mighty Mr. Darcy.

1250
01:03:32,142 --> 01:03:33,768
Oh, do be quiet, Lydia.

1251
01:03:34,019 --> 01:03:36,146
Without a sign of a proposal.

1252
01:03:36,604 --> 01:03:39,107
After his compromising attentions to Jane.

1253
01:03:39,274 --> 01:03:41,651
Mama, he did not compromise Jane.

1254
01:03:41,818 --> 01:03:44,279
He is a very undeserving young man.

1255
01:03:44,446 --> 01:03:47,115
My only comfort is
she'll die of a broken heart.

1256
01:03:47,282 --> 01:03:48,450
Then he'll be sorry.

1257
01:03:50,994 --> 01:03:51,911
Mr. Wickham.

1258
01:03:52,078 --> 01:03:53,079
Oh, how do you do, Mr. Wickham?

1259
01:03:53,246 --> 01:03:54,080
You'll excuse me, won't you?

1260
01:03:54,247 --> 01:03:55,999
I'm much too upset
to talk to anyone.

1261
01:03:56,166 --> 01:03:57,125
Lizzy will give you tea.

1262
01:03:57,375 --> 01:03:59,044
Oh, I'm sorry
you're disturbed, madam.

1263
01:03:59,294 --> 01:04:00,628
My visit is ill-timed, I'm afraid.

1264
01:04:00,795 --> 01:04:02,047
No, no. Mama has just heard

1265
01:04:02,213 --> 01:04:04,257
some rather surprising news,
that's all.

1266
01:04:04,424 --> 01:04:05,759
She'll be herself again directly.

1267
01:04:06,092 --> 01:04:08,219
I heard some surprising news
myself this morning.

1268
01:04:08,386 --> 01:04:09,596
- Really?
- Yes.

1269
01:04:10,305 --> 01:04:11,389
But it was good news.

1270
01:04:11,806 --> 01:04:12,390
Yes?

1271
01:04:12,807 --> 01:04:13,975
Good news, indeed.

1272
01:04:15,101 --> 01:04:15,810
Well?

1273
01:04:16,061 --> 01:04:17,520
Mr. Darcy has left Netherfield.

1274
01:04:20,648 --> 01:04:21,733
So I hear.

1275
01:04:22,650 --> 01:04:25,445
Well, uh, don't you want
to know why he went?

1276
01:04:26,237 --> 01:04:28,031
I should like very much to know.

1277
01:04:28,823 --> 01:04:30,533
His conscience drove him away,
Miss Elizabeth.

1278
01:04:30,784 --> 01:04:33,328
You mean he was ashamed of
his behavior at the Assembly Ball.

1279
01:04:33,495 --> 01:04:34,496
Oh, that was nothing.

1280
01:04:35,163 --> 01:04:35,830
Thank you.

1281
01:04:36,581 --> 01:04:40,043
Merely the insult Mr. Darcy
likes to add to injury.

1282
01:04:41,795 --> 01:04:45,340
Miss Elizabeth, having confided
so much of my story to you,

1283
01:04:45,840 --> 01:04:47,008
I'd like you to understand the rest.

1284
01:04:47,801 --> 01:04:48,593
Would it bore you?

1285
01:04:49,302 --> 01:04:51,179
Oh, no. On the contrary. I--

1286
01:04:51,346 --> 01:04:52,430
I am deeply interested.

1287
01:04:53,264 --> 01:04:55,558
How kind and sympathetic you are.

1288
01:04:56,684 --> 01:04:57,560
Would it surprise you to learn

1289
01:04:57,727 --> 01:04:59,854
that I was once intended
for the church, Miss Elizabeth?

1290
01:05:00,021 --> 01:05:02,982
Really? Well, you seem
so well-fitted for the army.

1291
01:05:03,358 --> 01:05:05,193
I have no taste for soldiering.

1292
01:05:05,693 --> 01:05:07,404
The church ought to
have been my profession,

1293
01:05:07,695 --> 01:05:08,571
and would have been,

1294
01:05:08,988 --> 01:05:11,783
if Mr. Darcy hadn't chosen
to disregard his father's will.

1295
01:05:11,950 --> 01:05:14,285
Disregard a will?
Well, how could he?

1296
01:05:14,577 --> 01:05:16,621
For a man of honor,
it would have been impossible.

1297
01:05:17,497 --> 01:05:19,124
But Darcy chose to regard the annuity

1298
01:05:19,290 --> 01:05:21,751
which his father left me,
provided I entered the church,

1299
01:05:22,335 --> 01:05:24,337
as a mere recommendation
and not a bequest.

1300
01:05:25,672 --> 01:05:29,092
I knew Mr. Darcy was...
proud and arrogant.

1301
01:05:30,510 --> 01:05:32,470
I never imagined him dishonorable.

1302
01:05:36,474 --> 01:05:38,476
He should be publicly exposed.

1303
01:05:38,643 --> 01:05:39,811
Not by me, Miss Elizabeth.

1304
01:05:40,353 --> 01:05:41,271
While I remember the father,

1305
01:05:41,438 --> 01:05:43,314
I could never bring myself
to disgrace the son.

1306
01:05:43,815 --> 01:05:45,900
I admire your generosity, Mr. Wickham.

1307
01:05:46,401 --> 01:05:47,777
Thank you, Miss Elizabeth.

1308
01:05:48,611 --> 01:05:50,697
Your sympathy means very much to me.

1309
01:05:54,200 --> 01:05:55,410
Oh, there you are.

1310
01:05:55,577 --> 01:05:56,828
We can't let you keep him, Lizzy.

1311
01:05:56,995 --> 01:05:58,413
He's got to come and play with us.

1312
01:05:58,830 --> 01:06:00,206
You're going to be my partner,
Mr. Wickham.

1313
01:06:00,373 --> 01:06:01,916
What an honor.
I've been kidnapped.

1314
01:06:02,083 --> 01:06:03,418
- Won't you join us, Miss Elizabeth?
- Come on.

1315
01:06:03,585 --> 01:06:04,961
No thanks, Mr. Denny.
Later perhaps.

1316
01:06:05,336 --> 01:06:07,088
Come along. Gee up.

1317
01:06:08,965 --> 01:06:12,385
♪♪

1318
01:06:19,184 --> 01:06:20,351
Why, Jane.

1319
01:06:20,685 --> 01:06:21,269
Oh, Lizzy.

1320
01:06:21,436 --> 01:06:23,271
If you've let that
Caroline Bingley make you cry,

1321
01:06:23,438 --> 01:06:25,148
I'll--I'll shake you.

1322
01:06:25,315 --> 01:06:26,399
She says none of them intend

1323
01:06:26,566 --> 01:06:28,193
to return to Netherfield this winter.

1324
01:06:28,860 --> 01:06:31,070
She means she intends
none of them to return.

1325
01:06:31,237 --> 01:06:32,906
Oh, Lizzy, how can you think that?

1326
01:06:33,072 --> 01:06:34,657
After all, he's his own master.

1327
01:06:35,074 --> 01:06:37,619
Look. Read this part.

1328
01:06:40,413 --> 01:06:43,374
"My brother has long had
an affectionate interest

1329
01:06:44,334 --> 01:06:46,920
in Mr. Darcy's sister, Georgiana.

1330
01:06:48,713 --> 01:06:50,507
And during the next few months
In London,

1331
01:06:50,924 --> 01:06:53,092
both families are hoping
that their attachment

1332
01:06:53,259 --> 01:06:55,136
will flower into an event

1333
01:06:55,970 --> 01:06:58,223
which will secure
the happiness of us all."

1334
01:06:58,473 --> 01:07:01,643
You see? She knows her brother's
fond of someone else and

1335
01:07:02,227 --> 01:07:04,103
doesn't want me
to have any false hope.

1336
01:07:06,064 --> 01:07:08,149
She knows her brother's
in love with you.

1337
01:07:09,359 --> 01:07:11,819
She doesn't intend that
he shall marry into a family...

1338
01:07:12,403 --> 01:07:14,155
of such low descent.

1339
01:07:15,365 --> 01:07:17,951
Lizzy, what are you talking about?

1340
01:07:18,743 --> 01:07:20,495
Oh, never mind.

1341
01:07:21,746 --> 01:07:23,540
You'll see, dearest.
He'll come back to you.

1342
01:07:24,165 --> 01:07:26,084
Who could stay away from you for long?

1343
01:07:26,251 --> 01:07:27,085
Dearest.

1344
01:07:28,002 --> 01:07:29,671
Now come along down with me
and we'll have some tea.

1345
01:07:29,837 --> 01:07:30,672
All right.

1346
01:07:32,882 --> 01:07:34,467
Lizzy, are you really as indifferent

1347
01:07:34,634 --> 01:07:36,511
to Mr. Darcy's departure as you seem?

1348
01:07:36,678 --> 01:07:39,180
Indifferent?
I am delighted he's gone.

1349
01:07:39,514 --> 01:07:40,723
Wait till I tell you the monstrous thing

1350
01:07:40,890 --> 01:07:41,766
he did to Mr. Wickham.

1351
01:07:42,183 --> 01:07:43,351
It's absurd, Sir William.

1352
01:07:43,685 --> 01:07:45,270
I shall never believe it. Never.

1353
01:07:45,436 --> 01:07:47,397
Mr. Collins came here expressly

1354
01:07:47,564 --> 01:07:49,732
to propose marriage
to one of my daughters.

1355
01:07:49,899 --> 01:07:53,861
That may have been his purpose
in coming here, Mrs. Bennet, uh--oh, but--

1356
01:07:54,028 --> 01:07:55,697
Oh, there you are, Elizabeth.

1357
01:07:56,281 --> 01:07:57,532
This is all your fault.

1358
01:07:58,032 --> 01:07:58,950
What's my fault, Mama?

1359
01:07:59,117 --> 01:08:01,244
He says Charlotte is going
to marry Mr. Collins.

1360
01:08:01,411 --> 01:08:03,329
If that isn't your fault,
I don't know whose it is.

1361
01:08:03,496 --> 01:08:04,455
Charlotte?

1362
01:08:05,123 --> 01:08:07,458
- How delightful, Sir William.
- Thank you, Miss Jane.

1363
01:08:07,625 --> 01:08:09,252
But Charlotte...

1364
01:08:09,877 --> 01:08:11,671
Charlotte's going to marry Mr. Collins?

1365
01:08:11,838 --> 01:08:13,256
On Tuesday, week, to be precise.

1366
01:08:13,423 --> 01:08:14,841
Uh, Lady, uh, Catherine de Bourgh

1367
01:08:15,008 --> 01:08:17,051
doesn't believe
in long engagements, and--

1368
01:08:17,218 --> 01:08:18,177
But, Sir William,

1369
01:08:18,344 --> 01:08:20,221
Mr. Collins wants to marry Lizzy.

1370
01:08:20,555 --> 01:08:21,931
Oh, Lydia, be quiet.

1371
01:08:22,098 --> 01:08:23,349
The child is right, Lizzy.

1372
01:08:23,641 --> 01:08:26,561
Are you quite sure, Sir William,
that you haven't been misinformed?

1373
01:08:26,728 --> 01:08:28,730
I am quite positive, Mrs. Bennet. Um--

1374
01:08:28,896 --> 01:08:29,647
Mrs. Bennet.

1375
01:08:29,814 --> 01:08:30,565
Oh, there you are.

1376
01:08:30,732 --> 01:08:32,817
Come in and share in the rejoicing.

1377
01:08:32,984 --> 01:08:35,320
Oh, dear Mrs. Bennet,
I know you'll understand my feelings.

1378
01:08:35,653 --> 01:08:36,654
Such a happy event.

1379
01:08:37,071 --> 01:08:39,032
But then to lose one's dearest daughter,

1380
01:08:39,365 --> 01:08:41,409
oh, well, I'm still quite overcome.

1381
01:08:42,035 --> 01:08:43,911
It's probably the unexpectedness of it

1382
01:08:44,078 --> 01:08:45,747
that has overcome you, Lady Lucas.

1383
01:08:46,706 --> 01:08:49,083
And Mr. Collins' conduct is so very odd.

1384
01:08:49,250 --> 01:08:50,793
Perhaps some tea will revive you.

1385
01:08:54,339 --> 01:08:55,214
Lizzy.

1386
01:08:55,673 --> 01:08:56,799
Dear Charlotte, I--

1387
01:08:59,510 --> 01:09:00,345
Come with me.

1388
01:09:00,511 --> 01:09:01,512
Well, Lady Lucas,

1389
01:09:01,929 --> 01:09:03,264
little did I think that Charlotte

1390
01:09:03,431 --> 01:09:06,142
would one day take my place
as mistress of this house.

1391
01:09:06,809 --> 01:09:09,896
No doubt she and Mr. Collins would like to
go over the place thoroughly

1392
01:09:10,063 --> 01:09:11,564
and see what they're
going to inherit.

1393
01:09:12,148 --> 01:09:14,734
Mr. Collins,
why don't you go to the pantry

1394
01:09:15,026 --> 01:09:17,028
and get the maid to show you the silver.

1395
01:09:17,445 --> 01:09:19,113
Oh, Charlotte, dear, I beg you,

1396
01:09:19,447 --> 01:09:20,948
postpone the marriage for a time.

1397
01:09:21,115 --> 01:09:22,659
I'm only thinking of your happiness.

1398
01:09:23,117 --> 01:09:24,035
Happiness, Lizzy?

1399
01:09:24,702 --> 01:09:27,205
In marriage,
happiness Is just a matter of chance.

1400
01:09:27,372 --> 01:09:31,167
But, Charlotte,
his defects of character.

1401
01:09:31,834 --> 01:09:33,086
You know him so little.

1402
01:09:33,252 --> 01:09:35,213
Well, ignorance is bliss, Lizzy.

1403
01:09:35,546 --> 01:09:37,131
If one's to spend one's life
with a person,

1404
01:09:37,298 --> 01:09:39,801
it's best to know as little
as possible of his defects.

1405
01:09:40,551 --> 01:09:42,679
After all,
one will find them out soon enough.

1406
01:09:44,305 --> 01:09:47,308
Well, luckily Hunsford
isn't the end of the world.

1407
01:09:47,475 --> 01:09:50,103
You must come and visit me,
Lizzy, very soon. Promise.

1408
01:09:50,269 --> 01:09:51,896
- I promise.
- Good.

1409
01:09:52,772 --> 01:09:55,525
♪♪

1410
01:09:59,529 --> 01:10:00,863
Put those over here, Patrick.

1411
01:10:01,030 --> 01:10:01,823
Yes, madam.

1412
01:10:03,783 --> 01:10:05,034
Those will go on the chair, Nellie.

1413
01:10:05,952 --> 01:10:09,330
Big one against the wall,
small one there. That's fine.

1414
01:10:10,540 --> 01:10:11,958
- That will be all, Nellie.
- Thank you, miss.

1415
01:10:12,917 --> 01:10:14,544
Thank you.
That's very kind of you.

1416
01:10:14,711 --> 01:10:15,670
You're welcome, miss.

1417
01:10:16,254 --> 01:10:17,714
Now, Lizzy, give me your key.

1418
01:10:18,005 --> 01:10:19,674
Don't you bother, Charlotte.
I'll do this myself.

1419
01:10:19,841 --> 01:10:21,843
Oh, you'll not. You're my guest.

1420
01:10:22,093 --> 01:10:23,636
You're going to sit by and look on.

1421
01:10:24,220 --> 01:10:25,179
But, Charlotte--

1422
01:10:25,346 --> 01:10:28,141
This is my house,
and you'll do just as I say.

1423
01:10:28,558 --> 01:10:30,101
I tremble and obey.

1424
01:10:31,519 --> 01:10:32,437
Well, while you're unpacking,

1425
01:10:32,603 --> 01:10:34,814
I'll remove the dust
and change my dress.

1426
01:10:35,314 --> 01:10:36,315
Did you have a hard time

1427
01:10:36,482 --> 01:10:38,067
persuading your mother
to let you come?

1428
01:10:38,359 --> 01:10:40,611
Oh, no. No, it wasn't so difficult.

1429
01:10:41,487 --> 01:10:43,698
Jane went to London, you know,
to stay with Aunt Gardiner.

1430
01:10:44,532 --> 01:10:46,367
So of course she had to have
somebody to go with her.

1431
01:10:47,201 --> 01:10:49,537
And Papa--
Papa had some writing to do.

1432
01:10:50,121 --> 01:10:52,915
So he was quite delighted to get
a couple of us out of the house.

1433
01:10:54,167 --> 01:10:55,543
Two daughters out of five.

1434
01:10:55,710 --> 01:10:58,463
That represents 40 percent of the noise.

1435
01:10:59,464 --> 01:11:01,716
Why, Lizzy, this is daring.

1436
01:11:01,883 --> 01:11:03,384
Yes, isn't it?

1437
01:11:03,551 --> 01:11:04,927
I haven't dared show it to Mama.

1438
01:11:11,184 --> 01:11:12,477
Mr. Collins!

1439
01:11:13,060 --> 01:11:13,853
Mr. Collins!

1440
01:11:14,020 --> 01:11:14,979
Oh, Lizzy, do look.

1441
01:11:15,146 --> 01:11:16,063
Mr. Collins.

1442
01:11:23,738 --> 01:11:25,031
Well, what?

1443
01:11:25,823 --> 01:11:27,742
It's Lady Catherine de Bourgh
and her daughter, Anne.

1444
01:11:28,659 --> 01:11:29,702
Oh, is that all?

1445
01:11:29,869 --> 01:11:31,829
I expected at least the pigs
had gone into the garden.

1446
01:11:31,996 --> 01:11:34,040
Oh, pigs.
I must go down at once.

1447
01:11:34,665 --> 01:11:36,125
Oh, is my hair tidy?

1448
01:11:37,627 --> 01:11:39,337
So that's the great Lady Catherine.

1449
01:11:40,338 --> 01:11:42,048
Now I see where
he learned his manners.

1450
01:11:42,298 --> 01:11:43,466
Where who learned his manners?

1451
01:11:43,841 --> 01:11:45,259
Well, Mr. Darcy, of course.

1452
01:11:45,802 --> 01:11:46,969
I'll be back in a moment, my dear.

1453
01:11:52,642 --> 01:11:54,143
Yes, yes, Mr. Collins. Proceed.

1454
01:11:54,310 --> 01:11:55,102
Your ladyship.

1455
01:11:55,269 --> 01:11:56,938
- How do you do, Mrs. Collins?
- Miss de Bourgh.

1456
01:11:57,438 --> 01:11:58,147
How do you do?

1457
01:11:58,940 --> 01:11:59,774
Now, let me see, Lady Catherine.

1458
01:11:59,941 --> 01:12:01,943
Uh, a flannel petticoat for Mrs. Hodge,

1459
01:12:02,109 --> 01:12:04,195
a quarter of pound of tea
for old Martha Spratt,

1460
01:12:04,362 --> 01:12:05,947
and a hundredweight
of coals for the Burtons.

1461
01:12:06,155 --> 01:12:07,782
But nothing for the Smees,
do you understand?

1462
01:12:07,949 --> 01:12:08,991
Nothing whatever.

1463
01:12:09,408 --> 01:12:11,410
You must learn, Mrs. Collins,
to draw a firm line

1464
01:12:11,577 --> 01:12:13,955
between the deserving poor
and the undeserving.

1465
01:12:14,121 --> 01:12:15,414
What wise benevolence.

1466
01:12:15,581 --> 01:12:17,667
Are the chickens
still laying satisfactorily?

1467
01:12:18,000 --> 01:12:19,877
They've fallen off a little
these last days.

1468
01:12:20,211 --> 01:12:21,754
Then give them hot food,
Mrs. Collins.

1469
01:12:22,088 --> 01:12:25,049
If that has no effect,
then it means they're incorrigible.

1470
01:12:25,383 --> 01:12:27,134
They must be killed and boiled.
Killed and boiled.

1471
01:12:28,553 --> 01:12:30,179
Anne, my love,
you're not getting cold, I hope.

1472
01:12:30,596 --> 01:12:32,223
- A little, Mama.
- Ah...

1473
01:12:33,099 --> 01:12:34,016
Well, Mr. Collins,

1474
01:12:34,183 --> 01:12:36,060
I shall expect you all
to dinner this evening.

1475
01:12:36,477 --> 01:12:37,895
Goodbye, Mrs. Collins. Goodbye.

1476
01:12:38,062 --> 01:12:39,272
Uh, permit me to say
how much I appreciate--

1477
01:12:39,438 --> 01:12:40,189
Drive on, Smith.

1478
01:12:40,356 --> 01:12:42,733
...your ladyship's
affability and kindness.

1479
01:12:45,862 --> 01:12:47,446
What extraordinary
condescension.

1480
01:12:48,197 --> 01:12:50,324
I'm quite delighted of this,
for Miss Elizabeth's sake.

1481
01:12:52,159 --> 01:12:54,996
Now, my dear Miss Elizabeth,
permit me to show you

1482
01:12:55,162 --> 01:12:58,207
some of the priceless art
treasures of Lady Catherine's.

1483
01:12:58,791 --> 01:13:01,002
This, one of the finest
timepieces in the country.

1484
01:13:02,545 --> 01:13:05,089
Observe the noble proportions,
Miss Eliza.

1485
01:13:05,548 --> 01:13:08,134
And the ornaments.
What magnificence. What taste.

1486
01:13:08,634 --> 01:13:10,678
Very true, Mr. Collins.
Very true.

1487
01:13:11,095 --> 01:13:13,639
I've never met a painter or an architect

1488
01:13:13,890 --> 01:13:16,309
who did not congratulate me
upon my taste.

1489
01:13:16,851 --> 01:13:18,644
There. What did I say?

1490
01:13:18,895 --> 01:13:21,772
And now, let me call your
attention to the mantelpiece.

1491
01:13:24,066 --> 01:13:25,443
Observe, Miss Eliza,

1492
01:13:25,610 --> 01:13:27,987
solid marble entirely hand-carved.

1493
01:13:29,071 --> 01:13:31,032
Well, Mrs. Collins,
you will be surprised

1494
01:13:31,198 --> 01:13:32,783
to find someone you know
dining with us this evening.

1495
01:13:37,121 --> 01:13:38,247
Oh, there you are.

1496
01:13:38,664 --> 01:13:40,416
I was just about to tell the ladles,
Darcy,

1497
01:13:40,583 --> 01:13:42,710
of your sudden arrival
at Rosings this afternoon.

1498
01:13:47,715 --> 01:13:48,591
Mr. Darcy.

1499
01:13:49,091 --> 01:13:49,967
Miss Elizabeth.

1500
01:13:51,802 --> 01:13:53,262
A happy meeting, Miss Elizabeth.

1501
01:13:59,101 --> 01:14:01,395
Mrs. Collins, you know
one of my nephews, I believe.

1502
01:14:02,271 --> 01:14:03,773
Darcy. Darcy.

1503
01:14:05,274 --> 01:14:06,651
A pleasure, Mrs. Collins.

1504
01:14:06,817 --> 01:14:07,777
And this is another nephew.

1505
01:14:07,944 --> 01:14:09,487
Colonel Fitzwilliam, Mrs. Collins.

1506
01:14:10,237 --> 01:14:11,280
Miss Elizabeth Bennet,

1507
01:14:11,530 --> 01:14:12,531
Colonel Fitzwilliam.

1508
01:14:13,407 --> 01:14:16,410
A--oh, yes, and Mr. Collins.
Mr. Collins.

1509
01:14:16,619 --> 01:14:17,286
How do you do?

1510
01:14:18,287 --> 01:14:20,081
I thought you were In London,
Mr. Darcy.

1511
01:14:20,623 --> 01:14:23,626
Oh, yes. But, uh, my cousin
and I left there this morning.

1512
01:14:24,043 --> 01:14:25,836
Rather unexpectedly,
as a matter of fact.

1513
01:14:26,003 --> 01:14:29,048
All your departures seem to be
rather unexpected, Mr. Darcy.

1514
01:14:32,510 --> 01:14:35,429
You know, Miss Elizabeth,
I have thought a great deal

1515
01:14:35,596 --> 01:14:37,431
of what you said to me
at Netherfield that day.

1516
01:14:37,598 --> 01:14:39,558
Thank you.
About laughing more.

1517
01:14:40,101 --> 01:14:41,435
I've tried to follow your advice.

1518
01:14:42,061 --> 01:14:44,438
I hope it worked.
Do you feel happier now?

1519
01:14:45,606 --> 01:14:47,191
I've never felt
more miserable in my life.

1520
01:14:48,985 --> 01:14:50,736
Oh, it's doubtless
the lack of exercise.

1521
01:14:50,903 --> 01:14:52,822
You'll feel happier when
the hunting season begins.

1522
01:14:53,489 --> 01:14:55,116
Well, Darcy.

1523
01:14:55,783 --> 01:14:58,119
Now I know what took you
into Herefordshire this summer.

1524
01:14:58,536 --> 01:15:00,162
You also know what
drove him out again.

1525
01:15:00,663 --> 01:15:02,581
He liked the landscape
well enough, but the natives,

1526
01:15:02,748 --> 01:15:04,667
Colonel Fitzwilliam, the natives.

1527
01:15:05,084 --> 01:15:08,337
What boors. What savages.
Utterly insupportable.

1528
01:15:08,754 --> 01:15:10,089
Isn't that so, Mr. Darcy?

1529
01:15:10,256 --> 01:15:12,258
It evidently amuses you
to think so, Miss Elizabeth.

1530
01:15:12,925 --> 01:15:13,676
Miss Bennet.

1531
01:15:14,760 --> 01:15:15,428
Come here.

1532
01:15:19,098 --> 01:15:20,641
Mrs. Collins,
go and talk to your husband.

1533
01:15:20,808 --> 01:15:21,976
I wish to speak to Miss Bennet.

1534
01:15:22,143 --> 01:15:23,227
Yes, Lady Catherine.

1535
01:15:24,562 --> 01:15:25,438
Be seated.

1536
01:15:28,649 --> 01:15:30,359
Have you any accomplishments,
Miss Bennet?

1537
01:15:30,568 --> 01:15:31,652
Accomplishments.

1538
01:15:32,028 --> 01:15:35,364
Well, I don't know whether
Mr. Darcy would think I had.

1539
01:15:35,781 --> 01:15:36,907
Do you sing and play?

1540
01:15:37,074 --> 01:15:37,825
A little.

1541
01:15:38,159 --> 01:15:39,702
You should perform for us one day.

1542
01:15:40,119 --> 01:15:42,246
Our instrument here
is one of the best in the country.

1543
01:15:43,205 --> 01:15:44,957
You have several sisters, I understand.

1544
01:15:45,332 --> 01:15:47,293
- Four.
- Four. No brothers?

1545
01:15:47,460 --> 01:15:49,211
None, unfortunately for us.

1546
01:15:49,420 --> 01:15:50,379
Ah, yes.

1547
01:15:50,546 --> 01:15:53,215
Your father's estate is entailed
to Mr. Collins, I believe.

1548
01:15:53,507 --> 01:15:54,133
It is.

1549
01:15:54,300 --> 01:15:56,052
For Mrs. Collins' sake, I'm glad of it.

1550
01:15:56,385 --> 01:15:58,929
Otherwise, I see no occasion
for entailing estates

1551
01:15:59,221 --> 01:16:00,848
away from the female line.

1552
01:16:02,058 --> 01:16:03,267
When you marry, Darcy,

1553
01:16:03,684 --> 01:16:05,019
don't make that mistake.

1554
01:16:05,728 --> 01:16:08,147
It was never made
in Sir Lewis de Bourgh's family.

1555
01:16:08,773 --> 01:16:12,109
Anne, as you know, is the sole heiress.

1556
01:16:15,863 --> 01:16:16,822
Do you draw, Miss Bennet?

1557
01:16:17,448 --> 01:16:18,407
No, Lady Catherine.

1558
01:16:18,866 --> 01:16:20,534
What? None of you?

1559
01:16:20,785 --> 01:16:21,535
Not one of us.

1560
01:16:21,952 --> 01:16:22,953
But how strange.

1561
01:16:23,788 --> 01:16:24,997
Why didn't your governess see to that?

1562
01:16:25,581 --> 01:16:26,540
We never had a governess.

1563
01:16:26,874 --> 01:16:28,334
No governess?

1564
01:16:28,584 --> 01:16:29,627
I never heard of such a thing.

1565
01:16:30,044 --> 01:16:31,837
Miss Bennet seems to have got on

1566
01:16:32,004 --> 01:16:33,214
very well without one,
Aunt Catherine.

1567
01:16:33,464 --> 01:16:35,132
Don't talk nonsense, Darcy.

1568
01:16:35,883 --> 01:16:38,385
Are any of your younger sisters
out in society?

1569
01:16:38,719 --> 01:16:39,428
All of them.

1570
01:16:39,845 --> 01:16:40,846
All?

1571
01:16:42,056 --> 01:16:43,057
How very odd.

1572
01:16:43,599 --> 01:16:44,767
Really, Lady Catherine,

1573
01:16:44,934 --> 01:16:46,811
I think it would be
very hard on younger sisters

1574
01:16:46,977 --> 01:16:48,687
to be kept without
society or amusement

1575
01:16:48,854 --> 01:16:50,147
until the elder ones were married.

1576
01:16:50,898 --> 01:16:52,858
It would hardly promote
sisterly affection

1577
01:16:53,067 --> 01:16:54,860
or even delicacy of mind.

1578
01:16:55,611 --> 01:16:57,530
Upon my word, Miss Bennet.

1579
01:16:58,114 --> 01:17:00,241
You express your opinions
very decidedly.

1580
01:17:00,658 --> 01:17:02,743
Miss Bennet is nothing
if not decided, Aunt Catherine.

1581
01:17:05,704 --> 01:17:07,081
Dinner is served, milady.

1582
01:17:07,915 --> 01:17:09,500
Come, I hate cold soup.

1583
01:17:09,708 --> 01:17:10,793
Your arm, Fitzwilliam.

1584
01:17:13,462 --> 01:17:15,589
May I be allowed to continue
your interrogation during dinner?

1585
01:17:15,756 --> 01:17:17,591
There are so many things
I should like to find out.

1586
01:17:17,758 --> 01:17:19,260
It seems to be a family failing, sir.

1587
01:17:19,426 --> 01:17:21,762
No, Darcy.
You are to take Anne into dinner.

1588
01:17:22,429 --> 01:17:24,223
Mr. Collins will take
Miss Bennet.

1589
01:17:25,474 --> 01:17:27,893
I'm afraid you'll have to
go in alone, Mrs. Collins.

1590
01:17:28,185 --> 01:17:31,564
♪♪

1591
01:18:08,976 --> 01:18:13,189
Mr. Darcy's sister, Georgiana,
is a very accomplished musician.

1592
01:18:14,773 --> 01:18:17,484
And I too should have been
a great proficient,

1593
01:18:18,152 --> 01:18:19,153
if I'd ever learnt.

1594
01:18:19,695 --> 01:18:22,031
You would have been proficient
at anything, Lady Catherine.

1595
01:18:22,489 --> 01:18:23,324
So would Anne.

1596
01:18:23,741 --> 01:18:24,950
That goes without saying.

1597
01:18:34,418 --> 01:18:35,377
Darcy?

1598
01:18:36,754 --> 01:18:37,630
Do come here.

1599
01:18:46,555 --> 01:18:47,681
Sit down, sit down.

1600
01:18:51,602 --> 01:18:53,187
I was just telling Mrs. Collins

1601
01:18:53,437 --> 01:18:55,773
how exquisitely dear Anne
would have played...

1602
01:18:56,315 --> 01:18:58,567
if her health
had permitted her to study.

1603
01:18:59,652 --> 01:19:00,361
I don't doubt it.

1604
01:19:00,527 --> 01:19:02,655
Your dear mother
was so fond of Anne.

1605
01:19:03,322 --> 01:19:04,114
Yes, I know.

1606
01:19:04,281 --> 01:19:06,700
"You have an only daughter,"
she used to say to me.

1607
01:19:07,117 --> 01:19:08,911
"And I have an only son.

1608
01:19:09,870 --> 01:19:13,207
It's as though Providence had
created them for one another,"

1609
01:19:13,832 --> 01:19:14,750
she used to say.

1610
01:19:15,834 --> 01:19:19,046
Incredible.
I-I mean, uh, exactly.

1611
01:19:20,214 --> 01:19:22,841
I--I mean, uh, excuse me.

1612
01:19:42,695 --> 01:19:44,363
Well, don't stop, Miss Elizabeth,
that was charming.

1613
01:19:44,697 --> 01:19:47,283
Isn't that the right time to stop?
When people still think you're charming?

1614
01:19:47,700 --> 01:19:49,493
If I went on,
you might change your mind.

1615
01:19:55,291 --> 01:19:56,041
Miss Bennet.

1616
01:20:00,921 --> 01:20:02,006
I'm summoned.

1617
01:20:04,591 --> 01:20:06,302
That was quite creditable, my dear.

1618
01:20:06,802 --> 01:20:08,554
Miss Bennet wouldn't
play at all badly,

1619
01:20:08,721 --> 01:20:09,930
if she practiced more.

1620
01:20:10,347 --> 01:20:13,100
Practice, Miss Bennet, practice.
You can't do enough of it.

1621
01:20:14,226 --> 01:20:16,437
Mrs. Collins has no pianoforte, of course,

1622
01:20:16,603 --> 01:20:18,230
but you're...
you're very welcome

1623
01:20:18,397 --> 01:20:19,648
to practice here every day.

1624
01:20:20,441 --> 01:20:22,318
Oh, thank you, Lady Catherine.

1625
01:20:22,735 --> 01:20:25,446
There's a very fair instrument
in the housekeeper's room.

1626
01:20:25,863 --> 01:20:27,406
You'll disturb no one there.

1627
01:20:28,824 --> 01:20:31,243
You are really too gracious,
Lady Catherine,

1628
01:20:31,785 --> 01:20:34,621
but I shouldn't care
to disturb the housekeeper.

1629
01:20:34,913 --> 01:20:36,915
I protest, Aunt Catherine.

1630
01:20:37,082 --> 01:20:39,168
Why talk of practicing
when Miss Bennet should be playing?

1631
01:20:39,543 --> 01:20:40,294
Come, Miss Bennet.

1632
01:20:40,544 --> 01:20:42,171
I insist on your favoring us again.

1633
01:20:48,635 --> 01:20:52,014
There is, uh, needless to say,
a rich assortment of music here.

1634
01:20:52,765 --> 01:20:54,641
My aunt means quite kindly,
Miss Elizabeth.

1635
01:20:54,808 --> 01:20:56,477
Her manner is sometimes
a little unfortunate.

1636
01:20:56,643 --> 01:20:57,978
Having already met you,

1637
01:20:58,145 --> 01:21:00,773
I was happily prepared
for your aunt's manner.

1638
01:21:09,490 --> 01:21:11,325
Lizzy, Mr. Darcy's in the study.

1639
01:21:11,492 --> 01:21:12,993
He's been waiting
for you for nearly an hour.

1640
01:21:13,786 --> 01:21:16,246
Let him wait.
I don't want to see him.

1641
01:21:16,789 --> 01:21:18,165
I never want to see him again.

1642
01:21:18,332 --> 01:21:20,000
Well, Lizzy, what's happened?
What's come over you?

1643
01:21:20,584 --> 01:21:21,919
Do you want to know the real reason

1644
01:21:22,086 --> 01:21:23,796
why Mr. Bingley
left Netherfield for London?

1645
01:21:24,338 --> 01:21:27,091
His high-and-mightiness, Mr. Darcy.

1646
01:21:27,257 --> 01:21:28,592
But I thought it was Caroline Bingley.

1647
01:21:28,759 --> 01:21:29,843
She was only half the reason.

1648
01:21:30,177 --> 01:21:31,220
I've just heard about it by chance

1649
01:21:31,387 --> 01:21:33,013
this very moment from Colonel Fitzwilliam.

1650
01:21:33,305 --> 01:21:34,431
Colonel Fitzwilliam?

1651
01:21:34,598 --> 01:21:36,183
Of course he didn't know
I was Jane's sister.

1652
01:21:36,517 --> 01:21:39,645
He was just holding forth about
the virtues of his precious cousin.

1653
01:21:40,187 --> 01:21:41,522
Telling me how unselfish he was

1654
01:21:41,772 --> 01:21:43,732
and what an infinite amount
of trouble he'd gone to

1655
01:21:43,899 --> 01:21:46,527
to save his friend Bingley
from an impossible marriage.

1656
01:21:46,693 --> 01:21:47,361
Oh...

1657
01:21:47,861 --> 01:21:49,863
You can tell your Mr. Darcy
that I'm not at home.

1658
01:21:50,030 --> 01:21:51,824
He must have seen you come in.
I can't tell him that.

1659
01:21:52,324 --> 01:21:54,118
After all, he is Lady Catherine's nephew.

1660
01:21:54,952 --> 01:21:57,454
Lizzy, for my sake.

1661
01:21:58,122 --> 01:22:00,249
Very well, Charlotte, for your sake.

1662
01:22:13,095 --> 01:22:14,221
Good morning, Miss Elizabeth.

1663
01:22:14,721 --> 01:22:15,889
Good morning, Mr. Darcy.

1664
01:22:24,481 --> 01:22:26,316
Mrs. Collins gave me leave
to wait on you.

1665
01:22:41,123 --> 01:22:41,957
It's no use.

1666
01:22:42,958 --> 01:22:44,126
I've struggled in vain.

1667
01:22:44,960 --> 01:22:46,503
I must tell you how much

1668
01:22:46,837 --> 01:22:48,297
I admire and love you.

1669
01:22:49,047 --> 01:22:49,882
Miss Elizabeth,

1670
01:22:50,966 --> 01:22:52,759
my life and happiness
are in your hands.

1671
01:22:53,594 --> 01:22:55,262
These last weeks
since I left Netherfield

1672
01:22:55,429 --> 01:22:57,556
have been empty,
meaningless days and nights.

1673
01:22:58,599 --> 01:23:00,726
I thought I could put you
out of my mind.

1674
01:23:01,185 --> 01:23:03,437
That inclination would
give way to judgment.

1675
01:23:04,605 --> 01:23:06,148
I walked the streets of London,

1676
01:23:06,315 --> 01:23:08,025
reminding myself of the unsuitability

1677
01:23:08,192 --> 01:23:09,151
of such a marriage.

1678
01:23:09,735 --> 01:23:11,653
Of the obstacles between us.

1679
01:23:13,363 --> 01:23:14,198
But it won't do.

1680
01:23:15,365 --> 01:23:17,159
I can struggle against you no longer.

1681
01:23:17,826 --> 01:23:18,785
Mr. Darcy.

1682
01:23:18,952 --> 01:23:20,287
I've reminded myself again and again

1683
01:23:20,454 --> 01:23:22,456
that I have obligations
of family and position.

1684
01:23:22,956 --> 01:23:26,502
Obligations I was born to.
Nothing I tell myself matters.

1685
01:23:27,586 --> 01:23:28,378
I love you.

1686
01:23:29,922 --> 01:23:30,797
I love you.

1687
01:23:33,258 --> 01:23:34,468
Do you know what you're saying?

1688
01:23:34,635 --> 01:23:35,719
Yes, my darling.

1689
01:23:36,637 --> 01:23:37,971
I'm asking you to marry me.

1690
01:23:45,395 --> 01:23:46,647
Do you expect me to thank you

1691
01:23:46,813 --> 01:23:49,066
for this extraordinary offer of marriage?

1692
01:23:49,775 --> 01:23:52,361
Am I supposed to feel flattered
that you have so overcome

1693
01:23:52,528 --> 01:23:54,112
your aversion to my family,

1694
01:23:54,279 --> 01:23:55,572
that you're ready to marry into it?

1695
01:23:55,989 --> 01:23:57,366
But do you expect me to be glad

1696
01:23:57,533 --> 01:23:58,784
that your family is inferior to mine?

1697
01:24:00,536 --> 01:24:01,828
I suppose I should congratulate you

1698
01:24:01,995 --> 01:24:04,456
on winning the battle
between your unwilling affection

1699
01:24:04,623 --> 01:24:06,542
and my unworthiness.

1700
01:24:07,000 --> 01:24:09,044
But, you see, I have never desired
your good opinion.

1701
01:24:09,378 --> 01:24:11,171
And if you were not so lacking
in perception,

1702
01:24:11,380 --> 01:24:13,382
you might have
spared yourself my refusal.

1703
01:24:14,258 --> 01:24:16,385
It's--is this the only reply
I am to be honored with?

1704
01:24:17,386 --> 01:24:20,430
I might, perhaps,
deserve to be told why I am rejected

1705
01:24:20,597 --> 01:24:21,807
and with so little civility.

1706
01:24:22,307 --> 01:24:24,101
I also might deserve to know why,

1707
01:24:24,268 --> 01:24:26,645
determined, evidently,
to offend and insult me,

1708
01:24:26,979 --> 01:24:29,690
you chose to tell me
that you liked me against your will.

1709
01:24:29,940 --> 01:24:32,651
Against your reason.
Against even your character.

1710
01:24:33,151 --> 01:24:34,653
Why, if the manner of my expression--

1711
01:24:34,820 --> 01:24:37,447
The manner of your proposal
is only one reason for my incivility,

1712
01:24:37,614 --> 01:24:38,740
if I have been uncivil.

1713
01:24:39,199 --> 01:24:40,742
Even had my feelings been favorable--

1714
01:24:40,909 --> 01:24:41,827
which they never could have been,

1715
01:24:41,994 --> 01:24:44,121
but even if they had,
I still have every reason in the world

1716
01:24:44,288 --> 01:24:45,163
to think I" of you.

1717
01:24:46,290 --> 01:24:48,041
Do you think anything would
tempt me to accept the man

1718
01:24:48,208 --> 01:24:50,586
who has destroyed
the happiness of my sister?

1719
01:24:52,045 --> 01:24:54,423
The sweetest soul that ever lived.

1720
01:24:56,425 --> 01:24:57,634
How could you do it?

1721
01:24:59,553 --> 01:25:01,722
Knowing Jane,
how could you hurt her so?

1722
01:25:02,055 --> 01:25:02,848
In observing them together,

1723
01:25:03,015 --> 01:25:05,017
I could not believe
that she really loved Charles.

1724
01:25:05,851 --> 01:25:08,520
As his friend I considered it
my duty to advise his cause.

1725
01:25:09,021 --> 01:25:10,147
And even without this,

1726
01:25:10,731 --> 01:25:11,982
your character was clearly revealed

1727
01:25:12,149 --> 01:25:13,275
in your treatment of Mr. Wickham.

1728
01:25:13,525 --> 01:25:15,444
You take an eager interest
in that gentleman's concern.

1729
01:25:15,611 --> 01:25:17,821
And who that knows his misfortunes
could fail to take an interest?

1730
01:25:17,988 --> 01:25:19,114
"His misfortune.“

1731
01:25:20,282 --> 01:25:22,451
Brought on by your injustice
and betrayal.

1732
01:25:23,785 --> 01:25:24,911
Where Wickham is concerned,

1733
01:25:25,746 --> 01:25:26,580
I have nothing to say.

1734
01:25:27,122 --> 01:25:28,498
In other words,
you dare not speak

1735
01:25:28,665 --> 01:25:29,833
because you know you're guilty.

1736
01:25:31,335 --> 01:25:32,502
And that is your opinion of me.

1737
01:25:36,048 --> 01:25:37,674
Perhaps my faults might
have been overlooked

1738
01:25:38,175 --> 01:25:39,718
had I concealed my struggles

1739
01:25:39,926 --> 01:25:41,553
and flattered you
that no doubt of my course

1740
01:25:41,720 --> 01:25:42,888
had ever entered my mind.

1741
01:25:43,805 --> 01:25:45,474
I made the mistake
of being honest with you.

1742
01:25:45,974 --> 01:25:47,976
Honesty is a greatly overrated virtue.

1743
01:25:48,143 --> 01:25:50,062
Silence in this case
would have been more agreeable.

1744
01:25:50,228 --> 01:25:52,147
But I'm not ashamed of
my scruples about your family.

1745
01:25:52,314 --> 01:25:52,939
They were natural.

1746
01:25:53,106 --> 01:25:55,067
And should have been
kept to yourself.

1747
01:25:56,318 --> 01:25:58,654
Let us end this distasteful subject.

1748
01:26:00,739 --> 01:26:03,575
Your arrogance.
Your conceit.

1749
01:26:04,409 --> 01:26:06,995
Your--your selfish disregard
of other people's feelings

1750
01:26:07,162 --> 01:26:08,580
made me dislike you from the first.

1751
01:26:08,789 --> 01:26:11,291
I-I... I hadn't known you a week
before I decided

1752
01:26:11,458 --> 01:26:14,252
you were the last man in the world
I'd ever be prevailed upon to marry.

1753
01:26:14,753 --> 01:26:15,962
You've said quite enough, madam.

1754
01:26:16,463 --> 01:26:17,881
I understand your feelings

1755
01:26:18,382 --> 01:26:20,759
and have now only to be ashamed
of having confessed my own.

1756
01:26:22,094 --> 01:26:24,680
Forgive me for having taken up
so much of your valuable time.

1757
01:26:25,347 --> 01:26:28,266
♪♪

1758
01:26:30,477 --> 01:26:34,189
And accept my best wishes
for your health and happiness.

1759
01:26:44,366 --> 01:26:45,492
Ugh-

1760
01:26:55,293 --> 01:26:57,504
♪♪

1761
01:27:00,507 --> 01:27:01,383
Allow me, Miss Eliza.

1762
01:27:01,550 --> 01:27:02,342
Lizzy.

1763
01:27:03,802 --> 01:27:04,803
Oh, Jane.

1764
01:27:07,723 --> 01:27:09,349
- Lizzy.
- I thought you were In London.

1765
01:27:09,516 --> 01:27:10,684
No, they sent for me this morning.

1766
01:27:10,851 --> 01:27:12,310
Lizzy, it's so awful.

1767
01:27:12,811 --> 01:27:13,562
Oh, what is it?

1768
01:27:13,812 --> 01:27:14,855
It's poor little Lydia.

1769
01:27:15,188 --> 01:27:16,982
She's run away with Mr. Wickham.

1770
01:27:18,942 --> 01:27:19,860
Mr. Wickham.

1771
01:27:20,402 --> 01:27:21,987
And they didn't go to Gretna Green.

1772
01:27:22,571 --> 01:27:23,697
Lizzy, they're not married.

1773
01:27:24,239 --> 01:27:25,031
Not married?

1774
01:27:25,365 --> 01:27:26,783
And we can't find them anywhere.

1775
01:27:29,119 --> 01:27:29,870
Oh, Jane.

1776
01:27:32,873 --> 01:27:34,416
You tell Charlotte. I'm going in.

1777
01:27:37,169 --> 01:27:39,713
Beware of officers,
I kept on telling her.

1778
01:27:40,046 --> 01:27:41,923
They're fickle. They're unprincipled.

1779
01:27:42,507 --> 01:27:43,925
They never have a sixpence.

1780
01:27:44,092 --> 01:27:45,635
You're right there, my dear.

1781
01:27:45,927 --> 01:27:48,638
Mr. Wickham owes money
to every tradesman in Meryton.

1782
01:27:48,847 --> 01:27:50,474
Not to mention gambling debts

1783
01:27:50,640 --> 01:27:52,309
to the tune of 500 or 600 pounds

1784
01:27:52,476 --> 01:27:53,435
at the very least.

1785
01:27:53,643 --> 01:27:55,604
- Lizzy.
- Oh, Lizzy.

1786
01:27:55,896 --> 01:27:56,980
Oh.

1787
01:27:57,147 --> 01:28:00,025
Oh, you don't know
how I have suffered, Lizzy.

1788
01:28:00,192 --> 01:28:03,153
Such--such spasms.
Such palpitations.

1789
01:28:03,320 --> 01:28:04,696
Such thunderings.

1790
01:28:04,863 --> 01:28:07,449
Yes, Mama, I know, I know.

1791
01:28:07,616 --> 01:28:09,409
What, no broth?
Where are the bird feathers?

1792
01:28:09,576 --> 01:28:10,994
Oh, I forgot those.

1793
01:28:13,246 --> 01:28:14,498
When did it happen, Aunt Philips?

1794
01:28:14,664 --> 01:28:15,707
Only yesterday.

1795
01:28:16,208 --> 01:28:18,126
It seems they're hiding
somewhere in London.

1796
01:28:18,710 --> 01:28:20,086
Your father's gone to look for them.

1797
01:28:20,337 --> 01:28:22,714
Yes, and you know
what'll happen when he finds them.

1798
01:28:23,131 --> 01:28:24,800
He'll challenge Mr. Wickham to a duel

1799
01:28:24,966 --> 01:28:25,842
and he'll be killed.

1800
01:28:26,468 --> 01:28:28,094
And then what will become of us?

1801
01:28:28,595 --> 01:28:30,555
Those Collinses will turn us out

1802
01:28:30,722 --> 01:28:32,599
before he's cold in his grave.

1803
01:28:33,391 --> 01:28:35,685
Oh, the vultures.
They're here already.

1804
01:28:37,020 --> 01:28:38,230
Shh. Mama.

1805
01:28:39,314 --> 01:28:40,440
Poor Mrs. Bennet.

1806
01:28:41,107 --> 01:28:43,151
I just heard the news.
It's too dreadful.

1807
01:28:43,485 --> 01:28:45,278
Ah, Mrs. Bonnet,

1808
01:28:45,445 --> 01:28:46,238
Mrs. Bennet.

1809
01:28:46,655 --> 01:28:49,616
Yours is a misfortune
which no lapse of time can alleviate.

1810
01:28:49,783 --> 01:28:51,284
No lapse of time, Mrs. Philips.

1811
01:28:51,701 --> 01:28:52,619
The death of your daughter

1812
01:28:52,786 --> 01:28:54,329
would have been a blessing
compared to this.

1813
01:28:54,579 --> 01:28:56,248
- Mr. Collins.
- And what is it, my dear?

1814
01:28:56,540 --> 01:28:58,416
Poor Mrs. Bennet,
you're distressing her.

1815
01:28:58,667 --> 01:29:00,460
Distressing her?
I'm bringing her consolation.

1816
01:29:00,877 --> 01:29:02,504
May I add, madam,

1817
01:29:02,671 --> 01:29:04,256
that this false step
of one of your daughters,

1818
01:29:04,422 --> 01:29:06,049
uh, must prove very injurious

1819
01:29:06,216 --> 01:29:07,759
unto the fortunes of all the others.

1820
01:29:07,926 --> 01:29:10,053
Oh, he's right. He's right.
They'll never get married now.

1821
01:29:10,220 --> 01:29:11,721
What's to become of them?

1822
01:29:11,930 --> 01:29:14,266
I shudder to think what
Lady Catherine will say to all this.

1823
01:29:15,684 --> 01:29:18,395
Miss Elizabeth.
Mr. Darcy just called.

1824
01:29:18,562 --> 01:29:19,938
I've shown him into the library.

1825
01:29:20,105 --> 01:29:20,939
Mr. Darcy.

1826
01:29:21,356 --> 01:29:22,774
Oh, that odious man.

1827
01:29:22,941 --> 01:29:24,693
Don't you see him, Lizzy.

1828
01:29:25,068 --> 01:29:26,903
Oh, madam. 0h, don't forget
that Mr. Darcy is a nephew

1829
01:29:27,070 --> 01:29:28,154
of Lady Catherine de Bourgh.

1830
01:29:28,655 --> 01:29:30,490
Perhaps it would be better
if I saw him, Miss Eliza.

1831
01:29:30,740 --> 01:29:33,118
Thank you, Mr. Collins,
I'd prefer to see him myself.

1832
01:29:34,286 --> 01:29:35,871
Oh, Mr. Collins.

1833
01:29:46,506 --> 01:29:48,842
Mr. Darcy.
What brings you here?

1834
01:29:49,509 --> 01:29:50,594
Feel no alarm, madam.

1835
01:29:51,177 --> 01:29:53,388
I have no intention
of reopening a painful subject.

1836
01:29:54,306 --> 01:29:55,807
After what you said
to me the other day,

1837
01:29:55,974 --> 01:29:59,394
that chapter is definitely closed.

1838
01:30:01,521 --> 01:30:03,315
Bad news travels fast, Miss Bennet.

1839
01:30:04,733 --> 01:30:06,401
A few hours after you left Hunsford,

1840
01:30:06,902 --> 01:30:08,737
I heard about George Wickham
and your sister.

1841
01:30:09,738 --> 01:30:11,489
I felt it my duty to come at once.

1842
01:30:13,158 --> 01:30:15,952
To triumph over us, I suppose.

1843
01:30:19,581 --> 01:30:21,082
To offer you my services.

1844
01:30:23,209 --> 01:30:24,711
Miss Bennet, I told you the other day

1845
01:30:24,878 --> 01:30:26,129
that where George Wickham
was concerned,

1846
01:30:26,296 --> 01:30:27,380
I chose to be silent.

1847
01:30:29,299 --> 01:30:31,760
What has happened to your sister
has made me change my mind.

1848
01:30:33,011 --> 01:30:34,471
You have a right to the truth.

1849
01:30:36,264 --> 01:30:38,934
George Wickham will never marry
your sister, Miss Bennet.

1850
01:30:41,853 --> 01:30:42,812
Her case...

1851
01:30:43,688 --> 01:30:44,898
was not the first.

1852
01:30:46,149 --> 01:30:47,025
You mean that Wickham--?

1853
01:30:48,693 --> 01:30:50,904
My own sister, Georgiana.

1854
01:30:51,905 --> 01:30:52,864
Your sister.

1855
01:30:54,866 --> 01:30:55,575
Yes.

1856
01:30:57,243 --> 01:30:59,120
She was younger even than Lydia.

1857
01:31:00,288 --> 01:31:02,248
Oh, Mr. Darcy.

1858
01:31:04,292 --> 01:31:07,003
Georgiana has a considerable fortune
in her own right.

1859
01:31:08,213 --> 01:31:09,673
His plan was to elope with her,

1860
01:31:10,215 --> 01:31:13,009
and then, under the threat
of publishing her disgrace,

1861
01:31:13,510 --> 01:31:15,512
to force my consent to their marriage.

1862
01:31:16,429 --> 01:31:17,722
By the mercy of Providence,

1863
01:31:18,473 --> 01:31:19,933
I discovered the plot in time.

1864
01:31:21,476 --> 01:31:23,395
Your sister has been less fortunate.

1865
01:31:24,813 --> 01:31:25,772
Miss Elizabeth,

1866
01:31:26,773 --> 01:31:30,235
may I ask if everything possible
is being done to recover her?

1867
01:31:31,236 --> 01:31:32,862
My father has gone to London.

1868
01:31:33,780 --> 01:31:35,949
He and my uncle are searching for her.

1869
01:31:37,200 --> 01:31:39,244
If there is any help that I could give,

1870
01:31:39,995 --> 01:31:41,246
I would be only too happy.

1871
01:31:41,413 --> 01:31:42,122
Thank you.

1872
01:31:43,039 --> 01:31:44,624
I'm sure they will find her.

1873
01:31:45,583 --> 01:31:47,460
It will all be settled somehow.

1874
01:31:49,546 --> 01:31:51,172
I'm afraid I've stayed too long.

1875
01:31:53,049 --> 01:31:53,758
Goodbye.

1876
01:31:55,969 --> 01:31:56,928
Goodbye.

1877
01:31:58,221 --> 01:32:00,640
♪♪

1878
01:32:10,275 --> 01:32:13,236
This is perhaps the last time
I shall see you.

1879
01:32:17,323 --> 01:32:18,950
God bless you, Elizabeth.

1880
01:32:30,795 --> 01:32:32,589
- Mr. Darcy.
- Oh, Lizzy.

1881
01:32:33,089 --> 01:32:33,965
Oh.

1882
01:32:35,508 --> 01:32:37,010
I thought it was--I...

1883
01:32:38,094 --> 01:32:39,137
Has he gone?

1884
01:32:39,971 --> 01:32:40,597
Yes.

1885
01:32:41,514 --> 01:32:42,891
He's just riding away.

1886
01:32:46,728 --> 01:32:47,896
Riding away.

1887
01:32:52,025 --> 01:32:53,359
Will he ever ride back?

1888
01:32:56,279 --> 01:32:59,365
"That chapter is definitely...

1889
01:33:00,033 --> 01:33:01,201
closed."

1890
01:33:01,659 --> 01:33:02,368
Lizzy.

1891
01:33:03,286 --> 01:33:04,454
What are you talking about?

1892
01:33:06,039 --> 01:33:06,873
Oh, Jane.

1893
01:33:07,791 --> 01:33:10,126
Jane, you don't know
what happened at Hunsford.

1894
01:33:10,752 --> 01:33:14,005
Something so extraordinary,
so unbelievable.

1895
01:33:14,172 --> 01:33:14,756
What?

1896
01:33:15,006 --> 01:33:16,382
He asked me to marry him.

1897
01:33:16,800 --> 01:33:17,634
Who, Lizzy?

1898
01:33:17,801 --> 01:33:18,760
Mr. Darcy.

1899
01:33:19,135 --> 01:33:20,345
Mr. Darcy?

1900
01:33:20,637 --> 01:33:23,556
Oh, but Lizzy.
What did you say to him?

1901
01:33:25,266 --> 01:33:26,518
What did I say to him?

1902
01:33:29,270 --> 01:33:30,605
What did I say to him?

1903
01:33:32,899 --> 01:33:34,067
I said I hated him.

1904
01:33:34,984 --> 01:33:36,778
I said I never wanted to see him again.

1905
01:33:38,238 --> 01:33:39,364
Now, suddenly, I...

1906
01:33:41,908 --> 01:33:43,034
Jane, I love him.

1907
01:33:45,537 --> 01:33:46,579
You love him?

1908
01:33:46,746 --> 01:33:48,623
I'm so dreadfully unhappy.

1909
01:33:49,082 --> 01:33:50,667
Lizzy, dearest.

1910
01:33:51,793 --> 01:33:54,754
I brought it all on myself.
It's all my own stupid fault.

1911
01:33:56,047 --> 01:33:58,550
Heavens,
how could I have misjudged him so?

1912
01:33:59,134 --> 01:34:03,721
Oh, what a fool I've been.
What a despicable fool.

1913
01:34:03,888 --> 01:34:06,057
Oh, Lizzy, dearest,
we all make mistakes.

1914
01:34:06,224 --> 01:34:08,268
- You mustn't feel--
- Oh, and how selfish I'm being.

1915
01:34:08,560 --> 01:34:10,436
As if I were the only one
to be made unhappy.

1916
01:34:10,937 --> 01:34:12,313
Poor Jane, my darling.

1917
01:34:12,480 --> 01:34:13,898
Why, you've never done anything wrong.

1918
01:34:14,065 --> 01:34:15,275
Look what's happened to you.

1919
01:34:15,483 --> 01:34:16,484
Oh.

1920
01:34:17,819 --> 01:34:18,778
It's not fair.

1921
01:34:18,945 --> 01:34:19,904
Oh, Lizzy.

1922
01:34:20,238 --> 01:34:21,698
I'm not really unhappy.

1923
01:34:22,407 --> 01:34:23,449
It was worse in the beginning

1924
01:34:23,616 --> 01:34:25,285
when I was always
expecting him to write

1925
01:34:25,451 --> 01:34:27,036
or even to come back.

1926
01:34:27,704 --> 01:34:28,913
But I don't do that anymore.

1927
01:34:29,414 --> 01:34:30,415
I just dream of him.

1928
01:34:31,666 --> 01:34:35,128
Lizzy, you've got to learn
to dream, like I do.

1929
01:34:36,546 --> 01:34:38,756
Sometimes I dream
we're out walking in the woods,

1930
01:34:38,923 --> 01:34:40,633
and the primroses are out.

1931
01:34:41,217 --> 01:34:43,136
Sometimes he comes riding up to the door.

1932
01:34:43,511 --> 01:34:45,555
Riding on a white horse, Lizzy.

1933
01:34:46,556 --> 01:34:48,683
And he goes in,
and I'm waiting for him.

1934
01:34:49,601 --> 01:34:51,019
And sometimes we're dancing.

1935
01:34:51,269 --> 01:34:52,562
And it's the waltz, Lizzy.

1936
01:34:53,313 --> 01:34:55,732
And the music's playing,
and lights are shining.

1937
01:34:55,899 --> 01:34:57,567
Oh, it feels as if it could go on forever.

1938
01:34:59,110 --> 01:35:01,404
Oh, Lizzy,
you shouldn't let me go on like this.

1939
01:35:14,250 --> 01:35:16,044
Oh, well done, Mr. Darcy.

1940
01:35:17,670 --> 01:35:19,464
The question is, what to do now?

1941
01:35:24,135 --> 01:35:25,011
Ah.

1942
01:35:26,304 --> 01:35:27,555
More news from Meryton.

1943
01:35:27,889 --> 01:35:30,433
Another bulletin about
your beloved Bennets, Charles.

1944
01:35:31,267 --> 01:35:33,394
"There is still no trace
of Lydia or Wickham.

1945
01:35:33,811 --> 01:35:36,064
Poor old Mr. Bennet
has come home in despair."

1946
01:35:36,231 --> 01:35:37,440
Do you mean that they've
given up the search?

1947
01:35:37,607 --> 01:35:38,858
Mm. So it seems.

1948
01:35:41,527 --> 01:35:42,278
Listen.

1949
01:35:43,029 --> 01:35:44,614
"At the Assembly Ball last week,

1950
01:35:44,864 --> 01:35:47,367
the Bennet family
was conspicuous by its absence.

1951
01:35:47,742 --> 01:35:48,826
Shall I tell you why?

1952
01:35:49,202 --> 01:35:52,038
Because the Entertainment Committee
had dropped a gentle hint

1953
01:35:52,372 --> 01:35:53,790
that, in view of the scandal,

1954
01:35:53,957 --> 01:35:55,875
its presence would not be welcome."

1955
01:35:57,043 --> 01:35:59,212
Isn't that exquisitely funny, Mr. Darcy?

1956
01:35:59,379 --> 01:36:00,338
Exquisitely.

1957
01:36:00,713 --> 01:36:03,216
Just think how you would roar
with laughter if it happened to yourself.

1958
01:36:05,343 --> 01:36:08,137
"Only yesterday, I saw her sisters, Jane
and Elizabeth,

1959
01:36:08,554 --> 01:36:11,516
almost running down Market Street,
in an attempt to escape

1960
01:36:11,683 --> 01:36:12,600
from their disgrace."

1961
01:36:16,646 --> 01:36:18,439
That's what comes
of your chattering, Caroline.

1962
01:36:19,440 --> 01:36:20,316
I'm sorry, Darcy.

1963
01:36:20,817 --> 01:36:22,235
I've ruined your table, I'm afraid.

1964
01:36:23,027 --> 01:36:24,279
It's nothing, Charles.
It might have happened

1965
01:36:24,445 --> 01:36:25,863
to anybody in the same circumstances.

1966
01:36:26,281 --> 01:36:27,323
I'd better stop playing

1967
01:36:27,782 --> 01:36:28,950
before something worse happens.

1968
01:36:29,367 --> 01:36:30,451
- Goodnight, Darcy.
- Goodnight.

1969
01:36:30,827 --> 01:36:31,744
Goodnight, Caroline.

1970
01:36:39,836 --> 01:36:42,880
I don't believe I shall ever
get back my strength.

1971
01:36:43,423 --> 01:36:45,216
It won't be long now, Mama.

1972
01:36:45,383 --> 01:36:46,592
You'll feel so much better

1973
01:36:46,759 --> 01:36:48,344
when we've moved away
from this place.

1974
01:36:48,511 --> 01:36:49,429
Won't she, Papa?

1975
01:36:49,595 --> 01:36:50,888
Well, I sincerely hope so.

1976
01:36:51,306 --> 01:36:53,391
This house with its sad associations

1977
01:36:53,558 --> 01:36:55,768
and now the people
being so dreadfully unkind.

1978
01:36:56,519 --> 01:36:57,729
It's no wonder you're ill.

1979
01:36:57,937 --> 01:36:59,814
Here's some delicious chicken broth, Mama.

1980
01:37:00,231 --> 01:37:01,607
Now, you must eat it while it's hot.

1981
01:37:01,858 --> 01:37:04,152
No. No, thank you, Lizzy, I couldn't.

1982
01:37:04,986 --> 01:37:07,447
You don't know how “I I feel.

1983
01:37:09,032 --> 01:37:10,575
Did you say it was chicken broth?

1984
01:37:11,367 --> 01:37:13,244
Well... well, perhaps...

1985
01:37:13,995 --> 01:37:15,496
if I make a great effort.

1986
01:37:15,663 --> 01:37:17,290
Ah, there, Mama.

1987
01:37:18,041 --> 01:37:18,750
There.

1988
01:37:21,210 --> 01:37:23,504
Papa, what was that you were saying

1989
01:37:23,671 --> 01:37:25,340
about those nice cheap lodgings

1990
01:37:25,506 --> 01:37:26,549
you heard of by the sea?

1991
01:37:26,716 --> 01:37:28,384
- At “agate, my dear?
- Yes.

1992
01:37:28,968 --> 01:37:29,844
Margate.

1993
01:37:30,428 --> 01:37:32,513
To think that it should come to Margate.

1994
01:37:32,972 --> 01:37:35,433
No, Lizzy, I... I couldn't eat any more.

1995
01:37:35,850 --> 01:37:37,310
Not after that.

1996
01:37:37,477 --> 01:37:38,603
Oh, but Mama.

1997
01:37:38,853 --> 01:37:40,730
Everyone says Margate's
such a charming place

1998
01:37:40,897 --> 01:37:42,106
and so inexpensive.

1999
01:37:42,357 --> 01:37:44,317
Besides, what does it matter where we go,

2000
01:37:44,859 --> 01:37:46,110
as long as we go together?

2001
01:37:46,277 --> 01:37:49,197
Yes, Mama.
We'll make a little world of our own.

2002
01:37:49,489 --> 01:37:52,158
Yes. A Bennet utopia, my dear.

2003
01:37:52,658 --> 01:37:54,285
A domestic paradise,

2004
01:37:54,786 --> 01:37:58,247
where nobody shall ever talk
more than is strictly necessary.

2005
01:37:59,248 --> 01:38:01,376
Oh, Mr. Bennet.

2006
01:38:03,419 --> 01:38:06,089
Where nobody shall ever
play scales on the piano, Lizzy.

2007
01:38:06,506 --> 01:38:09,425
Where nobody shall ever
even think of bonnets

2008
01:38:09,592 --> 01:38:11,594
or tea parties or gossip or--

2009
01:38:11,761 --> 01:38:12,929
Why do you have to tell Mama?

2010
01:38:13,096 --> 01:38:14,180
Tell Mama. Tell them all.

2011
01:38:14,347 --> 01:38:15,640
Mama!

2012
01:38:15,807 --> 01:38:16,682
Oh!

2013
01:38:16,849 --> 01:38:18,184
My poor nerves.

2014
01:38:18,726 --> 01:38:20,520
Stop squabbling, you two,
for goodness' sake.

2015
01:38:20,686 --> 01:38:22,939
Mary says I can't take
my musical box to the new house.

2016
01:38:23,106 --> 01:38:24,023
Listen to it.

2017
01:38:24,190 --> 01:38:25,942
It's not nearly as bad
as your horrid old bird.

2018
01:38:26,109 --> 01:38:27,944
Polly is not a horrid old bird.

2019
01:38:28,111 --> 01:38:30,029
And if you think that I can bear
to listen to that thing--

2020
01:38:30,196 --> 01:38:32,657
Aren't you ashamed of yourselves,
with poor Mama so ill?

2021
01:38:32,824 --> 01:38:34,242
A Bennet utopia, my dear.

2022
01:38:34,409 --> 01:38:35,576
But, Lizzy, it's not fair.

2023
01:38:35,743 --> 01:38:38,371
If Mary can take her parrot,
why shouldn't I take my musical box?

2024
01:38:38,538 --> 01:38:39,747
Well, why shouldn't we take the piano?

2025
01:38:39,914 --> 01:38:41,707
Why shouldn't Papa take
all the books in his library?

2026
01:38:41,874 --> 01:38:44,377
Why should poor Mama have to leave
her collection of china behind?

2027
01:38:44,544 --> 01:38:46,421
Come along and tell Mama you're sorry.
Come on.

2028
01:38:49,090 --> 01:38:50,174
I'm sorry, Mama.

2029
01:38:50,341 --> 01:38:51,843
We oughtn't to have made such a fuss.

2030
01:38:52,009 --> 01:38:52,927
I'm sorry.

2031
01:38:54,220 --> 01:38:55,179
Mr. Collins.

2032
01:38:56,180 --> 01:38:57,723
I took the liberty of coming
across the garden.

2033
01:38:57,890 --> 01:38:58,766
May I be permitted?

2034
01:38:58,933 --> 01:39:00,268
Come in, Mr. Collins. Come in.

2035
01:39:00,435 --> 01:39:01,644
Thank you, sir, thank you.

2036
01:39:02,145 --> 01:39:03,020
Oh, ladies.

2037
01:39:03,688 --> 01:39:05,565
Miss Eliza. I, uh--

2038
01:39:05,857 --> 01:39:07,900
I trust, madam,
I see you in better health.

2039
01:39:08,151 --> 01:39:09,610
I wish you did, Mr. Collins.

2040
01:39:10,611 --> 01:39:12,822
Nobody can imagine how weak I feel,

2041
01:39:12,989 --> 01:39:14,615
as if I were fading away.

2042
01:39:14,866 --> 01:39:17,201
Well, it's not to be wondered at
in the circumstances.

2043
01:39:17,743 --> 01:39:21,372
I'm sorry to see that Mr. Bennet
also looks far from well.

2044
01:39:22,206 --> 01:39:23,499
He seems to have aged a great deal

2045
01:39:23,666 --> 01:39:25,751
in the last few weeks,
don't you think so, Miss Eliza?

2046
01:39:26,085 --> 01:39:28,963
Does he? Perhaps the wish is
father to the thought, Mr. Collins.

2047
01:39:30,131 --> 01:39:31,466
I suppose you have heard

2048
01:39:31,632 --> 01:39:34,427
that we are leaving Longbourn,
Mr. Collins.

2049
01:39:34,719 --> 01:39:36,053
A wise decision, madam.

2050
01:39:36,512 --> 01:39:38,431
Find some remote and secluded spot

2051
01:39:38,681 --> 01:39:40,641
where no one has ever heard
of your unhappy daughter.

2052
01:39:40,808 --> 01:39:42,935
Oh, my poor little Lydia.

2053
01:39:43,102 --> 01:39:45,271
What can have happened to her?

2054
01:39:47,356 --> 01:39:48,524
- What Is It, Papa?
- 1".--

2055
01:39:49,775 --> 01:39:51,152
It's from your Uncle Gardiner.

2056
01:39:51,486 --> 01:39:52,904
He's found Lydia.

2057
01:39:53,154 --> 01:39:54,489
- He's found her?
- Yes.

2058
01:39:57,158 --> 01:40:00,119
"...and Wickham asked for
1,000 pounds at your death

2059
01:40:00,495 --> 01:40:02,413
and 100 pounds a year
during your lifetime.

2060
01:40:02,747 --> 01:40:06,000
These terms seemed moderate,
and I took upon myself

2061
01:40:06,167 --> 01:40:07,835
the responsibility of agreeing to them."

2062
01:40:08,085 --> 01:40:09,462
He's agreed to Wickham's terms.

2063
01:40:10,129 --> 01:40:12,548
He doesn't seem to be
asking very much, does he?

2064
01:40:13,424 --> 01:40:14,800
Considering what he'd demanded when--

2065
01:40:16,344 --> 01:40:18,804
I mean, considering the sort of man he is.

2066
01:40:20,348 --> 01:40:22,517
Why do you think he's content
with so little, Papa?

2067
01:40:22,934 --> 01:40:24,185
Well, this is what your uncle says.

2068
01:40:24,352 --> 01:40:25,436
Here. Postscript.

2069
01:40:26,270 --> 01:40:30,399
"It seems that Wickham recently came
into a very considerable sum of money."

2070
01:40:31,400 --> 01:40:34,362
Oh, I see. Well... that explains it.

2071
01:40:34,529 --> 01:40:36,572
No, it doesn't explain anything, my child.

2072
01:40:37,114 --> 01:40:38,074
We know that Wickham's in debt.

2073
01:40:38,241 --> 01:40:40,243
We know he's extravagant.
We know he's a gambler.

2074
01:40:40,701 --> 01:40:42,912
And yet suddenly,
he has so much money

2075
01:40:43,079 --> 01:40:45,665
that he'll take a girl like Lydia
for two pounds a week.

2076
01:40:47,250 --> 01:40:49,126
Ah, there are two things I want to know.

2077
01:40:50,086 --> 01:40:53,339
One is how much money your uncle
has laid down to bring this about.

2078
01:40:54,257 --> 01:40:55,424
The other is...

2079
01:40:55,967 --> 01:40:57,843
how can I ever repay him?

2080
01:41:00,429 --> 01:41:02,431
Oh, well, let's go and
break the good news to your mother.

2081
01:41:04,642 --> 01:41:05,643
What's that?

2082
01:41:15,611 --> 01:41:16,862
What can it be?

2083
01:41:21,367 --> 01:41:24,161
♪♪

2084
01:41:37,300 --> 01:41:38,217
It's Lydia.

2085
01:41:45,600 --> 01:41:47,310
- They're married. Mama!
- Married?

2086
01:41:47,476 --> 01:41:49,061
Mama. Mama!

2087
01:41:49,228 --> 01:41:50,896
It's Lydia. They're married.

2088
01:41:51,147 --> 01:41:52,315
- What?
- They're married!

2089
01:42:02,867 --> 01:42:04,410
- Look, Mama.
- The ring.

2090
01:42:05,870 --> 01:42:07,788
Oh, my dear, dear son-in-law.

2091
01:42:07,955 --> 01:42:09,624
May I give you a hug too?

2092
01:42:11,834 --> 01:42:13,002
What do you think of that, Kitty?

2093
01:42:13,252 --> 01:42:15,296
It's better than one of your old books.

2094
01:42:15,713 --> 01:42:16,922
Well, Jane.

2095
01:42:17,798 --> 01:42:19,425
- Oh, Lydia.
- Elizabeth.

2096
01:42:20,051 --> 01:42:21,969
You can't imagine the fun we've had.

2097
01:42:22,219 --> 01:42:23,179
Oh, Mama.

2098
01:42:25,931 --> 01:42:27,058
That will do for now.

2099
01:42:29,935 --> 01:42:32,605
Did you see?
We got the liveries secondhand.

2100
01:42:32,772 --> 01:42:34,857
But they're awfully smart,
don't you think so?

2101
01:42:35,316 --> 01:42:36,567
Are they your servants?

2102
01:42:37,068 --> 01:42:38,486
We're rich, Mama.

2103
01:42:38,653 --> 01:42:39,528
Rich.

2104
01:42:39,779 --> 01:42:43,074
Oh, my sweetest child. Rich!

2105
01:42:43,366 --> 01:42:44,533
Rich!

2106
01:42:48,287 --> 01:42:51,499
May I ask how you have suddenly
become so rich, Mr. Wickham?

2107
01:42:53,000 --> 01:42:55,044
Well, it was quite a surprise.

2108
01:42:55,753 --> 01:42:58,255
One of my, uh, my uncles
died a few weeks ago.

2109
01:42:58,673 --> 01:43:00,591
An uncle I haven't seen
since childhood.

2110
01:43:01,133 --> 01:43:02,802
He'd been living in Jamaica.

2111
01:43:03,928 --> 01:43:05,012
Yes, Jamaica.

2112
01:43:05,680 --> 01:43:06,972
And he left you a fortune?

2113
01:43:07,139 --> 01:43:08,599
Oh, a modest competence,

2114
01:43:09,141 --> 01:43:10,643
but it's coming was very timely.

2115
01:43:11,060 --> 01:43:12,186
Very timely, indeed.

2116
01:43:13,104 --> 01:43:14,230
Very timely.

2117
01:43:16,190 --> 01:43:18,025
Oh, dear George.

2118
01:43:18,317 --> 01:43:21,278
We're all so proud of you,
aren't we, Lizzy?

2119
01:43:21,445 --> 01:43:22,905
Oh, prodigiously.

2120
01:43:23,155 --> 01:43:24,699
So handsome
and so distinguished.

2121
01:43:24,865 --> 01:43:26,867
And two footmen in livery. Heh.

2122
01:43:27,076 --> 01:43:29,912
Come, my loves.
Oh, think of it.

2123
01:43:30,079 --> 01:43:33,582
A daughter married
and only 16 last June.

2124
01:43:33,749 --> 01:43:36,252
- Papa.
- Mr. Bennet. Mr. Bonnet.

2125
01:43:36,502 --> 01:43:38,337
We shan't have to leave Longbourn.

2126
01:43:38,504 --> 01:43:40,756
People can't say anything
now that they're married.

2127
01:43:41,090 --> 01:43:43,634
We won't have to go to Margate.

2128
01:43:46,095 --> 01:43:47,930
Why, how glum you look, Papa.

2129
01:43:48,514 --> 01:43:50,891
What's happened?
What does all this mean?

2130
01:43:51,308 --> 01:43:52,810
Oh, how do you do,
Mr. Collins?

2131
01:43:53,436 --> 01:43:55,354
How's your funny old lady thingamabob?

2132
01:43:55,646 --> 01:43:57,857
Oh, I forgot. Wicky, Papa.

2133
01:44:02,403 --> 01:44:03,738
If you'll excuse me, my dear.

2134
01:44:04,739 --> 01:44:05,865
Goodbye, Mr. Collins.

2135
01:44:09,118 --> 01:44:11,996
Oh, well.
Papa will get to like you In time, Wicky.

2136
01:44:12,288 --> 01:44:15,416
Nobody can help liking you.

2137
01:44:15,916 --> 01:44:17,460
Don't you envy me, Lizzy?

2138
01:44:18,127 --> 01:44:20,337
Ask me that question again
five years from now.

2139
01:44:20,504 --> 01:44:21,297
Five years?

2140
01:44:21,464 --> 01:44:24,008
Who cares what happens In five years?

2141
01:44:24,425 --> 01:44:25,259
Oh, Mama,

2142
01:44:25,426 --> 01:44:27,136
do you think the servants
would like to see my ring?

2143
01:44:27,303 --> 01:44:28,471
I'm sure of it.

2144
01:44:28,888 --> 01:44:30,723
Well, then let's all go out
to the kitchen.

2145
01:44:30,890 --> 01:44:32,683
Come along.
I want everybody to see.

2146
01:44:33,267 --> 01:44:34,560
Oh, you, too, Mr. Collins.

2147
01:44:34,894 --> 01:44:36,979
We old married people must stick together.

2148
01:44:39,148 --> 01:44:40,608
Lady Catherine de Bourgh.

2149
01:44:40,775 --> 01:44:41,776
♪♪

2150
01:44:47,865 --> 01:44:49,283
Lady Catherine.

2151
01:44:49,784 --> 01:44:50,785
Lady Catherine.

2152
01:44:50,951 --> 01:44:52,703
What an honor for this humble house.

2153
01:44:52,870 --> 01:44:54,830
No honor was intended,
Mr. Collins.

2154
01:44:56,165 --> 01:44:57,333
Mrs. Bennet,
I presume.

2155
01:44:57,500 --> 01:44:58,959
How do you do, Lady Catherine?

2156
01:44:59,668 --> 01:45:01,295
Such a pleasure to make
your acquaintance.

2157
01:45:02,838 --> 01:45:04,381
- Do come in.
- Thank you.

2158
01:45:05,382 --> 01:45:06,258
Miss Bennet.

2159
01:45:08,511 --> 01:45:09,762
Come right in, Lady Catherine.

2160
01:45:09,929 --> 01:45:11,430
Come right in.

2161
01:45:12,306 --> 01:45:15,184
Won't you, uh, sit down?

2162
01:45:41,001 --> 01:45:42,294
Stupid child.

2163
01:45:43,337 --> 01:45:45,130
Things are in such confusion today.

2164
01:45:46,465 --> 01:45:47,299
So I see.

2165
01:45:47,466 --> 01:45:49,885
Yes. Ye--

2166
01:45:51,428 --> 01:45:53,180
I wish to speak
to Miss Elizabeth Bennet.

2167
01:45:53,514 --> 01:45:54,849
Oh, um...

2168
01:45:55,224 --> 01:45:56,183
Elizabeth.

2169
01:45:57,726 --> 01:46:00,813
Lizzy, Lady Catherine
wishes to speak to you.

2170
01:46:01,647 --> 01:46:04,066
I wish to speak to Miss Bennet alone.

2171
01:46:04,608 --> 01:46:06,277
You will kindly leave us,
Mrs. Bennet.

2172
01:46:06,610 --> 01:46:08,571
Oh, certainly, ma'am.
If you wish it.

2173
01:46:08,904 --> 01:46:10,030
I do wish it.

2174
01:46:11,198 --> 01:46:12,575
Uh, come, children.

2175
01:46:13,367 --> 01:46:15,077
Uh, I hope we shall all have the pleasure

2176
01:46:15,244 --> 01:46:16,495
of seeing you later, Lady Catherine.

2177
01:46:16,662 --> 01:46:18,080
Possibly, Mrs. Bennet, possibly.

2178
01:46:18,247 --> 01:46:19,790
Ah--yes.

2179
01:46:21,750 --> 01:46:22,626
Mr. Collins.

2180
01:46:25,379 --> 01:46:26,589
Be seated, Miss Bennet.

2181
01:46:28,507 --> 01:46:31,176
Oh! My poor nerves.

2182
01:46:32,636 --> 01:46:33,262
Oh...

2183
01:46:33,596 --> 01:46:34,889
He's very young.

2184
01:46:42,980 --> 01:46:44,398
Come, come.
Be seated, Miss Bennet.

2185
01:46:46,025 --> 01:46:47,109
Stop dawdling.

2186
01:46:50,988 --> 01:46:51,780
Miss Bennet,

2187
01:46:52,448 --> 01:46:56,076
a report has reached me
of a most alarming nature.

2188
01:46:56,577 --> 01:46:59,622
I was told that you,
Miss Elizabeth Bennet,

2189
01:46:59,872 --> 01:47:03,250
were shortly to be engaged
to my nephew, Mr. Darcy.

2190
01:47:03,959 --> 01:47:07,922
Of course, I could not believe this report
could possibly be true.

2191
01:47:08,464 --> 01:47:09,340
Nevertheless,

2192
01:47:09,506 --> 01:47:11,800
I immediately resolved upon
setting out to see you.

2193
01:47:12,384 --> 01:47:14,011
If it could not possibly be true, madam,

2194
01:47:14,261 --> 01:47:16,889
I wonder you gave yourself
the trouble of coming so far.

2195
01:47:18,349 --> 01:47:22,102
I came to insist upon the report
being universally contradicted.

2196
01:47:22,478 --> 01:47:25,439
But won't your coming here
seem rather to confirm it?

2197
01:47:25,606 --> 01:47:27,900
Insolent, headstrong girl.

2198
01:47:28,275 --> 01:47:29,693
I'm ashamed of you.

2199
01:47:29,944 --> 01:47:31,779
Is this your gratitude

2200
01:47:32,029 --> 01:47:34,031
for my attentions to you at Rosings?

2201
01:47:34,907 --> 01:47:37,201
Miss Bennet, I am not to be trifled with.

2202
01:47:37,952 --> 01:47:39,703
Has my nephew made you
an offer of marriage?

2203
01:47:40,120 --> 01:47:41,664
You have declared that to be impossible.

2204
01:47:41,872 --> 01:47:45,209
Impossible?
I have the power to make It Impossible.

2205
01:47:46,043 --> 01:47:49,588
Are you aware that as trustee
of my sister's estate,

2206
01:47:49,922 --> 01:47:53,342
I can strip Mr. Darcy
of every shilling he has?

2207
01:47:54,051 --> 01:47:56,428
And if he were to marry
against my wishes,

2208
01:47:56,595 --> 01:47:59,807
I should not hesitate
in carrying out my power.

2209
01:48:00,432 --> 01:48:02,184
Now what have you to say?

2210
01:48:03,435 --> 01:48:04,395
Nothing whatever.

2211
01:48:05,562 --> 01:48:08,023
I take no interest in matters
that are none of my business.

2212
01:48:08,774 --> 01:48:09,525
Ahh.

2213
01:48:09,900 --> 01:48:12,319
Bold words, my girl, bold words.

2214
01:48:12,861 --> 01:48:13,946
But remember this,

2215
01:48:14,405 --> 01:48:16,991
marry him and you will be poor.

2216
01:48:17,449 --> 01:48:19,576
That would be no novelty for me,
Lady Catherine.

2217
01:48:20,744 --> 01:48:22,496
Once and for all,
are you engaged to him?

2218
01:48:24,289 --> 01:48:25,582
No, I am not.

2219
01:48:26,083 --> 01:48:26,959
Ah.

2220
01:48:27,710 --> 01:48:29,086
And, uh, will you promise me

2221
01:48:29,253 --> 01:48:31,338
never to enter
into such an engagement?

2222
01:48:34,675 --> 01:48:36,135
No, I will not.

2223
01:48:36,427 --> 01:48:37,302
Oh.

2224
01:48:37,970 --> 01:48:40,431
So you do expect him to propose to you?

2225
01:48:41,140 --> 01:48:42,766
I have no right to expect anything,

2226
01:48:43,225 --> 01:48:44,435
excepting, perhaps,

2227
01:48:45,185 --> 01:48:46,228
never to see him again.

2228
01:48:46,395 --> 01:48:48,689
What? Do you have
the impertinence to pretend

2229
01:48:48,856 --> 01:48:50,232
that he isn't in love with you?

2230
01:48:51,233 --> 01:48:52,776
I can't imagine that he would be.

2231
01:48:53,277 --> 01:48:54,028
Not now.

2232
01:48:54,361 --> 01:48:57,197
Then why his kind consideration
for your sister?

2233
01:48:57,489 --> 01:48:59,616
Was that the act of a man
who isn't in love?

2234
01:49:00,117 --> 01:49:01,827
I don't know
what you're talking about.

2235
01:49:02,161 --> 01:49:05,914
Possibly you don't.
But that rascal, Wickham, does.

2236
01:49:06,415 --> 01:49:09,043
Imagine it. My nephew, Darcy,

2237
01:49:09,585 --> 01:49:13,422
scouring the courts and alleys
of London looking for him.

2238
01:49:13,672 --> 01:49:16,050
Huh! Setting him up with an income.

2239
01:49:16,592 --> 01:49:21,221
Forcing him to marry that silly little...
flibbertigibbet.

2240
01:49:21,764 --> 01:49:22,765
Did he do that?

2241
01:49:23,766 --> 01:49:24,475
Oh.

2242
01:49:25,225 --> 01:49:27,061
Thank you for telling me,
Lady Catherine.

2243
01:49:27,895 --> 01:49:30,230
- Thank you.
- I will not be thanked.

2244
01:49:30,397 --> 01:49:32,900
Let us have no more
of this mummery, Miss Bennet.

2245
01:49:35,444 --> 01:49:36,445
I shall not leave this house

2246
01:49:36,612 --> 01:49:38,530
until you have given me
the assurance for which I ask.

2247
01:49:38,864 --> 01:49:39,907
In that case, Lady Catherine,

2248
01:49:40,074 --> 01:49:41,533
I had better ring for the butler.

2249
01:49:44,870 --> 01:49:46,246
He will show you to your bedroom.

2250
01:49:46,830 --> 01:49:49,208
Or if you decide,
after all, not to stay,

2251
01:49:49,374 --> 01:49:50,918
he will conduct you to your carriage.

2252
01:49:52,920 --> 01:49:53,921
Yes, Miss Elizabeth?

2253
01:49:54,254 --> 01:49:55,047
Oh, Matthews,

2254
01:49:55,339 --> 01:49:56,673
I have the impression that her ladyship

2255
01:49:56,840 --> 01:49:58,509
wishes to be taken to her carriage.

2256
01:50:01,720 --> 01:50:03,097
Goodbye, Lady Catherine.

2257
01:50:03,847 --> 01:50:05,766
I take no leave of you, Miss Bennet.

2258
01:50:06,016 --> 01:50:07,893
I send no compliments to your mother.

2259
01:50:08,268 --> 01:50:09,895
You deserve no such attention.

2260
01:50:10,729 --> 01:50:13,565
I am seriously displeased.

2261
01:50:14,233 --> 01:50:16,860
♪♪

2262
01:50:28,163 --> 01:50:30,541
- Well?
- A blank refusal.

2263
01:50:31,291 --> 01:50:32,000
She refused to see me?

2264
01:50:32,167 --> 01:50:33,585
She refused not to see you.

2265
01:50:35,003 --> 01:50:37,297
- Did she?
- Most emphatically.

2266
01:50:37,798 --> 01:50:39,716
But that's not the worst, Darcy.

2267
01:50:40,008 --> 01:50:41,051
I told her...

2268
01:50:41,510 --> 01:50:44,346
that I could strip you of your fortune
if I chose to.

2269
01:50:44,763 --> 01:50:47,057
But she refused to be
the least bit impressed.

2270
01:50:47,224 --> 01:50:48,016
You see?

2271
01:50:48,225 --> 01:50:49,393
Yes, I see, Darcy.

2272
01:50:49,560 --> 01:50:51,520
I grant I was wrong about that.

2273
01:50:52,229 --> 01:50:54,356
But there's one thing
I can't agree with.

2274
01:50:54,940 --> 01:50:56,316
You told me at Rosings...

2275
01:50:56,984 --> 01:50:58,777
she was nothing if not decided.

2276
01:50:59,111 --> 01:51:00,028
That's not true.

2277
01:51:00,320 --> 01:51:02,823
The young woman
is positively obstinate.

2278
01:51:03,198 --> 01:51:04,658
What? Did she refuse anything else?

2279
01:51:04,867 --> 01:51:06,034
Well, she--

2280
01:51:06,535 --> 01:51:09,121
she merely refused
to refuse to marry you.

2281
01:51:13,000 --> 01:51:14,918
Why, Da--Darcy. Darcy.

2282
01:51:15,252 --> 01:51:17,296
What manners. Have you gone mad?

2283
01:51:17,462 --> 01:51:18,630
Yes, yes. Quite mad.

2284
01:51:18,797 --> 01:51:20,841
And I don't believe I shall
ever be quite sane again.

2285
01:51:21,258 --> 01:51:22,801
But you wouldn't
wish me to be, would you?

2286
01:51:23,051 --> 01:51:26,180
No, I don't think I would.
She's right for you, Darcy.

2287
01:51:26,597 --> 01:51:28,432
You were a spoiled child.

2288
01:51:28,932 --> 01:51:30,350
But we don't want
to go on spoiling you.

2289
01:51:30,642 --> 01:51:33,854
What you need is a woman
who will stand up to you.

2290
01:51:34,771 --> 01:51:36,398
I think you've found her.

2291
01:51:37,649 --> 01:51:38,650
Well, Darcy,

2292
01:51:38,817 --> 01:51:40,110
help me into my carriage.

2293
01:51:40,777 --> 01:51:42,404
How can I ever thank you, Aunt Catherine?

2294
01:51:42,696 --> 01:51:45,365
Upon my word,
I'm not accustomed to so much gratitude.

2295
01:51:45,616 --> 01:51:47,409
Everybody seems to be thanking me today.

2296
01:51:47,826 --> 01:51:48,702
Drive on, Smith.

2297
01:51:49,369 --> 01:51:50,829
Don't stand there and keep me waiting.

2298
01:51:50,996 --> 01:51:51,997
Shut the door, Darcy.

2299
01:51:53,248 --> 01:51:54,333
Go into the house.

2300
01:52:07,596 --> 01:52:08,597
How do you do,
Mrs. Bennet?

2301
01:52:09,014 --> 01:52:09,848
Mr. Darcy.

2302
01:52:10,682 --> 01:52:11,683
Well, this is an honor.

2303
01:52:11,934 --> 01:52:13,310
First, Lady Catherine and now you.

2304
01:52:13,477 --> 01:52:15,062
I was traveling with my aunt,
and I thought I would

2305
01:52:15,229 --> 01:52:17,022
- give myself the pleasure--
- Jane.

2306
01:52:17,940 --> 01:52:20,692
Jane. Mama,
I can't find Jane anywhere. I--

2307
01:52:22,402 --> 01:52:23,070
Oh.

2308
01:52:27,950 --> 01:52:29,159
How do you do, Miss Elizabeth?

2309
01:52:29,326 --> 01:52:30,202
How do you do?

2310
01:52:30,744 --> 01:52:32,663
Jane ls somewhere In the garden,
I believe.

2311
01:52:32,996 --> 01:52:33,872
Oh, Miss Jane,

2312
01:52:34,206 --> 01:52:35,874
I have a message for her
from the Bingleys.

2313
01:52:36,333 --> 01:52:37,918
Should we...?
Should we see if--?

2314
01:52:38,085 --> 01:52:39,962
- Oh, why, yes. Let's do that.
- Fine.

2315
01:52:40,462 --> 01:52:41,088
Will you excuse us, madam?

2316
01:52:41,797 --> 01:52:44,132
Very gladly, Mr. Darcy.

2317
01:52:50,180 --> 01:52:52,307
♪♪

2318
01:52:53,850 --> 01:52:54,768
Miss Bennet.

2319
01:52:57,521 --> 01:52:58,897
I have a confession to make.

2320
01:52:59,648 --> 01:53:01,733
I didn't tell the exact truth, I'm afraid,

2321
01:53:01,900 --> 01:53:03,360
about the message from the Bingleys.

2322
01:53:03,610 --> 01:53:04,903
They didn't send one?

2323
01:53:05,070 --> 01:53:06,363
They didn't send one
for the good reason

2324
01:53:06,530 --> 01:53:09,157
that Charles Bingley had every intention
of bringing it himself.

2325
01:53:09,408 --> 01:53:09,992
Himself?

2326
01:53:10,158 --> 01:53:11,994
Yes. He came back
to Netherfield last night.

2327
01:53:12,160 --> 01:53:15,122
I was rather expecting
to see him here this afternoon.

2328
01:53:16,748 --> 01:53:17,457
Ah.

2329
01:53:20,961 --> 01:53:24,339
♪♪

2330
01:53:30,804 --> 01:53:33,015
Oh, Mr. Darcy, this is your doing.

2331
01:53:33,932 --> 01:53:35,600
Shall I tell you
who is really responsible

2332
01:53:35,767 --> 01:53:37,519
for your sister's happiness,
Miss Elizabeth?

2333
01:53:38,770 --> 01:53:39,855
Caroline Bingley.

2334
01:53:41,315 --> 01:53:42,232
Miss Bingley?

2335
01:53:42,399 --> 01:53:43,233
Yes.

2336
01:53:43,734 --> 01:53:46,111
She sent her brother back
by dwelling on all the reasons

2337
01:53:46,278 --> 01:53:48,030
why he should stay away.

2338
01:53:48,447 --> 01:53:49,489
I only approved a decision

2339
01:53:49,656 --> 01:53:51,491
that he had already taken
on his own account.

2340
01:53:52,951 --> 01:53:55,120
Mr. Darcy,
there's something else.

2341
01:53:55,912 --> 01:53:58,915
I hardly know how to put it into words.

2342
01:53:59,791 --> 01:54:00,959
What you did for Lydia.

2343
01:54:01,710 --> 01:54:04,046
I? But I assure you
I did nothing, Miss Bennet.

2344
01:54:04,921 --> 01:54:06,631
Lady Catherine was not of that opinion.

2345
01:54:07,049 --> 01:54:09,176
What? But I never gave her
leave to tell you that.

2346
01:54:09,718 --> 01:54:10,927
Gave her leave?

2347
01:54:11,887 --> 01:54:13,096
Do you mean to say
that Lady Catherine--?

2348
01:54:13,388 --> 01:54:16,058
I... wanted to know if I would be welcome.

2349
01:54:16,641 --> 01:54:18,018
She came as my ambassador.

2350
01:54:18,643 --> 01:54:19,895
Your ambassador?

2351
01:54:21,146 --> 01:54:23,273
I never imagined that that
was the language of diplomacy.

2352
01:54:24,399 --> 01:54:26,318
You know, she likes you
in spite of the language.

2353
01:54:26,735 --> 01:54:28,653
- Me?
- Yes, she really does.

2354
01:54:29,738 --> 01:54:32,532
I wish I had known it.
I wouldn't have been so rude.

2355
01:54:32,824 --> 01:54:33,909
But that was what she liked.

2356
01:54:34,326 --> 01:54:36,620
People flatter her so much,
she enjoys an occasional change.

2357
01:54:36,787 --> 01:54:38,872
Oh, I'm afraid I gave her
a good change this afternoon.

2358
01:54:39,039 --> 01:54:40,415
She went away delighted.

2359
01:54:41,500 --> 01:54:44,586
You evidently confirmed the good opinion
she'd formed of you at Rosings.

2360
01:54:45,003 --> 01:54:48,006
I don't know what to say or think.

2361
01:54:48,840 --> 01:54:51,551
Except that you must
allow me to thank you for

2362
01:54:52,302 --> 01:54:53,428
what you did for Lydia.

2363
01:54:54,221 --> 01:54:56,306
And if the facts were known
to the rest of my family,

2364
01:54:56,598 --> 01:54:59,559
I should not merely have
my own gratitude to express.

2365
01:54:59,893 --> 01:55:03,814
If you must thank me,
let it be for yourself alone.

2366
01:55:04,648 --> 01:55:06,608
Whatever I did,
I thought only of you.

2367
01:55:07,317 --> 01:55:08,610
Oh, Mr. Darcy.

2368
01:55:09,486 --> 01:55:11,363
When I think of how I've misjudged you,

2369
01:55:13,031 --> 01:55:15,367
the--the horrible things I said,

2370
01:55:16,368 --> 01:55:17,702
I'm so ashamed.

2371
01:55:18,078 --> 01:55:19,996
Oh, no, it's I who should be ashamed.

2372
01:55:20,622 --> 01:55:23,708
Of my arrogance.
Of my stupid pride.

2373
01:55:24,543 --> 01:55:27,587
Of all... except one thing.

2374
01:55:28,755 --> 01:55:29,714
One thing,

2375
01:55:31,049 --> 01:55:32,426
I'm not ashamed of having loved you.

2376
01:55:37,264 --> 01:55:38,181
Elizabeth,

2377
01:55:39,641 --> 01:55:40,892
dare I ask you again?

2378
01:55:48,692 --> 01:55:49,568
Elizabeth.

2379
01:55:51,486 --> 01:55:54,489
Dear, beautiful Lizzy.

2380
01:55:59,161 --> 01:56:02,038
Lord, bless my soul.

2381
01:56:02,873 --> 01:56:04,416
Mr. Bennet. Mr. Bennet.

2382
01:56:06,084 --> 01:56:08,420
Miracles will never cease,
Mrs. Bennet.

2383
01:56:08,587 --> 01:56:11,506
Mr. Darcy. Who would have believed it?

2384
01:56:11,965 --> 01:56:14,468
Oh, my sweetest, sweetest Lizzy.

2385
01:56:14,634 --> 01:56:17,596
What pin money she'll have.
What jewels. What carriages.

2386
01:56:17,762 --> 01:56:20,015
Jane's is nothing to it.
Absolutely nothing.

2387
01:56:20,182 --> 01:56:23,477
Oh, and such a charming man.

2388
01:56:24,144 --> 01:56:27,189
I do hope you overlook
my having disliked him so much.

2389
01:56:27,522 --> 01:56:30,108
